\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Indonesia's 2024 outlook: Thriving through transition\b0\par\par\uc2 986 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 January 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Andry Asmoro, Mandiri, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has once again proven to be a regional hotspot capable of dampening the effects of increased global volatility. In the last two years, it has been able to avoid a greater negative impact from rising risk coming from aggressive benchmark rate hikes for a longer period. It is worth noting that at the same time, Indonesian regulators have successfully balanced their policies between ensuring stability and supporting growth. Thus, we saw many positive macro and financial figures in the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and banking sector last year: (1) \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth that most likely ended the year at 5 percent, the fourth highest annual figure in Asia; (2) a low inflation rate of around 2.6 percent; (3) a stable rupiah, which ended the year at around 15,300 per US dollar and (4) loan growth, which may have reached 10 percent. These figures were very tough to maintain in the midst of much uncharted territory in the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .We noted several key success factors that drove Indonesia's positive performance last year: consistent, detailed and ahead-of-the-curve policies; persistent improvement in financial literacy and inclusive growth; downstreaming in several industries that supported Indonesia's current account balance, especially from the metal-mining sector; and persistent support to maintain consumer purchasing power. This \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  coordination boosted Indonesia's post-pandemic growth and made it competitive with other emerging markets.Now, entering the second week of 2024, how do we see the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  compared to last year? Can it optimize the momentum from the biggest and longest election in national history? Let's examine the major challenges we will face this year.We believe that Indonesia will face relatively balanced opportunities and risks this year. First, challenges will still come from slower Chinese and United States economies while at the same time \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will stay high, at least through the first half of the year.Currently, the domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has started feeling the impact. Despite the resilience shown in the first half, signs of moderating growth have been showing up in various leading indicators. Trade performance has deteriorated along with the correction in commodity prices. Consumption remains strong in some areas (i.e., mobility \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and recreation), yet retail sales have been pressured. Some of the export-oriented manufacturing sectors are affected by the large \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown, most of them coming from labor-intensive industries.On a positive note, Indonesia's strong domestic basis should still be able to cushion the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from the downturn. Although there are not many catalysts next year, national election \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  can provide somewhat of a boost to private consumption growth. The government has allocated Rp 76.6 trillion (US$4.93 billion) for 2023 and 2024, substantially higher than in past elections, given the larger election scale this time. Another upside catalyst lies in the timing of a global rate cut. The current market assumption is that a rate cut is most likely in the second half of next year. We expect a rebound in financial markets, as global sentiment should improve while other central banks may follow suit, including BI. A lower benchmark rate means lower cost of funds and cost of borrowing. At this point, the pivotal \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate from higher to lower trajectory will bring more demand for loans, especially consumer and capital loans. Combined with the expectation of \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  clarity post-election, these factors should be the buffer of 2024 growth in the midst of potential export and investment growth.Faster \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  is needed. Liquidity has been tighter lately, with the loan to deposit ratio (LDR) consistently increasing (currently at 84 percent) and M1 growth contracting for the first-time last year. Tighter liquidity could have many causes, such as lower corporate revenue and individual income in the midst of lower commodity prices. These phenomena were clearly reflected in deposit growth last year, which was below 1 percent year to date, the slowest growth in the last 6 years. Government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  acceleration can play a bigger role in cushioning the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by increasing the liquidity in the system. Last year, the realized 2023 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  was smaller than the government's initial target. The \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  was initially set at 2.8 percent of GDP (Rp 598.2 trillion) and it ended up at 1.65 percent of GDP (Rp 347.6 trillion). In our view, the government can support the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by maintaining a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of around 2 percent and accelerating it after the second quarter of every year. Government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the beginning of the year is even more necessary in 2024, when the private sector remains in "wait and see" mode and holds off on capital \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  (capex) expansion in the first half until there is clarity on the new government. In conclusion, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue to be a hotspot among emerging markets because of its fundamentals and \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  consistency. The risk of a global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown is, indeed, still looming large. On the domestic side, the election will, like it or not, lead to the postponement of expansion plans. In this situation, the government must push for faster \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , given the wider \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  space. The remaining national strategic projects need to be accelerated to cushion the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .However, despite all the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , there is always a light at the end of the tunnel. We estimate that global rate cuts will be a game changer for many emerging markets, including Indonesia. We estimate that this will happen in second half, preceded by the \uc2 Federal Reserve\uc2 . Global rate cuts should revive market sentiment and end the prolonged global slowdown cycle. At this juncture, we believe that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could stay at 5 percent growth this year and that it has greater opportunity to accelerate further next year.___________________Chief Economist of Bank Mandiri\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240109ek190000c\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
