\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Unlocking Indonesia's supply chain opportunity in energized SEA\b0\par\par\uc2 1,071 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 January 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Kazutoshi Tominaga and Hitesh Tak, \uc2 Boston Consulting Group (BCG)\uc2 ,\par \par \uc2 Leaders of multinational companies face unprecedented \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in shaping their supply chain strategies and reconfiguring their companies' network footprints in response to global geopolitical upheaval.\par \par \uc2 Dynamics between manufacturing powerhouse China and several major trading partners have accelerated preexisting production shifts. Technology and relative labor costs are changing.\par \par \uc2 COVID-19 demonstrated the need for more resilient supply chains, at a time when geopolitical tensions have created more complex considerations for global trade partners.\par \par \uc2 In addition, CEOs must assess how to establish an environmental, social and corporate governance (ESG)-compliant supply base, while identifying which geographical location will be the engine of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in coming years. These complex considerations are why over 90 percent of global manufacturers intend to redesign their supply footprints in the next five years according to a survey by \uc2 Boston Consulting Group\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Resilient companies are two times as likely to outperform non-resilient peers in long-term total shareholder return (TSR) performance. Whatis more, a successful footprint transformation can improve companies' resilience and sustainabilityandcut their global manufacturing and supply-chain costs by 20 to 50 percent.\par \par \uc2 Southeast Asia has emerged as an attractive location in this evolving landscape, as companies look to manage supply costs and mitigate risks. This provides a lucrative opportunity to explore manufacturing opportunities in markets such as Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 New manufacturing epicenter\par \par \uc2 Adding to this attractive proposition is the compelling cost-competitiveness of Southeast Asia's manufacturing landscape. \uc2 BCG\uc2 's proprietary Global Manufacturing Cost Comparison Model assesses that baseline manufacturing costs in Southeast Asia are now up to 15 percent lower than China,even before applying potential logistics and \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  costs,in a region boasting large volumes of skilled, low-cost labor.\par \par \uc2 Southeast Asia has already benefited from significant shifts away from China, with exports to the United States soaring by 65 percent from 2018 through 2022, while US goods imports from China declined by 10 percent.\par \par \uc2 Domestic consumption in Southeast Asia is projected to reach US$4 trillion by 2031. Rapid regional growth has also fashioned a large domestic market, with a GDP of $3.6 trillion in 2022, with the share of middle- and high-income households on track to reach 84 percent of households by 2031.\par \par \uc2 Regionally, ASEAN has implemented a range of supportive policies in recent years, with measures to enhance free flow of goods and services among member states. Expansion and modernization of ports has been complemented by investment in energy, transportationand digital infrastructure.\par \par \uc2 The ASEAN highway network, Singapore-Kunming rail project and Indonesia-Malaysia-Thailand Growth Triangle are all examples of this evolving ecosystem.These initiatives align with the wider \uc2 ASEAN \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Community\uc2  blueprint, which looks to embed a deeply integrated and mutually beneficial regional \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , with seamless movement of goods and people.\par \par \uc2 Major trade agreements such as the \uc2 Regional Comprehensive \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Partnership\uc2  (\uc2 RCEP\uc2 ) and Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership (CP-TPP) mean the region has competitive trade access with countries that together account for 40 percent or more of global GDP.\par \par \uc2 Globally, the value-add of Southeast Asia's manufacturing industry will double from $748 billion in 2022 to $1.4 trillion by 2028. The projected compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 11 percent puts Southeast Asia at the forefront of global manufacturing growth, outpacing competitors India (8.4 percent), China (3.6 percent), and Mexico (3.3 percent).\par \par \uc2 According to \uc2 BCG\uc2 's proprietary Global Trade Model, Southeast Asia's exports will grow by nearly 90 percent, reaching $3.2 trillion by 2031.\par \par \uc2 The region is poised to capture value from increasingly dynamic global manufacturing shifts, a landscape explored in detail in \uc2 BCG\uc2 's recent report Harnessing the Tectonic Shifts in Global Manufacturing.\par \par \uc2 RI offers fresh opportunities\par \par \uc2 Southeast Asia's manufacturing market is currently dominated by six key countries, with unique considerations as to the opportunities they present.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia, Malaysia, Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam boast diverse manufacturing opportunities across a broad range of industries.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia and Southeast Asia's manufacturing opportunity is on the rise, but companies must make careful strategic choices to unlock the greatest share of this value, assessing local benefits and challenges.\par \par \uc2 As Southeast Asia's largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , with high-growth fundamentals and an appealing demographic advantage, Indonesia is well poised to position itself as an attractive regional location. Indonesia's manufacturing \uc2 PMI\uc2  index is the highest amongASEAN peers according to analysis from August 2023, and only slightly below that of Asian leader India.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia boasts low productivity-adjusted manufacturing costs,15 percent lower than China. It has an attractive domestic market with a population of approximately 275 million people, a workforce of 145 million, and a consumer class demographic expected to increase by 75 million 2020-2030.\par \par \uc2 While boasting encouraging fundamentals, Indonesia is home to some unique challenges. Theseinclude developing infrastructure that limits inter- and intra-island trading networks, creating inflationary pressures on domestically produced goods.\par \par \uc2 Lagging sustainability credentials also create issues in a global marketplace increasingly worried about ESG concerns.\par \par \uc2 Companies need to reflect on the complexities of entering and operating to ensure a successful supply chain transition. They need to understand how global trade flows will evolve, and how this may shift competitive advantages over rivals.\par \par \uc2 Benchmarking costs across different countries and regions is also essential. This includes understanding the impact of key components such as regional differences in wage rates, labor productivity, operating overheads, tariffs, \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  etc. Even within individual countries, companies need to analyze the most attractive region or location based on availability of local talent, supply base, government incentives, infrastructure and more.\par \par \uc2 This is a vibrant, high growth but diverse region, creating complex competitive considerations. Companies must also prepare to navigate a fragmented business ecosystem heavily reliant on the power of relationships.\par \par \uc2 Southeast Asia and Indonesia remain compelling and attractive destinationsfor supply chain\par \par \uc2 relocation thanks to persistent geopolitical trends, regional \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures and a growing domestic market.\par \par \uc2 While the regional opportunity is ripe, understanding the local context is vital to realizing this opportunity. Those who tread this path successfully are poised to position themselves at an exciting new heart of global manufacturing potential.\par \par \uc2 Special thanks: The authors would like to thank Michael McAdoo (partner and director, Global Trade & Investment, \uc2 Boston Consulting Group\uc2 ) for contributing his insights to this article.\par \par \uc2 _____________________\par \par \uc2 Managing director and senior partner at \uc2 Boston Consulting Group\uc2  Managing director and partner at \uc2 Boston Consulting Group\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240109ek190000i\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Business\par \b \uc2 What Happens to Indonesia-US  \highlight22\uc2 Economic \highlight\uc2  Ties if Trump Wins\b0\par\par\uc2 603 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 January 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. An analyst recently gave some head-ups on the impact of \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s possible return to the White House on US-Indonesia \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ties.\par \par \uc2 Although Republicans have yet to choose their presidential nominee, Trump has been the front-runner. The businessman-turned-politician Trump is the top choice for 52 percent of Republicans and Republican-leaning registered voters for the party\u8217\'20\'19s presidential nomination in 2024, a report by think-tank \uc2 Pew Research Center\uc2  shows. It is likely that Trump will have a rematch with the incumbent \uc2 Joe Biden\uc2  in the upcoming election this November. If Trump wins, Indonesia needs to brace itself for some changes.\par \par \uc2 Muhammad Habib, an international relations researcher at the think-tank Center for Strategic and International Studies (\uc2 CSIS\uc2 ), told the Jakarta Globe on Tuesday that Indonesia-US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ties could face some changes, judging by Trump\u8217\'20\'19s past \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies as the president. In 2018, Trump announced that he would review the eligibility of countries enjoying the \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  reductions under the generalized system of preferences (GSP) system, including Indonesia, with which the US had trade deficits. The GSP, however, already expired in late 2020, and is now waiting for congressional renewal.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe are currently enjoying a surplus with the US. If Trump gets reelected, there could be a review of the trading instruments between Indonesia and the US. \u8230\'20\'26 And [the US] will likely have a stronger \u8216\'20\'18me-first \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19,\u8221\'20\'1D Habib told the Globe.\par \par \uc2 He also warned that the US-China tension could worsen if Trump returned to the White House. The substantial Chinese investment in Indonesia, particularly in the minerals sector, will likely spark concerns for a Trump-led US, according to Habib.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIndonesia has to be ready for a more \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  world, especially if Trump wins the election,\u8221\'20\'1D Habib said.\par \par \uc2 Nickel-rich Indonesia is trying to secure a critical mineral agreement with the US. If Indonesia can get this pact, electric vehicles (EVs) made from Indonesian batteries can enjoy the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  credits under the Inflation Reduction Act (IRA). However, the government only grants the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  credits if the batteries are made using minerals extracted or processed in the US or the country\u8217\'20\'19s free trade agreement partners. Indonesia today does not have a free trade agreement with the US.\par \par \uc2 There are two likely scenarios for the deal if Trump claims victory. The first scenario is that the deficits that the US suffers when trading with Indonesia can hamper the negotiations. The second scenario is that the negotiations will likely go more smoothly, as Trump does not pay much attention to environmental concerns as he once pulled the US out of the climate accord Paris Agreement, according to Habib.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CBut it depends on whether the critical mineral agreement is in the form of a law that needs to get ratified or it will be an executive order. It will likely be easier if it is an executive order. But if it is something that needs to get approved by the congress, Indonesia, of course, has to meet the standards,\u8221\'20\'1D Habib said.\par \par \uc2 An executive order requires no approval from the congress.\par \par \uc2 Government data shows Indonesia-US trade totaled $39.8 billion in 2022. Indonesia recorded a $16.6 billion surplus that year. In January-October 2023, bilateral trade reached $28.6 billion with a $9.8 billion surplus for Indonesia. China is Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s second-largest foreign investor in January-September 2023, investing approximately $5.6 billion over the said period. The US came in 5th place with $2.4 billion in foreign investments to Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020240110ek1a00006\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
