\par\par \b \uc2 RI sees fintech investments down by half in 2023: Report\b0\par\par\uc2 Ruth Dea Juwita, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 614 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 January 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Homegrown fintech start-ups faced a brutal year in 2023 after funding channeled to the industry plummeted 51 percent compared with the previous year, as investors moved with caution amid growing global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Indonesian fintech only saw US$765 million in funding last year, down from $1.6 billion in 2022, according to private data market research firm \uc2 Tracxn\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "Investors are still stepping cautiously because of the global macroeconomic slowdown and other geopolitical issues," the company said in its report Geo Annual Report: Indonesia FinTech 2023 on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 The contraction was evident across all funding stages last year with the seed stage nosediving 84 percent to $9.5 million, while early-stage funding plunged 79 percent to $99.4 million.\par \par \uc2 Late-stage deals appeared to be much more resilient with a decline of only 40 percent to $656 million from $1.1 billion the previous year.\par \par \uc2 The number of megadeals exceeding $100 million continued to dwindle to just three last year, from previously four in 2022 and six in 2021.\par \par \uc2 Buy now, pay later (BNPL) platform Kredivo, peer-to-peer (P2P) lending firm Investree and tech giant GoTo managed to secure the coveted eight-figure sums, \uc2 Tracxn\uc2  reported,but no new unicorns emerged from the sector last year.\par \par \uc2 Despite the downturn, some sub-segments within fintech still managed to attract sizable investments, namely alternative lending such as P2P lending and payments.\par \par \uc2 Alternative lending raised $554 million in 2023, a healthy 82 percent increase from $305 million in 2022.\par \par \uc2 Paymentplatformcompanies still booked $217 million, albeit with a 67 percent drop from\par \par \uc2 the $659 million raised the previous year.\par \par \uc2 Association of Indonesian Venture Capital and Start-ups (Amvesindo) chairman Eddi Danusaputro affirmed that fintech funding "slowed down" in the first half of last year, but gained traction in the last quarter of 2023.\par \par \uc2 Funding worth $312 million and $407 million was observed in the first and fourth quarter of 2023 respectively, as per the report.\par \par \uc2 However, the second and third quarter of the same year witnessed only $25.5 million and $21 million respectively.\par \par \uc2 "Fintech companies need to adjust to business models that bring in finance," warned Eddi during a briefing with the Indonesia Fintech Society (Ifsoc) on Dec. 29, 2023.\par \par \uc2 He said several factors had brought in the tech winter in Indonesia in 2024, including rising \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and elections, among many other issues.\par \par \uc2 Yet, he expressed positive sentiment in local venture capital (VC) activity, particularly fromstate-owned enterprises (SOEs), who were more likely to remain active than their regional, Western and Silicon Valley counterparts.\par \par \uc2 Local VC firms like East Ventures, Mandiri Capital Indonesia, BRI Ventures and AC Ventures topped the chart of the most active investors in the country's fintech society throughout 2023, according to the Tracxn report.\par \par \uc2 Notably, Mandiri Capital Indonesia was among the top investors at the seed stage, while East Ventures, BRI Ventures and AC Ventures were active players at the seed level.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia is expected to see a deceleration in its digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the coming years, in line with other emerging countries in the ASEAN region, as tech companies in the bloc face pressure to shift to profitability after years of focusing on growth.\par \par \uc2 The country's digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is projected to reach $109 billion in gross merchandise value (GMV) in 2025, according to the annual e-Conomy Southeast Asia report published Nov. 1, 2023, by tech giant \uc2 Google\uc2 , Singapore-based \uc2 Temasek\uc2  and the United States-based research firm \uc2 Bain & Company\uc2 . That figure was lower than the $130 billion projected for the same period in the previous year's report.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240111ek1b0000d\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
