\par\par \b \uc2 How \uc2 Belt and Road Initiative\uc2  can give impetus to development in Indonesia\b0\par\par\uc2 885 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 January 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Veronika S. Saraswati , Shanghai, China\par \par \uc2 The 10th anniversary of the \uc2 Belt and Road Initiative\uc2  (BRI) was commemorated amid rising geopolitical tensions. Despite the immense challenges ahead, the BRI has passed its first decade vigorously and looks to continue to move forward and fly with ambitious global efforts on an unprecedented scale.\par \par \uc2 Malicious labels such as "debt trap" have failed to hamper the rapid pace of progress of the initiative. The unrelenting vilification of the initiative has hardly slowed the BRI progress in infrastructure development.\par \par \uc2 Instead, many countries, developing and underdeveloped, have gained huge benefits, either pragmatic or long-term, from their involvement in the BRI platform.\par \par \uc2 As of June 2023, China had signed more than 200 agreements with 152 countries and 32 international organizations, including 10 member states of ASEAN, under the "Belt and Road framework".\par \par \uc2 Indonesia joined the BRI at its inception in 2017 and has greatly benefited from the joint construction of the BRI. The positive results of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and trade cooperation between the two countries have given Indonesia confidence that China is an opportunity rather than a risk.\par \par \uc2 Under the framework of the BRI, a number of infrastructure projects have been realized together by Chinese and Indonesian companies. The cooperation has transformed Indonesia's traditional industries into modern ones and increased national and regional revenues.\par \par \uc2 The operation of nickel smelters led by Chinese companies, for example, contributed US$1.12 trillion in \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue to Indonesia in 2022.\par \par \uc2 This huge amount was the first \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue obtained by the Indonesian government from its downstream projects in the mining sector.\par \par \uc2 In addition to \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues, the nickel downstream projects have created jobs for local people, hence supporting Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development.\par \par \uc2 Natural resources have been the main factor in Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development over a long period. This development method attaches importance to quantitative expansion and ignores the quality and efficiency of products, resulting in excessive consumption of resources and the inability to achieve sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social development.\par \par \uc2 In the post-pandemic era, the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has faced \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Indonesia needs innovation-driven development to cultivate new \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth centers, create high-quality products and accelerate the transformation of traditional development, which is driven by natural resources.\par \par \uc2 The BRI projects support the Indonesian government in realizing this transformation, in which infrastructure development is the primary condition.\par \par \uc2 The BRI projects inject a new impetus into the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Under the BRI scheme, China's foreign direct investment (FDI) in the country continues to increase.\par \par \uc2 According to the Investment Ministry, the FDI of Chinese enterprises in Indonesia was $8.23 billion in 2022, and China ranked as the second largest source of foreign investment in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 In 2022, the bilateral trade volume between the two countries reached $149.09 billion, up 19.8 percent year-on-year. China has been Indonesia's largest trading partner for 10 consecutive years and among Indonesia's top three sources of investment for many successive years.\par \par \uc2 The BRI cooperation in Indonesia took shape in large-scale infrastructure projects, such as the Jakarta-Bandung high-speed train, power plants, highways, ports and digital infrastructure.\par \par \uc2 Indeed, \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and trade are the best peripheral diplomatic tools to develop China-Indonesia relations.\par \par \uc2 A positive achievement in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and trade sectors has therefore convinced Indonesia to continue its involvement in the BRI projects.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's industrial structure today is still improving at a relatively sluggish rate compared to that in developed countries. To boost its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  even further and more efficiently, Indonesia needs more BRI support in the form of technologies to develop industries that require a lot of capital and technology to produce goods with high added value.\par \par \uc2 To meet the need for improvement and acceleration of this industrial structure, Indonesia needs China as a capable partner. Indonesia can benefit from China's expertise to strengthen its industrial structure, which serves as a strong basis for development.\par \par \uc2 In theory, the reciprocal advantages in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sphere will enhance collaboration and resolve political and cultural tensions. In this case, under the BRI scheme, China and Indonesia enjoy huge reciprocal advantages.\par \par \uc2 Both Indonesia and China are rich in local wisdom that can be a source of value for knowledge-based \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development that supports people's lives. Differences should not loosen or even eliminate partnerships.\par \par \uc2 Therefore dialogue is th