\par\par \uc2 BUSSINESS\par \b \uc2 2023 TRADE SURPLUS POINTS TO RESILIENCE: MINISTRY\b0\par\par\uc2 468 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 January 2024\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Yuni Arisandy Sinaga\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - Head of the Finance Ministry\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Agency (BKF), Febrio Kacaribu, on Tuesday said that the 2023 trade balance surplus reflects the resilience of Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  amid a global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CAlthough it recorded a decrease compared to 2022, the 2023 balance of trade showed the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s external resilience amid (a) global risks increase, including the moderation of commodity prices and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown of our main trading partner countries, such as China,\u8221\'20\'1D he expounded here.\par \par \uc2 In total, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s trade balance recorded a surplus of US$36.93 billion in 2023.\par \par \uc2 The value of Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s exports was recorded at US$258.82 billion, lower than the previous year\u8217\'20\'19s achievement of US$290.90billion.\par \par \uc2 Despite a nominal decline in exports, in terms of volume, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s exports were up 8.55 percent year-on-year (yoy) in 2023. The dip in the value of exports was in line with the moderation of prices for Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s top commodities, such as palm oil and coal.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown in its main trading partner countries also played a role in Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s export value slowdown.\par \par \uc2 In 2023, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s exports were still concentrated in China (25.66 percent), the United States (9.57 percent), and India (8.35 percent).\par \par \uc2 The share of Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s exports to ASEAN and the \uc2 European Union\uc2  stood at 18.35 percent and 6.78 percent, respectively, of the total exports.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s imports in 2023 reached US$221.89 billion, a decline of 6.55 percent yoy compared to 2022.\par \par \uc2 The largest contributor to the slowdown in imports were machinery/electrical equipment and their parts, while machinery/mechanical equipment and their parts contributed to the increase in imports.\par \par \uc2 Similar to exports, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s import volume recorded a positive growth of 8.04 percent yoy, in keeping with strong domestic demand.\par \par \uc2 Sector-wise, the imports of capital goods and consumer goods clocked positive growth, while imports of raw materials experienced a decline.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s biggest imports were still from China and Japan, with a respective share of 33.42 percent and 8.84 percent of the total imports.\par \par \uc2 According to Kacaribu, global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities are still facing risks and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2024, as reflected in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth slowdown forecast by many international institutions, followed by a moderation in commodity prices.\par \par \uc2 This will directly impact Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s trade activities this year.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe government will monitor the impacts of a global (\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) slowdown on national exports, as well as prepare anticipatory measures through promoting the sustainability of downstream natural resources, increasing the competitiveness of national export products, and diversifying main trading partner countries,\u8221\'20\'1D Kacaribu informed.\par \par \uc2 (T.Y012/A/A063/A063) 16-01-2024 18:24:24\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020240116ek1g0015p\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Business\par \b \uc2 ASEAN+3\u8217\'20\'19s  \highlight22\uc2 Economy \highlight\uc2  to Grow 4.5 Pct This Year: Report\b0\par\par\uc2 374 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 January 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. ASEAN+3 region\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is set to expand by 4.5 percent in 2024 with Indonesia possibly witnessing a 5.2 percent growth this year, according to a report.\par \par \uc2 The ASEAN+3 Macroeconomic Research Office (AMRO) recently published its quarterly update of the regional \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook. The ASEAN+3 encompasses all 10 of the bloc\u8217\'20\'19s member states, while also including China, Hong Kong, Japan, and Korea.\par \par \uc2 The January report shows that AMRO decided to maintain its 4.5 percent outlook for ASEAN+3. AMRO attributes the growth to improving external demand amid resilient domestic demand. Tourism rebounds to pre-pandemic levels, coupled with the gradual recovery of China\u8217\'20\'19s property sector, will also spur regional growth.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CNevertheless, the moderation of growth in the US and the euro area is likely to limit the extent of the improvement in regional exports. Regional exporters\u8217\'20\'19 subdued optimism on future orders as reflected in recent purchasing managers\u8217\'20\'19 index surveys highlights the continued \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  surrounding the outlook for trade,\u8221\'20\'1D the AMRO report reads.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s gross domestic product (GDP) is set to grow at 5.2 percent this year, much higher than some of its ASEAN counterparts but still less than Cambodia, Vietnam, and the Philippines. Vietnam\u8217\'20\'19s GDP is projected to grow at 6 percent, while Cambodia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will expand at 6.2 percent. The Philippines is forecast to be the fastest-growing ASEAN \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2024 as the AMRO predicted a 6.3 percent growth.\par \par \uc2 The 2023 GDP growth for ASEAN+3 is expected to stand at 4.4 percent. Indonesia is forecast to expand by 5 percent in 2023.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  earlier this week revealed its national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  put Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s GDP growth outlook to range between 4.7 percent and 5.5 percent for 2024.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CAs for 2023, we [Indonesia] will likely see an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of between 4.5 and 5.3 percent, underpinned by consumption and investment. Substantial government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the end of the year, coupled with the acceleration of the national strategic projects, are also the drivers,\u8221\'20\'1D \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  governor \uc2 Perry Warjiyo\uc2  said Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020240119ek1j0000a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
