\par\par \uc2 BUSSINESS\par \b \uc2 GREEN  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMY \highlight\uc2  A FOUNDATION FOR SUSTAINABLE GROWTH\b0\par\par\uc2 1,194 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 January 2024\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Azis Kurmala\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - In 2022, the \uc2 National Development Planning Ministry\uc2  (\uc2 Bappenas\uc2 ) unveiled the Indonesian GEI (Green \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Index), themed "Towards Implementation and Beyond: Measuring the Progress of Low Carbon and Green \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," during the Third G20 DWG Meeting side event in Bali.\par \par \uc2 The ministry launched the index in partnership with the United Kingdom"s Foreign Commonwealth and Development Office, Germany"s Federal Ministry for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs and Climate Action, WRI Indonesia, international development agency GIZ, Low Carbon Development Initiative (LCDI), \uc2 Global Green Growth Institute (GGGI)\uc2 , and the United Nations Partnership for Action on Green \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  (PAGE).\par \par \uc2 The 15 indicators that make up the Indonesian GEI and indicate green \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development are divided into three pillars: environmental, social, and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Emission intensity, energy intensity, and gross national income (GNI) per capita are the six measures that make up the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  pillar.\par \par \uc2 The four variables that make up the social pillar are life expectancy, unemployment, poverty, and average length of schooling. Meanwhile, five indicators make up the environmental pillar: controlled waste, renewable energy, reduced emissions, degraded peatlands, and land cover.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia"s national development plans, including the Medium-Term National Development Plan (RPJMN) 2025\u8211\'20\'132029 and the Long-Term National Development Plan (RPJPN) 2025\u8211\'20\'132045, have incorporated into the Indonesian GEI.\par \par \uc2 Through the implementation of the GEI, the nation"s annual \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is predicted to reach 6.1\u8211\'20\'136.5 percent by 2050.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, by 2045, emission intensity is expected to drop by as much as 68 percent, and by 2030, 1.8 million new green jobs are likely to be created.\par \par \uc2 The green \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is one of six \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  transformation strategies formulated by the \uc2 Bappenas\uc2  to achieve Indonesia"s 2045 vision.\par \par \uc2 The strategy is considered a game changer for Indonesia in the post-Covid-19 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery period and in its steps toward achieving sustainable development\par \par \uc2 The implementation of the green \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not an obstacle, but a new opportunity for future \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, according to deputy for \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the \uc2 Ministry of National Development Planning\uc2 , Amalia Adiningrat Widyasanti.\par \par \uc2 Once people implement green \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  massively and thoroughly, it will definitely create a new opportunity for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities in Indonesia, contributing to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth acceleration, she explained.\par \par \uc2 Widyasanti made the statement at the launch of the \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Brief of Greenpeace Indonesia and CELIOS: The Fate of the Green \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Transition in the Political Year.\par \par \uc2 She informed that in the national long-term plan for 2025\u8211\'20\'132045, the transition to a green \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  involves several main focuses.\par \par \uc2 The first focus is transitioning toward clean and renewable energy, with the renewable energy mix targeted to reach around 60 percent by 2045.\par \par \uc2 Second, implementing environmentally friendly transportation, or green transportation. Third, applying a circular \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  approach in industries and people"s daily lives.\par \par \uc2 The implementation of the green \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be the main focus of the Golden Indonesia vision, starting from 2025 to 2045, and will be an integral part of Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  transformation efforts, she said.\par \par \uc2 Regarding the challenges, she emphasized the need to make the necessary preparations, including increasing human resources, adopting clean technology, and expanding the supporting ecosystem through policies and regulations that support the green \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in various sectors.\par \par \uc2 Implementing a green \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  requires major changes that must be supported by a good ecosystem and joint efforts to achieve sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the next 20 years, she said.\par \par \uc2 Several policies, such as increasing energy efficiency, a just energy transition, developing smart grids, and implementing a circular \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , are considered the basis for those changes.\par \par \uc2 Widyasanti also emphasized the importance of providing \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and non-\b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives for environmentally friendly products.\par \par \uc2 She added that the green \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  push is not only limited to the energy transition, but also extends to strengthening other pillars to ensure sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the next two decades.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, Indonesia is strengthening its commitment to embrace the green \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a foundation for future \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, she continued.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2  said that state expenditures in the 2024 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  (APBN) will be used to support the acceleration of the green \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 State \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2024 will also be directed toward completing priority infrastructure to accelerate the green \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  transformation and support bureaucratic and state apparatus reform, Indrawati informed.\par \par \uc2 She pointed out that the size of the state \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  allocation in the 2024 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is Rp3,325.1 trillion, or 8.6 percent higher compared to the 2023 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The APBN will make utmost efforts to fulfill all national development priority programs, starting from protecting the people, including vulnerable groups, restoring the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , encouraging transformation, and developing all corners of the region, to improving defense and security.\par \par \uc2 These efforts will be carried out while maintaining the APBN as an instrument whose health, sustainability, and credibility must be maintained.\par \par \uc2 In this way, the APBN \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  can continue to be effective in maintaining the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and protecting the Indonesian people, she affirmed.\par \par \uc2 The 2024 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  was prepared assuming optimistic macro indicators, but with due attention to the rapidly changing dynamics.\par \par \uc2 The basic macro assumptions for the 2024 APBN comprise \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 5.2 percent, controlled inflation of 2.8 percent, rupiah exchange rate of Rp15 thousand per US dollar, interest rate on 10-year Government Securities (SBN) of 6.7 percent, Indonesian Crude Price (ICP)of82 US dollars per barrel, as well as oil lifting of 635 thousand barrels per day and gas lifting of 1.033 million barrels of oil equivalent per day.\par \par \uc2 Assumptions for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators in 2024 will, of course, still be influenced by global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  developments. Therefore, to maintain the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , it is vital to also maintain the health of the APBN, she said.\par \par \uc2 In managing the State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the minister emphasized the quality of \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , synergy, and harmonization of the State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Regional Budgets (APBD), as well as anticipating \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  that will continue to arise through \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  prioritization, thereby necessitating automatic adjustment.\par \par \uc2 In addition, Coordinating Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs, \uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2 , said that the State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  will also prioritize projects that seek to overcome climate change and encourage climate-friendly activities.\par \par \uc2 To ensure this, the government is implementing a Climate \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  Tagging mechanism at the national and regional levels to track climate change \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  allocations as well as present data on activities and results.\par \par \uc2 Further, Indonesia has increased its Nationally Determined Contribution (NDC) emission reduction commitment from 29 percent to 31.89 percent through its own efforts, and from 41 percent to 43.20 percent with international assistance by 2030.\par \par \uc2 The Enhanced NDC is aligned with the Long-Term Low Carbon and Climate Resilience Strategy 2050 and the vision to achieve net zero emissions by 2060.\par \par \uc2 According to the UN Environment Program, the notion of a green \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  does not replace sustainable development, but creates a new focus on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , investment, capital and infrastructure, employment and skills, and positive social and environmental outcomes.\par \par \uc2 Thus, the green \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  provides a macroeconomic approach to sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth with a central focus on investments, employment, and skills.\par \par \uc2 (T.A063/B/A043/A043) 22-01-2024 20:33:53\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020240122ek1m0018h\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 News\par \b \uc2 President's Office Pushes Back Against Claims of Food Estate Program Failure\b0\par\par\uc2 436 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 January 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. Presidential Staff Office Coordinator Ari Dwipayana has refuted statements made by vice-presidential candidates Mohammad Mahfud MD and Muhaimin Iskandar, who labeled the government's food estate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a failed program.\par \par \uc2 "This food estate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is a responsive step to the situation we are facing. We realize that the current world \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions are experiencing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Ari said on Monday.\par \par \uc2 He stressed that post-Covid-19 pandemic, many countries worldwide are struggling to meet the food needs of their citizens, leading to global food price instability. "This includes a significant increase in food prices in the world market," he added.\par \par \uc2 Ari explained that to respond to this situation, the Indonesian government has taken significant steps by implementing the food estate program. This program has been carried out since 2021 in Humbang Hasundutan, Tapanuli Selatan, Tapanuli Utara, and Pakpak Bharat in North Sumatra, covering an area of 30,000 hectares for cultivating potatoes, shallots, and garlic.\par \par \uc2 "President \uc2 Joko Widodo\uc2  encourages the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of a food reserve in response to the pandemic's impact and the emerging food crisis," said Ari Dwipayana.\par \par \uc2 The goal of this \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is to create a production that can serve as a government food reserve, allowing Indonesia to be self-sufficient in food without depending on imports from other countries, especially when global food prices significantly increase.\par \par \uc2 Ari emphasized that the implementation of this program is continually being evaluated for improvements to ensure the expected achievements are realized.\par \par \uc2 "Yes, it is continuously evaluated because the implementation involves several complex aspects and requires refinements," he concluded.\par \par \uc2 VP candidate Muhaimin Iskandar argued that the food estate program has proven to be a big failure, causing ecological damages and minimal impact, if any, on national food security efforts.\par \par \uc2 "In the past 10 years, the food estate program has marginalized our farmers and indigenous people, triggered agrarian conflicts, and caused ecological disasters," Muhaimin said in his opening remarks at the fourth presidential debate of the 2024 Presidential Election in Jakarta on Sunday.\par \par \uc2 Mahfud, the Coordinating Minister for Political, Legal, and Security Affairs, also criticized the food estate program in the debate. Despite this, after the debate, he reiterated his commitment to continuing President \uc2 Joko Widodo\uc2 's ongoing initiatives in the post-debate press conference.\par \par \uc2 In 2010, ex-President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono (SBY) brought back a food security program called Merauke Integrated Food and Energy Estate (MIFEE) in Papua. The goal was to open 1.2 million hectares of farmland, but the MIFEE project faced delays and only succeeded in cultivating 100 hectares.\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020240122ek1m00008\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
