\par\par \uc2 BUSSINESS\par \b \uc2 BAPPENAS\uc2  PROJECTS INDONESIA'S  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMY \highlight\uc2  TO GROW STRONGER IN 2024\b0\par\par\uc2 331 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 February 2024\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - The Ministry of National Development Planning/National Development Planning Agency (Bappenas) projected that Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2024 would grow better than in 2023 despite the trend of slowdown in the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "Several international agencies have stated that Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , amidst the ongoing global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown, is projected to grow stronger than in 2023," the ministry"s Deputy of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs, Amalia Adininggar Widyasanti, stated during the 2023 Indonesia \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Report"s launch agenda here, Wednesday (January 31).\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian government targets the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2024 to grow by 5.3 percent, higher than the 2023 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth projection set at 5.1 percent.\par \par \uc2 She affirmed that Indonesia has a solid foundation to develop a stronger \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2024 despite \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  looming over the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and its divergence that is expected to continue in the upcoming years.\par \par \uc2 The official pointed out that the \uc2 Organisation for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation and Development\uc2  (\uc2 OECD\uc2 ) also forecast Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2024 to grow better than last year.\par \par \uc2 "This is a positive sign that the global community believed that Indonesia can recover and maintain its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the five-percent range, returning to the pre-COVID-19 pandemic growth level," Amalia noted.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Governor of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2 Perry Warjiyo\uc2  highlighted the need to remain vigilant while being optimistic in 2024 as well as to enhance synergy between \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies and efforts to strengthen national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  resilience in 2024.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  projected Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2024 to grow by 4.7 to 5.5 percent, provided that internal and external \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability are preserved.\par \par \uc2 Warjiyo is also optimistic that inflation would be manageable to the expected target of 2.5 percent, give or take one percent; banking credit would grow by 10-12 percent; and the exchange rate of the rupiah would improve in 2024.\par \par \uc2 (T.N015/B/A063/A063) 01-02-2024 12:03:37\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020240201ek2100001\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Business\par \b \uc2 Why a One-Round Election Appeals to Indonesia's  \highlight22\uc2 Economic \highlight\uc2  Minds\b0\par\par\uc2 975 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 February 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. As Indonesia eagerly anticipates the 2024 Presidential Election on Feb. 14, 2024, the potential for a single or dual-round election looms. Regardless of the outcome\u8212\'20\'14\uc2 Anies Baswedan\uc2 , \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2 , or Ganjar Pranowo\u8212\'20\'14business leaders, economists, and investors express a preference for a single-round election.\par \par \uc2 Shinta Widjaja Kamdani, Chairwoman of the Indonesian Employers' Association (Apindo), said business leaders and potential investors are eagerly awaiting the outcome of the 2024 Presidential Election, as it will determine the future direction of business activities.\par \par \uc2 "The inclination of business leaders and potential investors, especially in the real sector, will wait and see before deciding on business expansions. They are awaiting the election results before making decisions," she said in a recent interview with Beritasatu.com, a sister publication of the Jakarta Globe.\par \par \uc2 A single-round election requires a candidate pair to secure more than 50 percent of the total votes, with at least 20 percent of the votes in each province spread across more than half of Indonesia's provinces.\par \par \uc2 The Permanent Voters List (DPT) for the 2024 Election, as established by the \uc2 General Election Commission (KPU)\uc2 , includes a staggering 204,807,222 eligible voters. To win in a single-round election, one presidential and vice-presidential pair must garner support from 102.5 million voters.\par \par \uc2 In the event of a two-round election, the \uc2 KPU\uc2  would initiate a second campaign period for the two candidates who qualify for the runoff, spanning from June 2 to June 22, 2024. The second round of voting is scheduled for June 26, 2024.\par \par \uc2 Minister of Investment/Head of the \uc2 Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM)\uc2 Bahlil Lahadalia\uc2  said a single-round election would provide investment certainty more swiftly.\par \par \uc2 "The investment impact is very good if it's a single-round election to provide certainty about who will be elected," he said.\par \par \uc2 Bahlil downplayed concerns about which candidate pair would emerge victorious, emphasizing that a single-round election has several positive effects, particularly in creating a conducive investment climate.\par \par \uc2 "It doesn't matter who wins; what matters is that we have certainty from the beginning. This way, we can plan strategic steps to attract investment because otherwise, it will create \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  that can slow down the process," he added.\par \par \uc2 Senior economist Raden Pardede also highlighted the benefits of a single-round election, providing faster certainty to investors. A single-round election would reduce the waiting period (wait and see) by approximately four months.\par \par \uc2 "If it's two rounds, it won't be finished until June. So, the wait-and-see period of about four months can be reduced. This waiting period is a period of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , both in the capital market, financial markets, and the business world that wants to make investments," explained Raden.\par \par \uc2 Raden also emphasized the substantial \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  savings that could be achieved if the 2024 Election is a single-round event. This \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  could be redirected by the government for other productive purposes.\par \par \uc2 "This \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  can be used for other government programs, given that the current administration has nine months remaining, and there are still unfinished programs," he revealed.\par \par \uc2 The Ministry of Finance has allocated a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp 71.3 trillion ($4.5 billion) for the 2024 Election, making it the largest in the post-reform era and nearly three times the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the 2019 Election, which amounted to Rp 25.59 trillion.\par \par \uc2 Who Will Win in a One-round Election?\par \par \uc2 Several survey institutions released the electability results of presidential and vice-presidential pairs for the 2024 Election in January 2024. The findings showed that presidential candidate \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  and Gibran Rakabuming Raka, surpassed the other two candidates, Anies Baswedan-Muhaimin Iskandar and Ganjar Pranowo-Mahfud MD.\par \par \uc2 Indikator Politik Indonesia's survey conducted from Jan. 10-16, 2024, revealed that Pair 2, Prabowo-Gibran, had an electability of 48.55 percent, surpassing Anies-Muhaimin at 24.17 percent and Ganjar-Mahfud at 21.6 percent. Approximately 5.68 percent of respondents expressed \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  or did not respond.\par \par \uc2 Similarly, a survey by Lingkaran Survei Indonesia (LSI) Denny Januar Ali (JA) from Jan. 16-26, 2024, positioned Prabowo-Gibran ahead of Anies-Muhaimin and Ganjar-Mahfud.\par \par \uc2 Prabowo-Gibran's electability even exceeded the requirement for winning in a single round, reaching 50.7 percent. Meanwhile, Ganjar-Mahfud had 19.7 percent, and Anies-Muhaimin had 22 percent.\par \par \uc2 "We see the opportunity for a single round from the consistent increase in Prabowo's popularity. In the last month, they have consistently experienced a 5-7 percent increase. If this increase is maintained, then the opportunity for a single round is very likely," said LSI Denny JA senior researcher Adjie Alfaraby during the survey release at the LSI Denny JA office in Rawamangun, East Jakarta, on Tuesday, Jan. 30, 2024.\par \par \uc2 LSI Denny JA's survey of 1,200 respondents also found that 84% of the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  desires the 2024 Election to be held in a single round.\par \par \uc2 Political observer Ujang Komarudin from Al Azhar University Indonesia underscores the critical nature of the last two weeks preceding the 2024 Election, emphasizing it as a crucial period for candidates to garner votes before the polling day on February 14, 2024. Consequently, the upcoming fifth debate on Sunday stands as a pivotal event that candidates cannot afford to ignore.\par \par \uc2 "In my opinion, the debate will influence \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  opinion, including influencing the preferences of voters, especially those who are still undecided or have not made a choice," said Ujang to Beritasatu.com on Saturday, Jan. 27, 2024.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 KPU\uc2  has determined the theme for the fifth debate, covering social welfare, culture, education, information technology, health, employment, human resources, and inclusion. Ujang hopes that this final debate will focus more on the exchange of ideas and programs than personal attacks, as seen in previous debates.\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020240204ek2400008\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
