\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Indonesia's  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2 : Growth, challenges and the road ahead\b0\par\par\uc2 845 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 February 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Dian Ayu Yustina, Mandiri, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Early this week, the statistics office released GDP figures for the fourth quarter of 2023. Despite a turbulent global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  landscape marked by slowing growth, rising inflation and geopolitical tensions, Indonesia delivered a solid performance in 2023.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the fourth quarter remained robust at 5.04 percent, driven by stable consumption, investment and faster government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  realization. Election \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  also contributed to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, reflected in the faster growth of nonpro-fit institutions. The full year of 2023 saw growth of 5.05 percent, a slight moderation compared to the previous year.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, one of the highest of its peers, was primarily driven by stable consumption, amid rising inflation and faster investment growth amid decelerating export growth. The resilient growth was accompanied by relatively stable macro-indicators and sound external balance conditions.\par \par \uc2 The inflation rate, which peaked at 5.95 percent during the fuel price hike period, dropped to 2.6 percent by the end of 2023. \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's substantial interest rate hikes successfully curbed inflation, supporting the stable consumption.\par \par \uc2 Household consumption grew by 4.8 percent, only slightly lower than in 2022 at 4.94 percent. The growth of government consumption also recovered slightly, though disbursement mainly took place in the fourth quarter.\par \par \uc2 On a positive note, the government was able to achieve significant \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  reduction, from 5 percent during the pandemic to minus 1.65 percent of GDP, indicating healthy \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  finances.\par \par \uc2 However, challenges remain. Slowing global demand and normalizing commodity prices led to a lower trade surplus and a diminishing current account surplus. The current account surplus this year is expected to narrow, possibly even recording a small \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Further, market volatility, which occurred regularly in 2023, resulted in financial market and currency fluctuations, reflected in the balance of payments' financial accounts.\par \par \uc2 The declining balance of payments condition was also reflected in the liquidity in the system, which became another challenge. A narrower trade surplus meant lower foreign exchange liquidity in the market, further impacted by trade surpluses parked overseas.\par \par \uc2 The normalizing \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  led to tighter conditions, with deposit growth slowing significantly from 9 percent in 2022 to 3.7 percent in 2023. Meanwhile, credit growth remained strong at 10.3 percent by year-end, resulting in a higher loan-to-deposit ratio of 84 percent.\par \par \uc2 This year, these challenges continue to pose significant risks to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2024. The global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown is expected to continue, particularly in major countries like the United States, China and the \uc2 European Union\uc2 . While the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is outperforming expectations and may avoid recession, China's slowdown raises significant concerns.\par \par \uc2 China's demographic issues, with a slowing and declining productive population and overinvestment in the property sector, are contributing to its fundamental slowdown.\par \par \uc2 This will impact the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including Indonesia, as China remains its largest trading partner. Escalating geopolitical risks, such as the war in the Middle East, conflicts in the Red Sea and upcoming elections in several countries, add further \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The relationship among China, Taiwan and the US is particularly concerning, as election results could trigger tensions.\par \par \uc2 However, despite the somewhat gloomy global outlook, there are potential silver linings. An improving inflation outlook in the US may open the possibility of a rate cut later this year, boosting \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  optimism and sentiment, ultimately leading to faster \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. For Indonesia, domestic factors, particularly the upcoming national election, also present both positive and negative impacts. Past elections have shown that election \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  can stimulate private consumption, but it can also lead to moderation in investment and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity due to increased \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  during the period of government transition.\par \par \uc2 Despite these challenges, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to perform well, albeit with the risk of a moderating pace of growth. Household consumption and election \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  of nonprofit institutions will remain the main driver. Therefore, maintaining low inflation is key to preserving consumers' purchasing power.\par \par \uc2 The global slowdown of the main trading partners may impact the trade surplus and foreign investment, which necessitates government intervention with policies or \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  to cushion the blow. Faster \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , even in an election year, is necessary. The government can expedite \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  or \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives on top of the faster \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the unfinished national strategic projects and the development of the new capital city.\par \par \uc2 Policies supporting liquidity are also critical. Adequate liquidity will allow for faster credit growth. Finally, focusing on labor-intensive sectors like manufacturing and agriculture can further boost \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, as the manufacturing sector remains the largest contributor to Indonesia's GDP.\par \par \uc2 This year, \uc2 Bank Mandiri\uc2  will hold the Mandiri Investment Forum on March 5, which will mainly discuss the global risks and their impact on the macroeconomic outlook, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and investment opportunities this year.\par \par \uc2 For Indonesia, discussion on the outlook and strategy for potential sectors such as manufacturing and agriculture sector will be important and will be key to accelerating growth going forward.\par \par \uc2 ____________________\par \par \uc2 Senior economist \uc2 Bank Mandiri\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240206ek270000c\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
