\par\par \b \uc2 Car sales plummet 26 percent year-on-year in January\b0\par\par\uc2 Yohana Belinda , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 467 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 February 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Domestic car sales have plummeted in what automotive industry representatives attribute to a drop in demand on the back of weaker \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sentiment.\par \par \uc2 According to the Association of Indonesian Automotive Manufacturers (Gaikindo), wholesalers sold 69,619 cars nationwide last month, marking a 26 percent decline from the 94,270 units sold in January 2023.\par \par \uc2 Retail sales also declined strongly, dropping by 13.9 percent from 90,892 cars sold in January 2023 to 78,214 in January 2024.\par \par \uc2 Gaikindo chairman Jongkie Sugiarto said the poor car sales were related to Indonesia's slower \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and suggested that \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook was making consumers think twice before making large purchases.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's GDP growth fell to 5.05 percent last year, Statistics Indonesia (BPS) reported last week. That marks a slowdown from the growth rate of 5.31 percent logged in 2022, when the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was bouncing back from the slowdown caused by the coronavirus pandemic in 2021.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 Toyota\uc2  brand continues to dominate Indonesia's car market despite seeing its wholesale sales fall almost 28 percent to 20,988 vehicles in January 2024 from 28,970 a year earlier.\par \par \uc2 Toyota\uc2  is the world's biggest carmaker in terms of global unit sales.\par \par \uc2 Wholesale sales of \uc2 Toyota\uc2 -controlled \uc2 Daihatsu\uc2 , meanwhile, dropped 21 percent year-on-year (yoy) to 14,363 units in January 2024 from 18,194 units in January 2023.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, \uc2 Honda\uc2  automobile sales plunged 46.68 percent yoy. \uc2 Honda\uc2  sold 8,413 vehicles in January of this year, which compares to 15,781 units sold in January of 2023.\par \par \uc2 Gaikindo has set a target for 1.1 million cars to be sold nationwide in 2024, raising the bar from last year's missed target of 1.05 million units.\par \par \uc2 Coordinating \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister \uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2  said the decline in car sales was due to disruptions in mobility caused by the COVID-19 outbreak.\par \par \uc2 "First, there was COVID-19, so [\b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 ] mobility was disrupted. Now, it is already going back to the pre-COVID-19 [level], and there is a spike in auto exports, which exceeded 400,000," Airlangga told reporters on Feb. 5.\par \par \uc2 The minister expressed optimism that car sales in Indonesia would reach the targeted 1.1 million units this year and added that electric vehicles were expected to account for 15 to 18 percent of the total.\par \par \uc2 According to Gaikindo figures, 1,005,802 million cars were sold from factories to dealers nationwide in 2023. That wholesale number marks a 4 percent decline from the 2022 figure of 1,048,040 units.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, retail sales (from dealers to consumers) throughout 2023 reached 998,059 units, down 1.5 percent from 1,013,582 units in 2022.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240212ek2d0000b\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Business\par \b \uc2 Indonesia's Foreign Debt Rises 2.7% to $407.1 Billion\b0\par\par\uc2 533 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 February 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. Indonesia's foreign debt (ULN) hit $407.1 billion (Rp 6,364 trillion) in the fourth quarter of 2023, marking a 2.7 percent increase compared to the same period last year.\par \par \uc2 According to \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2 , the increase is attributed to \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector transactions funded by foreign debt. Additionally, the increase in foreign debt position was impacted by the depreciation of the greenback against the majority of global currencies, including the rupiah.\par \par \uc2 Erwin Haryono, the Head of the Communication Department at the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , announced on Thursday that the government's foreign debt position at the end of the fourth quarter of 2023 stood at $196.6 billion, reflecting a 5.4 percent year-on-year (YoY) increase. This marks an acceleration from the 3.3 percent YoY growth witnessed in the previous quarter.\par \par \uc2 The increase in government foreign debt is also influenced by an increase in portfolio investment placements in domestic and international government securities markets, following positive market sentiment and the easing of global financial market \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Most of the foreign debt is directed towards supporting government efforts in financing productive sectors and priority expenditures.\par \par \uc2 This financing support includes, among others, the health and social services sector (23.7 percent of total government foreign debt), government administration, defense, and mandatory social security (18.9 percent), education services (16.6 percent), construction (14.1 percent), and financial and insurance services (9.7 percent).\par \par \uc2 "The government's foreign debt position is relatively safe and controlled, as almost all of it has a long-term tenure, accounting for 99.8 percent of the total," Erwin added.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, private foreign debt remains under control and continues its contraction in growth. Private foreign debt at the end of Q4-2023 recorded $197.0 billion, experiencing a contraction of 1.9 percent YoY, continuing the contraction seen in Q2-2023 by 3.5 percent YoY.\par \par \uc2 The contraction comes from financial corporations and non-financial corporations, each experiencing a contraction of 2.4 percent YoY and 1.8 percent YoY, respectively.\par \par \uc2 In terms of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sectors, the primary contributors to private foreign debt are the processing industry, financial and insurance services, the supply of electricity, gas, steam/hot water, and air conditioning, as well as mining and quarrying, collectively constituting 78.7 percent of the total private foreign debt. Additionally, private foreign debt is predominantly composed of long-term debt, making up 74.9 percent of the total private foreign debt.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's foreign debt structure remains healthy, supported by the application of prudential principles in its management. This is reflected in Indonesia's foreign debt ratio to gross domestic product (GDP) at 29.7 percent, and it is dominated by long-term foreign debt, accounting for 86.6 percent of total foreign debt.\par \par \uc2 To maintain a healthy structure, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the government continue to strengthen coordination in monitoring foreign debt developments, supported by the application of prudential principles in its management.\par \par \uc2 "The role of foreign debt will continue to be optimized in supporting development financing and driving sustainable national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth while minimizing risks that can affect \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability," he concluded.\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020240215ek2f00008\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
