\par\par \b \uc2 Insight: Indonesia's valentine: Vote buying and democratic backsliding\b0\par\par\uc2 954 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 February 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Widya Tuslian,\par \par \uc2 During almost every Valentine's Day, cautionary flyers against the celebration's Western cultural values circulate in many Muslim-majority regions of Indonesia. While not universally opposed, Indonesia has maintained a love-hate relationship with Valentine's Day that is characterized by a mixture of acceptance and reservation.\par \par \uc2 However, this year, the dynamics surrounding Valentine's Day were particularly noteworthy, not due to a perceptible shift in its cultural significance, but rather because it coincided with the nation's most significant democratic event.\par \par \uc2 Across the country, the landscape has been transformed, not by romantic hues of pink, but by the vibrant display of political party banners heralding presidential and \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  candidates. In the days leading up to Feb. 14, discussions on political matters reached a crescendo, underscoring the gravity of the moment for Indonesian democracy.\par \par \uc2 On the dawn of Valentine's Day, a darker reality loomed--the exchange of votes for groceries or a couple hundred thousand rupiah and promises of future betterment became a deep-seated practice in Indonesian politics.\par \par \uc2 This phenomenon is widely known as "serangan fajar" (predawn attack), a bleak reality that stains Indonesia's democracy. In the early morning of Feb. 14, as couples elsewhere celebrated Valentine's Day with romantic gestures, many Indonesians found themselves engaged in a different kind of exchange that eroded the very foundation of democracy.\par \par \uc2 Serangan fajar unfolds in the darkness before dawn, when the streets are still quiet, and the day has yet to fully begin. It is a time when clandestine deals are struck, and the integrity of the electoral process is compromised. For some, it is a means of survival, an opportunity to alleviate the burdens of poverty, albeit temporarily. For others, it is a calculated strategy to secure power and influence at any cost.\par \par \uc2 The practice of vote buying perpetuates a cycle of corruption and disenfranchisement under which the voices of the marginalized are drowned out by the clamor of vested interests. It erodes trust in the electoral system and undermines the principles of accountability and transparency. Despite efforts to combat it, including \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  awareness campaigns, serangan fajar persists, casting a shadow over Indonesia's democratic aspirations.\par \par \uc2 But vote buying is just one facet of the broader challenge that faces Indonesian democracy: The specter of democratic backsliding. As the country grapples with the erosion of democratic norms and institutions, the promise of a vibrant and inclusive democracy remains elusive.\par \par \uc2 The rise of populist leaders, the politicization of the judiciary and the curtailment of civil liberties are among the many warning signs that Indonesia is sliding away from its democratic ideals.\par \par \uc2 At the heart of this democratic backsliding is a struggle for power and influence, where incumbents seek to entrench their hold on power at the expense of democratic principles. The ruling elite, buoyed by patronage networks and vested interests, manipulate the levers of power to their advantage, undermining the rule of law and the separation of powers. In this climate of impunity, dissent is silenced, and dissenters are branded as enemies of the state.\par \par \uc2 This year's election, which involved the scion of Indonesia's political dynasty, is emblematic of this trend. A meteoric rise to prominence, facilitated by familial connections and political patronage, underscores the entrenched nature of elite capture in Indonesian politics.\par \par \uc2 This candidacy, endorsed by powerful interests and backed by the machinery of the state, exemplifies the fusion of political power and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  privilege that defines Indonesia's political landscape.\par \par \uc2 But this is more than just a reflection of familial ties and political maneuvering; it is a symptom of a deeper malaise afflicting Indonesian democracy. The concentration of power in the hands of a select few, coupled with the erosion of democratic norms and institutions, poses a grave threat to the future of Indonesian democracy.\par \par \uc2 Unless urgent action is taken to address these underlying issues, Indonesia risks sliding further down the slippery slope of democratic decay.\par \par \uc2 In the face of these challenges, civil society actors, including academics, activists and ordinary citizens, have emerged as bulwarks of democracy, tirelessly advocating for reform and accountability. Their efforts, though often met with resistance and repression, serve as a beacon of hope in an otherwise bleak landscape.\par \par \uc2 Through their collective action and unwavering commitment to democratic ideals, they embody the spirit of resilience and resistance that is essential for safeguarding Indonesia's democratic future.\par \par \uc2 As Indonesia deals with the aftermath of another contentious election season, the specter of democratic backsliding looms large. The challenges facing the country are manifold, from the pervasive influence of money in politics to the erosion of democratic norms and institutions.\par \par \uc2 Yet, amid the gloom and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , there remains a glimmer of hope--a belief that Indonesia's democratic journey is far from over.\par \par \uc2 The fate of Indonesian democracy rests in the hands of its people. It is they who must rise to defend the principles of democracy, demand accountability from their leaders and uphold the rule of law. Only through collective action and unwavering resolve can Indonesia chart a course toward a more just, inclusive and democratic future.\par \par \uc2 In conclusion, Indonesia's Valentine's is not a day of love and romance, but a day marked by political intrigue and democratic backsliding. As the country grapples with the challenges facing its democratic experiment, it must confront the underlying causes of democratic decay and chart a new course toward a more resilient and inclusive democracy.\par \par \uc2 Only then can Indonesia truly fulfill its promise as a beacon of democracy in Southeast Asia and beyond.\par \par \uc2 ______________________\par \par \uc2 PhD researcher at Van Vollenhoven Institute (VVI) Leiden Law School, Royal Dutch Academy of South East Asia and Caribbean Studies (KITLV)\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240220ek2l00003\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Business\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia \highlight\uc2  Maintains Benchmark Interest Rate at 6%\b0\par\par\uc2 279 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 February 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  decided to keep the benchmark interest rate at 6 percent during the Board of Governors Meeting on Feb. 20-21, 2024, maintaining the rate since October.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the deposit facility interest rate remains at 5.25 percent, and the lending facility interest rate stays at 6.75 percent.\par \par \uc2 "The decision to maintain the BI Rate is consistent with the pro-stability monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  focus, aiming for the strengthening of the rupiah exchange rate. It also reflects pre-emptive and forward-looking measures to ensure controlled inflation within the target range of 2.5 plus-minus 1 percent i