\par\par \b \uc2 BI holds key  \highlight22\uc2 interest rates \highlight\uc2 , project cuts in second half\b0\par\par\uc2 Deni Ghifari , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 494 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 February 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  has kept its benchmark interest rate unchanged at 6 percent and reaffirmed that cuts to the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate might be in order in the second half of this year.\par \par \uc2 Briefing the press on Wednesday after the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's two-day monthly \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  meeting, BI Governor \uc2 Perry Warjiyo\uc2  noted that the decision considered geopolitical developments and a global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that was performing better than previously estimated.\par \par \uc2 "For now, we will maintain the BI Rate. Be patient, okay. Until when? [According to] our baseline scenario, the plan is [to reduce the rate] in the second half [of 2024]," Perry said, before mentioning three conditions to be met for rate cuts, namely under-control inflation, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and a stable rupiah exchange rate.\par \par \uc2 BI had maintained the key rate at 5.75 percent for most of 2023, before unexpectedly hiking it by 25 basis points (bps) in October, citing global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the main concern.\par \par \uc2 In February these \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  remain on BI's mind, as geopolitical tensions persist and may disrupt global supply chains, according to Perry.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, BI also considered when the \uc2 United States Federal Reserve\uc2  might start cutting its interest rate benchmark, the federal funds rate (FFR), Perry explained, adding that a cumulative reduction of 75 bps in the FFR was projected for the second half of 2024.\par \par \uc2 The latest US labor market and inflation data has dashed hopes for an imminent FFR reduction, with market pricing now pointing to June as the most likely time for a first rate cut in the US, according to the \uc2 CME\uc2  FedWatch Tool.\par \par \uc2 "We believe that when there is certainty about the FFR going down and about global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions [...], there will be certainty for foreign investors to invest in Indonesia," Perry said.\par \par \uc2 He elaborated that incoming investment was important to avoid imported inflation and ensure rupiah stability, which was needed to prepare for global risks.\par \par \uc2 However, fueled by strong GDP growth in the US and India, Perry noted that the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was playing out better than expected, despite recession in some developed economies like the United Kingdom and Japan.\par \par \uc2 Perry said that the growth in the US and India had also helped Indonesia's GDP grow, as exports to both countries were increasing, which was a big help amid weaker demand from China.\par \par \uc2 Recession is commonly defined as two consecutive quarters of annual GDP contraction.\par \par \uc2 Coordinating \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister \uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2  told reporters on Monday that the UK recession had little to no effect on Indonesia since the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  relationship between the two countries was limited.\par \par \uc2 Japan's recession, on the other hand, might impact Indonesia, although the nature of that impact is not straightforward. Airlangga claimed it may be positive for Indonesia as Japanese firms may look for new sources of growth, which could translate into increasing their investment in Southeast Asia's largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par