\par\par \b \uc2 How Indonesian Media Has Covered the Russia-Ukraine War\b0\par\par\uc2 878 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 February 2024\par \uc2 Tempo.co\par \uc2 TEMPOE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk \par \par \uc2 By: Ika Idris, Prasetia Pratama, Monash Data and Democracy Research Hub, and Nala Edwin, LSPR Communication & Business Institute, in Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Data showed the view of the Indonesian government was not very prominent in the news.\par \par \uc2 The two-year-old Russian invasion of Ukraine divided \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  opinion in many countries. Media coverage has naturally had a significant influence on people\u8217\'20\'19s views, especially in countries far removed from the conflict.\par \par \uc2 The war has strained international ties, with a refugee emergency, diplomatic tension, energy supply \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  anxiety.\par \par \uc2 While many countries have loudly condemned the war, others have responded more cautiously.\par \par \uc2 In Indonesia, sentiment in the media towards Russia's invasion has been overwhelmingly negative, reflecting widespread condemnation of the aggression.\par \par \uc2 An analysis of news reports relating to the war reveals important insights about the kind of information reaching the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the figures who have had the most prominent voice in the news.\par \par \uc2 In Indonesia, pro-Russia propaganda spread through social media, like \uc2 YouTube\uc2  and TikTok, as well as established news websites such as Tribun Timur and Tribun News.\par \par \uc2 According to the US Global Engagement Center, Russia has five pillars of propaganda: official government communications, state-funded global messaging, cultivation of proxy sources, weaponisation of social media, and cyber disinformation.\par \par \uc2 In Indonesia, the cultivation of proxy sources and weaponisation of social media have effectively influenced narratives of the war and the image of Russian president \uc2 Vladimir Putin\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Russia and Ukraine both have a significant role in the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  through trade in energy and food commodities.\par \par \uc2 An analysis of online news in Indonesia was warranted by the country\u8217\'20\'19s \u8216\'20\'18free and active\u8217\'20\'19 foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  principles.\par \par \uc2 Information about the war in Ukraine in online media is essential for several reasons.\par \par \uc2 First, it provides the Indonesian government and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  with current updates on the situation and fosters a better understanding of the conflict\u8217\'20\'19s complexities, its humanitarian impact, and potential geopolitical consequences.\par \par \uc2 Additionally, online media serves as a crucial platform for sharing diverse perspectives and analyses.\par \par \uc2 In our analysis, we collected news from Factiva using two keywords in Bahasa Indonesia: \u8220\'20\'1CRussia invasion\u8221\'20\'1D (invasi Rusia) and \u8220\'20\'1CRussia attack\u8221\'20\'1D (serangan Rusia). From February 24, 2022, to January 31, 2024, there were 3,279 results, consisting of 2,094 online articles from publishers and 1,185 other web-based articles.\par \par \uc2 Most were published by Antara (Indonesia's official news bureau), followed by Jawa Pos, Republika, and Tribun News. Three focused media \u8211\'20\'13 on \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , equity, and investment \u8211\'20\'13 were also at the top of the list: Bisnis Indonesia, IQPlus News, and Investor Daily.\par \par \uc2 We then sampled 600 articles to explore the main topics, sentiment towards Russia, types of sources in the news, and top opinion leaders.\par \par \uc2 The majority of articles covered the invasion itself (30.55 percent), followed by the impact of the war (10.34 percent), victims of conflict (8.34 percent) and other related topics.\par \par \uc2 From the 600 samples, we also found 294 news sources came from various backgrounds such as national leaders, academics and journalists with the most quoted sources from foreign governments and intergovernmental organisations (29.8 percent), followed by the Ukraine government (17 percent) and the Russian government (6.8 percent).\par \par \uc2 From this data, it\u8217\'20\'19s clear the view of the Indonesian government was not very prominent in the news. The voice of the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and civil society organisations in the Ukraine war was also very small, only around 7.22 percent.\par \par \uc2 While foreign governments and intergovernmental organisations were the most quoted sources, the voices of the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and civil society organisations were relatively marginalised, highlighting a potential gap in representing diverse perspectives in media coverage.\par \par \uc2 The news on the Russian invasion of Ukraine received widespread negative sentiments (65.83 percent), followed by neutral sentiments (31.33 percent), and only 2.83 percent positive sentiments.\par \par \uc2 When we analysed the sentiments, we found at least two main narratives about the invasion.\par \par \uc2 The first one was about Putin\u8217\'20\'19s ambition to restore the glory of the Soviet Union.\par \par \uc2 In this narrative, the Russian army and Putin were portrayed as easily taking down Ukraine and would soon target Baltic countries such as Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.\par \par \uc2 The second narrative portrayed that Russia\u8217\'20\'19s invasion was a lesson for the West\u8217\'20\'19s intervention in the Soviet Union through \uc2 NATO\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The top influencer was Ukraine President \uc2 Volodymyr Zelensky\uc2  (quoted in 58 articles), followed by US President \uc2 Joe Biden\uc2  (quoted in 21 articles), Putin (14 articles), and \uc2 UN\uc2  Secretary-General \uc2 Antonio Guterres\uc2  (11 articles).\par \par \uc2 The only Indonesian in the top 10 list of news influencers was a professor at Universitas Indonesia, Hikmahanto Juwana (7 articles). Indonesian President \uc2 Joko Widodo\uc2  only appeared three times in our sample, and the \uc2 Indonesian Ministry of Foreign Affairs\uc2  appeared twice.\par \par \uc2 So it would seem that the Indonesian government machinery has got its work cut out for it in its efforts to place the Indonesian government and Indonesian leaders more prominently in the global press.\par \par \uc2 Originally published under Creative Commons by 360info\u8482\'21\'22.\par \par \uc2 *) DISCLAIMER\par \par \uc2 Articles published in the \u8220\'20\'1CYour Views & Stories\u8221\'20\'1D section of en.tempo.co website are personal opinions written by third parties, and cannot be related or attributed to en.tempo.co\u8217\'20\'19s official stance.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://statik.tempo.co/data/2023/11/12/id_1253686/1253686_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMPOE0020240222ek2m00001\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
