\par\par \b \uc2 Prabowo's  \highlight22\uc2 fiscal \highlight\uc2  constraints\b0\par\par\uc2 695 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 February 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post,\par \par \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2 , the most likely winner of the Feb.14 presidential election, has set a high growth-oriented \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  agenda and asserted in his various campaign speeches over the last few weeks his tolerance of \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of up to 6 percent of gross domestic product and a greater government debt ratio of up to 60 percent to finance his programs.\par \par \uc2 But he will encounter \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  constraints to achieve annual \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 6 to 7 percent and to finance his very populist measures. His flagship social assistance program alone, which will provide free meals and milk for about 50 million children is estimated by many analysts to cost about Rp 450 trillion (US$30 billion) annually, or equivalent to 13 percent of the government's total \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  budgeted for the whole of this year.\par \par \uc2 Even though President \uc2 Joko "Jokowi" Widodo\uc2 , who endorsed and supported Prabowo's election, is still fully responsible for preparing and proposing to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  the first (2025) \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the new president on Aug. 16, Prabowo is unlikely to be able to get a far more expansive \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  plan than this year's total \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  set at Rp 3.3 quadrillion (US$213 billion) with a \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of 2.3 percent.\par \par \uc2 Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2 , now in the last few months of her tenure, is unlikely compromise the principle of prudent \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  management to allow for a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  close to the 3 percent legal ceiling. Amid the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Prabowo may eventually be able to implement his expansive \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  if he can get adequate political support at the House to amend the 2003 State Finances Law, which limits the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to 3 percent, but that would incur big risks to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability.\par \par \uc2 Even though bigger \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  will inject vitality to generate higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, in Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  context that always means a bigger \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which consequently requires bigger borrowing or debt because the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  ratio to GDP has mostly been hovering below 10 percent, among the lowest in the ASEAN region.\par \par \uc2 Increased borrowing requires more bond issues, creating a much heavier debt service burden, which this year alone is set at Rp 497 trillion, or more than 22 percent of total \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues and 15 percent of total state expenditures.\par \par \uc2 The debt interest costs, which do not yet include the bonds that mature this year and have to be amortized, are even bigger than the funds allotted for infrastructure projects this year. This situation is caused by Indonesia's relatively high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . At 6.7 percent, the benchmark 10-year government rupiah bond yield is the highest among 10 regional local-currency notes compiled by the \uc2 Asian Development Bank\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The bigger debt service burden will cause a vicious cycle of increased sovereign risk and consequently government borrowing costs, crowding out corporate bonds, setting off downward pressure on the rupiah and the bond market and increasing imported inflation in the domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Besides \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  restrictions, there is another major barrier that has been hindering the pace of growth over the past decade. Indonesia's high incremental capital output ratio (ICOR), a common measure of investment efficiency, which according to Coordinating Economics Minister \uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2  rose to 7.5 in 2023 from 6 in 2022 and 5.5 in 2014. This means that $7.50 spent on investment produces only $1 of income compared with Malaysia's ICOR at 4.6, the Philippines at 3.7, Vietnam at 5.2 and India at 4.9.\par \par \uc2 Based on various private sector surveys, including those by foreign chambers of commerce, the main identified structural and \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  impediments to investment and higher growth are a weak regulatory framework, inadequate infrastructure, a shallow capital market, the widespread mismatch of skills in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and stringent labor regulations.\par \par \uc2 Bureaucratic hurdles and socio-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  disparities also pose formidable barriers to sustainable growth. Hence, if the new government wants to achieve annual \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of more than 5 percent without creating \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  overheating, it needs to strengthen the three pillars of growth: basic infrastructure, institutional capacity and human capital.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240223ek2o0000i\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 The Meat Import  \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 2,406 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 February 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 ANOTHER letter was sent to the office of the Coordinating Ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Lapangan Banteng, Central Jakarta, on Wednesday, February 21. The senders were four meat business organizations, namely the Indonesian Animal Protein Entrepreneurs Association, the Indonesian Meat Importers Association, the Indonesian Meat Distributors Association, and the Indonesian Meat Processing Industry Association. They asked the government to immediately issue a letter approving the imports of beef for regular consumption for the period of 2024.\par \par \uc2 The four associations said the beef import permits are crucial for business certainty for the meat processing industry, hotels, restaurants and cafes. Business players in these sectors need sustainable supply at affordable prices. \u8220\'20\'1CThat way, when the demand for meat increases during Ramadan (Islamic fasting month) and Lebaran (end of fasting month celebration), there will be no supply shortages that trigger price fluctuations,\u8221\'20\'1D reads an excerpt from the letter signed by the leaders of the four associations.\par \par \uc2 The letter, addressed to Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2 , was copied to Trade Minister Zulkifli Hasan and the National Food Agency Chief Arief Prasetyo Adi. Earlier this year, on January 12, the four associations sent a similar letter to the Coordinating Ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s Deputy for Food and Agribusiness Coordination, Dida Gardera. They expressed concern that a delay in issuing permits would affect meat supplies and raise prices.\par \par \uc2 Workers unload Australia-imported cattle at \uc2 Tanjung Priok Port\uc2 , Jakarta, September 2015. TEMPO/Tony Hartawan\par \par \uc2 The slow pace of meat import permit issuance was mentioned during a coordination meeting to control regional inflation held by the Ministry of Home Affairs on February 19. Edy Priyono, Deputy III to the Chief of Presidential Staff for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs, who attended the meeting, revealed that there were observations indicating more commodities leaving the safe zone. These commodities include rice, chili, and beef. \u8220\'20\'1CCurrently, it\u8217\'20\'19s still at a safe level, even though the prices are above the reference price,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Edy reminded the need for caution against potential inflation from these commodities. He said that business actors have complained to the Presidential Staff Office about the slow issuance of approvals for beef and feeder cattle imports. If not addressed immediately, Edy feared that supplies would be late and disrupt supplies during Ramadan and Idul Fitri (end of fasting month celebration). \u8220\'20\'1CIf there is a supply disruption, prices will almost certainly rise.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Edy\u8217\'20\'19s concerns are not without reason, given how importing meat from Australia takes time for the shipping process, quarantine and so on. That is why he is proposing to invite the Director-General of Foreign Trade at the Trade Ministry to the next meeting to coordinate inflation control and explain the developments in issuing permits to import live cattle and beef. \u8220\'20\'1CWe worry that if this is not anticipated, problems will arise,\u8221\'20\'1D he commented.\par \par \uc2 Finally, on February 22, Trade Minister Zulkifli Hasan issued import approval letters to a number of companies. Director of Imports at the Trade Ministry, Arif Sulistiyo, said that the ministry had received 56 applications for beef imports, with a total allocation of 140,951 tons. \u8220\'20\'1CAll these applications have been approved for import,\u8221\'20\'1D he told Tempo on February 23.\par \par \uc2 Imported frozen beef belonging to Berdikari arrive at \uc2 Tanjung Priok Port\uc2 , Jakarta, December 2022. National Food Agency Doc.\par \par \uc2 According to Arif, beef prices are still stable at Rp138,000 (around US$8.83) per kilogram, increasing slightly by 0.22 percent from the previous month. But Arif said that this figure is still below the sales reference price set by the National Food Agency. He said that the Trade Ministry supports efforts to stabilize meat prices through coordination with other ministries/agencies.\par \par \uc2 Earlier, the four meat business associations had sent letters several times requesting an audience with several ministers because the permits they requested had not been issued. They sent letters to the Minister of Trade and Minister of Agriculture on January 23, and another to the Minister of Trade on February 20. But their requests for an audience were not granted.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 APPLICATIONS for permits to import beef were halted in the Indonesia National Single Window system after importers submitted their data in the last quarter of 2023. It was not until a limited coordination meeting on food led by Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2  took place on December 13, that some progress was seen. The meeting decided that the import volume of beef for regular consumption stipulated in the food commodity balance is 145,251 tons.\par \par \uc2 In addition to the import permits for private parties, the government also gave assignments to two state-owned enterprises (SOEs), the State Logistics Agency (Bulog) and Berdikari. Bulog was assigned to import 100,000 tons of buffalo meat from India, while Berdikari\u8212\'20\'14part of the holding for food SOEs, ID Food\u8212\'20\'14was tasked to import 20,000 tons of beef. Meanwhile, meat for regular industrial purposes is imported by producer importers in a volume of 5,000 tons.\par \par \uc2 Beef imported from Australia unloaded at the State Logistics Agency (Bulog) warehouse, Jakarta, June 2016. TEMPO/Tony Hartawan\par \par \uc2 The regular consumption meat import quota given by the government for private importers is far below the amount proposed. There are 380 importing companies that applied for permits to import up to 462,011 tons. This means that the government only approved 31 percent of what was applied. Last year, the realization of meat imports by private companies amounted to 167,633 tons, just 18.68 percent of the volume permitted, which was 897,184 tons.\par \par \uc2 The allocated 145,251 tons is only a lump sum figure, the total volume of meat allowed to enter Indonesia. The government has not distributed that volume between the 380 companies that requested import permits. Minister Airlangga appointed the National Food Agency to verify the need for beef for regular consumption, including the import plans of companies that were given technical recommendations by the Agriculture Ministry.\par \par \uc2 The verification results are then entered into the National Commodity Balance System (Sinas NK). The recalculated figures or the determination of the verification results of the volume of beef needs will be the basis for issuing import approval letters (SPI) by the Trade Ministry.\par \par \uc2 This verification result by the National Food Agency caused a stir. Suhandri, Secretary-General of the Indonesian Meat Importers Association, said that the import permits issued to all association members were only 34 percent of what was requested. Noverdi Bross, Executive Director of the Indonesian Animal Protein Entrepreneurs Association, also mentioned that import permits issued for companies affiliated with his association were only one-third of the demand. \u8220\'20\'1CMoreover, the import approval letter was issued two months late,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. According to Noverdi, import permits are usually issued in early January, giving companies enough time to bring in meat from various sources.\par \par \uc2 A beef vendor at Jatinegara Market, Jakarta, February 20. TEMPO/Tony Hartawan\par \par \uc2 Noverdi believes that the government is imposing quotas that limit the procurement of meat from abroad. This time, he said, the restriction reached one-third of the requested amount. The government had actually abolished the quota system a decade ago. In 2016, Rizal Ramli, who was then the Coordinating Minister for Maritime and Resources Affairs, criticized the import quota system for food, which made prices more expensive.\par \par \uc2 Irregularities, among others, occurred in imports of beef. The large number of importers does not indicate healthy price competition. At that time, Rizal stated that of the many meat importers, there were only six to seven big players. The rest only made noises, and controlled the black market.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 THE fate of 2,500 feeder cattle from Australia purchased by Didiek Purwanto from Darwin, Broome, and Queensland remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . These live cattle are awaiting a livestock carrier to transport them to Indonesia. \u8220\'20\'1CHopefully, there will be a ship on March 6 or 8,\u8221\'20\'1D said Didiek, the owner of Karunia Alam Sentosa Abadi, a cattle fattening (feedlot) company in Lampung, to Tempo on February 22.\par \par \uc2 Didiek and members of the Indonesian Beef Cattle Business Association (Gapuspindo) acquired the license to import live cattle a week earlier than importers of frozen beef. However, this did not enable Didiek and Gapuspindo members to bring in the cattle sooner. He said that the import permit for Gapuspindo was issued on February 16, with the procurement period valid until December 31. The total number is 579,000 feeder cattle and 13,000 buffaloes. \u8220\'20\'1CCurrently, all members are working to bring the cattle in as soon as possible,\u8221\'20\'1D said Didiek, the Chairman of Gapuspindo.\par \par \uc2 However, another issue has emerged. Currently, there is a shortage of available ships in the cattle\u8217\'20\'19s countries of origin. According to Didiek, many ships have already been used to transport goods to other countries because Indonesia was late in issuing import licenses. Additionally, cattle that were initially going to be purchased have been redirected to buyers from other countries. To make things worse, heavy rainfall in Australia has caused flooding in several locations, making it difficult to ship cattle from farms.\par \par \uc2 Didiek said that Australian cattle are primarily available in the Northern Territory and Broome and Fremantle in Western Australia. Supplies can also be found in Queensland, located on the country\u8217\'20\'19s eastern side. However, recent significant flooding in Darwin and the Northern Territory has made it challenging to transport cattle. Didiek stated that it would be costly even if they managed to transport them.\par \par \uc2 According to Didiek, in Western Australia, most cattle are currently in the fattening period, which is yet to be harvest time. Therefore, alternative supplies are coming from Queensland. \u8220\'20\'1CBut the prices there are already high because cattle cannot be transported from other places,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile in Indonesia, the simultaneous issuance of import licenses has led to competition among importers in the search for cattle. This has led to price increases. On the vessel side, limited space has increased rent per square meter, resulting in a chain reaction of negative effects.\par \par \uc2 Didiek stated that Indonesian entrepreneurs who raise feeder cattle or live cattle for fattening have limited options. They are willing to pay a premium price for the goods they need. Didiek estimated that feeder cattle would arrive at several ports around mid-March, after which they will be fattened for two to three months before being slaughtered in May. What this means, he said, that even though the license was issued early, the cattle will only arrive in the next two weeks. \u8220\'20\'1CAnd that would be too late to meet the demand for Ramadan and Idul Fitri.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 This is unfortunate considering that members of Gapuspindo have applied for import permits since December 22 last year, expecting the import approval letter will be issued in January. According to Article 8 of Trade Minister \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 25/2022, import permits should be issued within a maximum of five working days from the date the application is received with sufficient requirements. The import permit was not issued until one and a half months later.\par \par \uc2 Deputy for Food and Agribusiness Coordination at the Coordinating Ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Dida Gardera, stated that the entire business process, from proposing demand plans by business actors to issuing import approvals, has been running according to the established procedures. The issuance of import approvals (PI) requires the verification of technical requirements and volumes set by the government. The allocation of import volumes for each company must also be entered into the Sinas NK and receive considerations for the determination of the demand plan from the supervising ministry. In short, PI is issued when the requirements and volumes in the Sinas NK are fulfilled.\par \par \uc2 Arif Sulistiyo from the Trade Ministry stated that they had only received applications for meat imports this month. He claimed that the meat import permit for regular consumption, which amounted to 145,251 tons, was issued after considering the local stock and production plan. Arif added that the government also considered the company\u8217\'20\'19s track record of import implementation over the past five years.\par \par \uc2 Over the past five years, Arif said, meat import approvals have averaged 900,000 tons, but the realization was only 16 to 18 percent, or 140,000 to 160,000 tons. \u8220\'20\'1CThis time, the allocation is more for better import control and planning,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. If there is a shortage later on, Arif added, entrepreneurs can propose additional volume in the commodity balance evaluation.\par \par \uc2 Sharing similar sentiments, National Food Agency Chief Arief Prasetyo Adi said that the government implemented import allocations as a form of measured importation \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . For instance, he said, the government has not issued import permits for buffalo meat because stocks are still available. \u8220\'20\'1CYou can check at the Suri warehouse, for example, where there are still 30,000 to 40,000 tons.\u8221\'20\'1D The Suri that Arief referred to is Suri Nusantara Jaya, a company that imports buffalo meat from India.\par \par \uc2 Trade Ministry Director of Imports Arif Sulistiyo. Trade Ministry Doc.\par \par \uc2 Regarding the cut in the allocation of frozen meat imports, Arief said the cause was a complaint from the Trade Minister. \u8220\'20\'1CWe gave the permit to import 100 (tons), but the realization was only 20,\u8221\'20\'1D he gave an example. There are also companies that were given certain meat import allotments, but only offal has been realized. \u8220\'20\'1CThis must be disciplined,\u8221\'20\'1D Arief emphasized.\par \par \uc2 Arief assured that the meat storage is still full. This means, he said, that there is still stock available. \u8220\'20\'1CThe question is, do we want excessive imports, or have a measured approach?\u8221\'20\'1D he asked. According to Arief, the National Food Agency is tasked with measuring imports. \u8220\'20\'1CWe are transparent. There are no fees here. There are no charges by the kilogram.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Marina Ratna