\par\par \b \uc2 Revamping bank funding for optimal capital allocation\b0\par\par\uc2 1,000 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 February 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Darmo Wicaksono, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 In the dynamic and ever-evolving landscape of the financial industry, banks continually seek innovative strategies to meet their credit targets and remain competitive. One such strategic approach that has gained significance in recent years is the reallocation of assets and the strengthening of funding.\par \par \uc2 By effectively managing and reallocating their assets and enhancing their funding sources, banks can improve their financial stability, optimize their resources and ultimately achieve their credit objectives.\par \par \uc2 The process of asset reallocation involves the strategic redistribution of a bank's resources, such as capital, investments and loans, to enhance its overall performance and profitability. By reassessing and prioritizing their existing assets based on risk, return and liquidity considerations, banks can align their resources more closely with their credit targets and business objectives.\par \par \uc2 This may involve divesting underperforming assets, investing in higher-yielding opportunities or rebalancing their asset portfolio to ensure optimal returns. Moreover, asset reallocation enables banks to adapt to changing market conditions and regulatory requirements while also mitigating risks and enhancing their capital adequacy.\par \par \uc2 By diversifying their asset base and optimizing their risk-weighted assets, banks can better withstand \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  downturns, navigate market \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  and capitalize on growth opportunities.\par \par \uc2 This strategic agility and resilience are essential for banks to effectively manage credit risks, sustain profitability and foster long-term financial sustainability. The reallocation of liquid assets to support credit growth is reflected in a decrease in the share of securities and an increase in the share of loans.\par \par \uc2 According to data from the Mandiri Institute, loans and securities still dominate the composition of assets in the banking industry. For loans, the share is expected to increase from 57.80 percent in 2022 to 62.35 percent in 2024, while securities are expected to decrease from 16.77 percent in 2022 to 16.53 percent in 2024.\par \par \uc2 Alongside asset reallocation, strengthening funding sources plays a crucial role in supporting banks' credit activities and achieving their lending objectives.\par \par \uc2 Banks rely on a diverse range of funding options, such as deposits, interbank borrowings, debt securities and equity capital, to finance their lending operations and meet regulatory requirements. By enhancing their funding mix and optimizing their funding structure, banks can reduce their funding costs, enhance their liquidity management and support their credit growth initiatives.\par \par \uc2 Banks currently appear to be focusing on gathering inexpensive funds, particularly current account saving account (CASA) deposits, as banks do not need to incur significant costs to obtain these types of third-party funds unlike deposits, which are more expensive.\par \par \uc2 According to the Integrated Commercial Bank Report (LBUT), bank funding is dominated by third-party funds, especially CASA, showing a growing trend from around Rp 150 trillion (US$9.6 billion) in 2018 to approximately Rp 270 trillion in 2023. In the future, banks also expect continued CASA growth to reach around Rp 300 trillion, as observed pre-pandemic.\par \par \uc2 In addition, strengthening funding sources can improve banks' financial flexibility and resilience, enabling them to better manage liquidity risks, fund future growth opportunities and maintain regulatory compliance.\par \par \uc2 By prioritizing stable and long-term funding sources, banks can reduce their reliance on volatile funding markets, enhance funding stability and ensure sustainable financing for credit activities. This proactive approach to funding management is essential for banks to build investor confidence, enhance their credit ratings and access funding at competitive rates.\par \par \uc2 Incorporating asset reallocation and strengthening funding as core components of their strategic planning, banks can leverage these initiatives to enhance their financial performance, optimize their balance sheet and achieve their credit targets more effectively.\par \par \uc2 Incorporating asset reallocation and strengthening funding as core components of their strategic planning, banks can leverage these initiatives to enhance their financial performance, optimize their balance sheet and achieve their credit targets more effectively.\par \par \uc2 By aligning their asset allocation with their risk appetite, profitability goals and market trends, banks can enhance their asset quality, maximize their returns and improve their overall financial health.\par \par \uc2 Likewise, by diversifying and optimizing their funding sources, banks can strengthen their funding resilience, support their lending activities and enhance their competitive position in the market. According to the LBUT, asset reallocation is supported by money market transactions, repos and monetary operations.\par \par \uc2 This is evident in the banks' efforts to optimize short-term liquidity management through outright government securities transactions, interbank money market activities, repos and monetary operations amid a decline in liquid instruments in 2022-2023.\par \par \uc2 Interbank money market transactions in the rupiah has seen a sharp increase from around Rp 120 trillion in January 2022 to reach around Rp 400 trillion in January 2024. This trend is in line with repo transactions between banks, which increased from around Rp 100 trillion in January 2022 to around Rp 300 trillion in January 2024.\par \par \uc2 Interbank money market and repo transactions are predominantly carried out by national private commercial banks and state-owned banks, in line with the high credit growth in these banking segments.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, by integrating asset reallocation and funding enhancement strategies, banks can create synergy and maximize the effectiveness of their financial management practices.\par \par \uc2 For instance, reallocating assets from low-yielding investments to higher-yielding opportunities can not only optimize returns, but also generate additional funds to support lending activities. Similarly, improving funding efficiency and diversifying funding sources can reduce funding costs, enhance liquidity management and support credit growth initiatives.\par \par \uc2 As banks navigate the complex and challenging environment of the financial industry, strategic reallocation of assets and strengthening of funding sources have emerged as critical imperatives to achieve credit targets and sustain long-term growth.\par \par \uc2 By adopting a proactive and holistic approach to asset management and funding optimization, banks can enhance their financial resilience, support their credit activities and drive sustainable business performance. Ultimately, the successful implementation of these strategies can enable banks to achieve their credit targets, meet regulatory requirements and deliver value to their stakeholders in a competitive market landscape.\par \par \uc2 ____________________\par \par \uc2 A senior economist at the International Department of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240225ek2q00004\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
