\par\par \b \uc2 Clear and timely  \highlight22\uc2 regulation \highlight\uc2  key to AI ecosystem\b0\par\par\uc2 1,034 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 February 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Janitra Haryanto , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The Communications and Information Ministry recently issued a set of artificial intelligence (AI) guidelines through Circular No. 9/2023, which outlines nonbinding AI-related ethical principles as well as responsibilities of private and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  AI developers and operators.\par \par \uc2 The circular stipulates nine values that align with international AI principles, like those of \uc2 UNESCO\uc2  and the \uc2 Organization for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation and Development\uc2  (\uc2 OECD\uc2 ).\par \par \uc2 The ministry's decision to issue these voluntary principles and responsibilities is a strategic move in response to the growing use of AI in the country. Governments within and beyond the Asia-Pacific area have taken similar approaches.\par \par \uc2 Singapore, for instance, has recently issued a nonbinding guideline specifically for generative AI, a technology that can generate text-based content and images.\par \par \uc2 Nonetheless, the circular can only explain so much about how Indonesia will govern AI in the future. With the issuance of the guideline, the government should start determining the appropriate regulatory model for AI by considering what institution will serve as the "hub" for AI \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  and how the institution can oversee AI in a clear and timely manner.\par \par \uc2 Currently, no \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  lays out Indonesia's AI regulatory framework. Many assume that the ministry will be the lead regulator of AI development.\par \par \uc2 However, several other government institutions are also working to make their own strides on AI.\par \par \uc2 For example, the National Research and Innovation Agency (BRIN) is playing an active role in shaping cross-sectoral AI \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Following the recommendations of the 2020 National AI Strategy, BRIN is now leading the formulation of a presidential \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on AI.\par \par \uc2 BRIN is also working with the multistakeholder AI forum KORIKA to establish another national AI strategy following the emergence of frontier AI.\par \par \uc2 Prior to the issuance of the circular, the \uc2 Financial Services Authority (OJK)\uc2  issued a similarly nonbinding AI guideline, encompassing the ethical\par \par \uc2 values AI used by financial technology (fintech) companies should espouse.\par \par \uc2 The National Cyber and Encryption Agency (BSSN), meanwhile, shared in a recent focus group discussion that it was formulating its own AI ethical standards.\par \par \uc2 This sporadic development of AI policies can result in regulatory \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  if the government fails to synchronize them. Government institutions should ensure alignment in ethical values as they evaluate AI.\par \par \uc2 To mitigate this potential \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Indonesia needs to build a clear regulatory framework based on the most the appropriate regulatory model, approach and timeline.\par \par \uc2 First, the government should consider a regulatory model that employs a key regulator that establishes the norms of AI development and ensures the concordance of sectoral AI policies.\par \par \uc2 This is not to leave the institution with the overarching authority to regulate AI in all sectors but rather to provide counsel for sectoral regulators.\par \par \uc2 Based on current developments, the communications ministry is the best-positioned to assume this role, as it already has sufficient experience in regulating emerging technologies across sectors.\par \par \uc2 The ethical values found in the circular can act as the main reference for intersectoral AI developers and operators.\par \par \uc2 Second, any regulatory approach the government adopts should take into account the risks posed and opportunity offered by different types of AI technologies.\par \par \uc2 Other countries have advocated a risk-based system in regulating AI, where the obligations imposed correspond to the risks that a given AI-based product poses.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's home-grown tech start-ups have only begun to utilize AI more optimally just as \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials are learning to use AI to increase work efficiency.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 European Union\uc2 's AI Act classifies AI into four categories: limited risk, generative and general AI, high risk and unacceptable risk.\par \par \uc2 AI with limited risk can operate so long as it fulfills minimum transparency requirements, while on the other extreme, AI of unacceptable risk is banned except in certain cases like real-time biometrics analysis for criminal prosecution.\par \par \uc2 While such an approach will help regulate AI appropriately, the government must carefully deliberate the qualifications of high-risk AI.\par \par \uc2 These AI applications often promise the greatest value for society. For instance, high-risk AI applications in the health sector (as identified in EU AI Act) may identify future disease trends or invent new ways to address diseases incurable today.\par \par \uc2 In such cases, the Indonesian government should assess the cost of using and not using certain AI technologies.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia can emulate the risk categorization of the EU's AI Act while pondering how AI can accelerate innovation in prioritized sectors like health and trade, especially relating to micro, small and medium enterprises.\par \par \uc2 Communications and Information Ministry \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 3/2021 on licenses for various businesses under the ministry's purview considers AI-based programming of medium to low risk.\par \par \uc2 The government will have to more comprehensively appraise the risks of different activities based on the current, ever-evolving AI landscape.\par \par \uc2 It should utilize the reports that the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  mandates AI developers and operators submit to the ministry annually on April 30 as primary data for analyzing the development of AI in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Lastly, effective AI \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  should factor in the optimal time to introduce stipulations, especially if these are legally binding in nature.\par \par \uc2 AI is still nascent and rapidly developing in Indonesia as much as it is globally. Indonesia's home-grown tech start-ups have only begun to utilize AI more optimally just as \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials are learning to use AI to increase work efficiency.\par \par \uc2 The data gathered as per the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  could serve as the backbone of evidence-based rule that accelerates \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and steers clear of haste and the stifling of innovation.\par \par \uc2 AI promises to propel \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development by making business processes more effective and efficient. A report from Access Partnership found that AI adoption could contribute an additional Rp 2.6 quadrillion (US$170 billion) to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 However, it can also lead to unintended consequences, potentially harming users and disrupting existing social and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  systems. It is essential for the Indonesian government to strategically contemplate the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  of AI.\par \par \uc2 Appointing a key regulator and embracing a clear and timely regulatory framework are key steps toward establishing a productive and safe AI environment.\par \par \uc2 _______________________\par \par \uc2 An analyst at BowerGroupAsia Indonesia, focusing on ICT and enterprise technology industries. The views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240227ek2s0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
