\par\par \b \uc2 Commentary: Improving people's access to new, innovative medicines\b0\par\par\uc2 938 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 March 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Elly Burhaini Faizal,\par \par \uc2 Last week's commemoration of World Rare Disease Day highlights the need for stronger commitments to ensure people with uncommon disorders receive better care and prompt access to adequate treatment.\par \par \uc2 Patients with rare diseases in Indonesia constantly face challenges, from delays in diagnosis and initiation of treatment to poor access to new and innovative medicines.\par \par \uc2 According to Health Ministry data, as of December 2022, about 27 million people, or 8-10 percent of the country's population, live with rare diseases.\par \par \uc2 Globally, there are more than 7,000 rare diseases, which affect over 300 million people. About 80 percent of the diseases have a genetic basis and more than 50 percent impact children. Rare diseases manifest in various forms, including some types of cancers, autoimmune diseases, metabolism disorders and congenital abnormalities.\par \par \uc2 To make it worse, currently approved treatments are only available for up to 5 percent of the recognized rare diseases.\par \par \uc2 Innovative medication is therefore pressing to help people with rare diseases.\par \par \uc2 An innovative medicine refers to a new or improved pharmaceutical product, which offers a new approach to the prevention, diagnosis, treatment and management of diseases, according to the \uc2 World Health Organization\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Innovative medicine also refers to a medicine that contains an active substance or combination of active substances that has not been authorized before.\par \par \uc2 The discovery of new and innovative medicines in recent years should give rise to optimism that orphan drugs, or medications used only for a specific rare disease, can show their efficacy.\par \par \uc2 Nearly 40 percent of the medicines now in development are for rare or very rare conditions, including many cell and gene therapies, according to the \uc2 Association of the British Pharmaceutical Industry\uc2  (\uc2 ABPI\uc2 ).\par \par \uc2 For Indonesia's pharmaceutical industry, an innovative drug discovery has the potential to drive growth and improve \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  health.\par \par \uc2 Innovative medicines can play a crucial role in the development of Indonesia's health sector because they offer new, cost-saving treatment techniques, and technology to invent new medicines for new diseases.\par \par \uc2 The problem is Indonesia only has a limited supply of new medicines and vaccines. The latest study commissioned by the \uc2 Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America\uc2  (\uc2 PhRMA\uc2 ) reveals that in terms of the availability of new medicines, Indonesia ranks the lowest among Asia-Pacific countries and members of the \uc2 Group of 20\uc2 , standing at only 9 percent out of 460 new medicines launched globally between 2012 and 2021.\par \par \uc2 Data from the \uc2 United Nations \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific\uc2  (\uc2 UN ESCAP\uc2 ) further show that in 2021, Indonesia had the lowest market share of investments in the health sector, compared with big countries in the Asia-Pacific, despite its promising \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 It takes about 40 months on average for new medicines--such as for cancers and rare diseases--to enter the Indonesian market after their global launch. And the number is very low at 1 percent of new medicines.\par \par \uc2 "This puts Indonesia in a less competitive position in handling diseases, compared with its neighboring countries," International Pharmaceutical Manufacturers Group (IPMG) vice chairwoman Evie Yulin told The Jakarta Post in an interview.\par \par \uc2 IPMG is a nonprofit organization of multinational research and development-based pharmaceutical companies operating in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 According to IPMG in its 2022 annual report, Indonesia has continued to lose foreign exchange, reaching up to US$50 billion per year, because many people opt to seek medical treatments abroad. This indicates low trust in the national health system and the poor availability of new and innovative medicines in the country.\par \par \uc2 As new diseases arise, a lack of supply of quality innovative medicines is the last thing that patients want to see. With its personalized setting, innovative medicine also can help reduce treatment costs.\par \par \uc2 Some studies have found several reasons behind the low availability of innovative medicines in Indonesia. Apart from patients' financial constraints and the small number of diagnosed rare diseases, regulatory \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  have made it difficult for innovative medicines to enter Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 "We need to develop a national strategy that can overcome the fundamental issue of poor access to innovative medicines through cross-sector collaboration and \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that is more pro-growth and pro-innovation," Evie, also president director of \uc2 Merck Indonesia\uc2 , told the Post.\par \par \uc2 As rare diseases have emerged as a global \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  health priority, the government bears a responsibility to help improve people's access to innovative medicines, encourage research to invent new drugs and localize pharmaceutical manufacturing.\par \par \uc2 Health Minister Budi Gunadi Sadikin has recently offered a respite. He said the government was committed to improving the national pharmaceutical regulatory system through greater adoption of new medicines and vaccines in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Budi admitted drug assessment, licensing, control and monitoring processes posed a great challenge to the national governance for medicines.\par \par \uc2 "[This is required anyway] because a rapid growth pharmaceutical industry impacts on the increase in the number of new products, far more complicated quality issues and various new tech problems," the minister said during a meeting between Indonesia's vaccine producers and Duke-National University of Singapore Medical School (Duke-NUS) representatives in Jakarta on Jan. 26.\par \par \uc2 There is still a long way to go for Indonesian people to get adequate access to innovative medicines.\par \par \uc2 But at least, this year's World Rare Disease Day commemoration served as a reminder that access to innovative medicines for people with rare diseases must be expanded and research and development to discover new drugs must be championed.\par \par \uc2 Let's imagine that one day innovative medicines will be available for those in dire need at any time\par \par \uc2 ______________________\par \par \uc2 A staff writer at The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240306ek370000i\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
