\par\par \b \uc2 Insight: Foreseeing the potential  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  growth risks for this year\b0\par\par\uc2 1,216 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 March 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Faisal Rachman,\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  demonstrated commendable growth of 5.05 percent in 2023, despite the tumultuous challenges posed by the global commodity price slump and the widespread increase in benchmark rates by major nations due to elevated global inflation rates.\par \par \uc2 The sustained resilience of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was underpinned by effective control of inflation, which ended last year at a modest 2.61 percent, comfortably within the targeted range of 2 to 4 percent set by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2 . The well-managed inflationary environment limited the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's key interest rate, the BI rate, to a modest increase of only 50 basis points.\par \par \uc2 Looking ahead to 2024, various international organizations such as the \uc2 International Monetary Fund\uc2 , World Bank and Organization for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation and Development (\uc2 OECD\uc2 ) predict that the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue its resilient growth trajectory amid the looming risks of a global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown driven by China's slower-for-longer \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance and the sustained higher-for-longer \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates in Western countries.\par \par \uc2 This outlook is further bolstered by Indonesia's successful general election in February, solidifying its position as the world's third-largest democracy. As a result, the cautious wait-and-see approach in investment activities is gradually dissipating.\par \par \uc2 Yet the question remains whether the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will further fortify its resilience and effectively navigate the challenges and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  presented by the global landscape.\par \par \uc2 Following the Asian financial crisis of 1998, Indonesia has consistently managed to mitigate the impact of external \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  pressures. However, this success is largely attributed to the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  structure, in which over 50 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) is contributed by household consumption. This implies that as long as household consumption or domestic demand remains stable, it will be relatively easy for the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to sustain its growth rates.\par \par \uc2 Despite the overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of around 5 percent last year, a closer examination reveals that household consumption grew less than 5 percent, specifically at 4.82 percent, falling below the pre-COVID-19 pandemic average growth. Therefore, this situation raises considerable concerns regarding the trajectory of Indonesia's future \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 What impediments are hindering the growth of household consumption?\par \par \uc2 The primary contributors to household consumption growth last year were mobility-related expenditures, namely transportation and communication and restaurant and hotel services, each experiencing substantial growth at 7.59 percent and 6.38 percent, exceeding the pre-pandemic average growth. Consumption associated with apparel and footwear has also returned to pre-pandemic levels.\par \par \uc2 However, consumption related to food and beverages, which constitutes the largest share of household consumption, only grew by 3.44 percent, below the pre-pandemic average of over 5 percent. This situation is concerning if it persists, given that food and beverage consumption represents primary consumption or basic needs.\par \par \uc2 Prolonged disruptions in the consumption patterns of essential goods may pose a risk of decline in secondary and tertiary consumption, such as equipment, services and leisure. Neglecting this issue could potentially lead to a weakening of overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the future.\par \par \uc2 So what factors are contributing to the disruption of consumption related to food and beverages?\par \par \uc2 One of the factors constraining the growth of food and beverage consumption is food inflation. The relatively manageable headline inflation rate in Indonesia last year was primarily due to the low administered price inflation and core inflation. Meanwhile, volatile price inflation, closely tied to food inflation, kept generally increasing. This trend continued into early 2024, creating risk for headline inflation going forward.\par \par \uc2 In February 2024, Indonesia's consumer price index (CPI) inflation was recorded at 2.75 percent year-on-year (yoy), an increase from the end of 2023. This rise was driven by volatile price inflation that was notably high at 8.47 percent yoy, contributing 1.34 percentage points to headline inflation. This was primarily due to the increase in rice prices, a staple for the Indonesian population.\par \par \uc2 Rice itself contributed 0.67 percentage points to headline inflation, half of the contribution to volatile price inflation. Meanwhile, administered price inflation continued to ease to 1.67 percent yoy, in line with the decrease in global commodity prices related to energy, and core inflation decreased to 1.68 percent yoy due to low inflation from the producer side, as reflected in the muted producer price index (PPI) inflation of 0.04 percent yoy at the end of 2023, thus avoiding the risk of inflation being passed through to consumers.\par \par \uc2 Several factors have contributed to the rise in rice prices, including the persistent El Ni?o phenomenon, the approaching harvest season in March to April 2024 leading to reduced market supply, extreme weather conditions disrupting distribution channels, the allocation of a portion of the rice supply for the El Ni?o social assistance aimed at aiding the poor, substantially strengthening demand nearing Ramadan and limited import supply due to many rice-producing countries restricting rice exports.\par \par \uc2 If this situation is not promptly addressed, the risk of rising food inflation will soar, potentially leading to weakened household consumption growth and overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, the challenge of inflation management this year has heightened with the reduction of BI's inflation target to 1.5 to 3.5 percent. Furthermore, starting this year, Statistics Indonesia (BPS) has adopted a new base year, which is 2022=100, for calculating CPI inflation, in which the weight of food, beverages and tobacco inflation has increased from 25.01 percent to 28 percent.\par \par \uc2 Specifically, the inflation weight for the top 10 staple food commodities has risen from 8.23 percent to 9.70 percent, with the inflation weight for rice increasing from 3.33 percent to 3.43 percent. The number of food commodities included in volatile price inflation also increased from 101 to 126.\par \par \uc2 Currently, the government's policies addressing the risks of food inflation and the impact on \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  purchasing power remain primarily focused on the poor segments of society. These include policies such as rice aid, social assistance in the form of direct cash transfers for food risk mitigation, non-cash food assistance and presidential aid. Up to this point, there has been no specific \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  directed at the middle-income class, which constitutes the largest proportion of Indonesia's demographic structure.\par \par \uc2 The absence of specific policies has led to the current rise in food prices eroding the purchasing power of the middle-income group, resulting in a decrease in their \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  allocation for secondary and tertiary consumption.\par \par \uc2 This situation also has occurred as their income growth has been limited, in line with the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  facing numerous challenges, ultimately leading to the use of savings for consumption. This, in turn, can impact future consumption due to the decline in their saving ability.\par \par \uc2 The government's necessary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures to assist the middle-income class do not necessarily have to directly address food consumption. Instead, they can involve providing enhancements to \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  facilities, both goods and services, such as improving education, health care and transportation services that are more accessible and affordable.\par \par \uc2 This approach can effectively smooth their consumption patterns without disrupting future consumption, therebyhaving a positive impact on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 ____________________\par \par \uc2 Head of macroeconomic and financial market research at \uc2 Bank Permata\uc2 . The views expressed are personal.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240307ek380000g\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
