\par\par \uc2 INTERNATIONAL NEWS\par \b \uc2 APEC\uc2  GROWTH OUTLOOK BRIGHTENS, BUT RISKS LINGER\b0\par\par\uc2 635 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 March 2024\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Yuni Arisandy Sinaga\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - The \uc2 APEC\b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to show 3.5-percent growth in 2023 and is projected to sustain growth at 3.2 percent in 2024, higher than previous estimates.\par \par \uc2 The APEC \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Support Unit (PSU) made the growth forecast in a revised report, as per a released received from the PSU here on Saturday.\par \par \uc2 The revised report forecasts that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth will moderate in 2025 to 2.8 percent, with global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  continuing to put pressure on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, in addition to the lagged effects of monetary tightening and scaled-down \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  support measures that \uc2 APEC\uc2  economies have to face, the release stated.\par \par \uc2 Sharing the report at the First APEC Senior Officials\u8217\'20\'19 Meeting in Lima, Peru, director of the PSU, Carlos Kuriyama, warned that protectionism has remained an issue, with the number of trade restrictions and remedies increasing anew in 2023.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThis is something that we need to really pay attention to, especially those (that are) discriminatory in nature as they have the potential to cause some geoeconomic fragmentation ... it is a lose-lose situation for \uc2 APEC\uc2  as a region as well as the world,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CHowever, we are also seeing an uptick in trade facilitation with the number of measures in force enabling trade increasing from 618 in 2022 to 682 in 2023. This is encouraging,\u8221\'20\'1D he added.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, inflation in the APEC region declined to 3.0 percent in December 2023 from 6.1 percent in December 2022. According to the report, while inflation has declined, interest rate adjustments over the past year have partly influenced exchange rate movement.\par \par \uc2 The currencies of 17 APEC economies depreciated 6 percent on average in the period from February 2023 to February 2024, putting an upward pressure on prices and risking currency mismatch, which may affect payment obligations.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CMonetary authorities need to remain on guard as incidents in the Red Sea and the drought in the Panama Canal are affecting shipping routes and freight costs that, in turn, could fuel inflationary pressures\u8212\'20\'14making things more expensive,\u8221\'20\'1D said Rhea C. Hernando, an analyst with the PSU.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThese issues have resulted in extended sailing times by one to two weeks, causing container and vessel shortages, as well as potential port congestion,\u8221\'20\'1D Hernando added.\par \par \uc2 Data in mid-January revealed that composite shipping costs had nearly doubled to reach their highest level in 12 months. Though the latest data, as of 1 February 1, 2024, has indicated some decline, the cost is still significant compared to the level a year ago.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, merchandise trade contracted during the first nine months of 2023 as global demand waned and prices of non-fuel commodities and manufactured products fell.\par \par \uc2 The export and import value of merchandise trade fell to -7.5 percent and -8 percent, respectively, while the export and import volume of merchandise trade fell to -2.1 percent and 4.7 percent, respectively.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe good news comes from commercial services trade, which grew 5.5 percent for export and 9.2 percent for imports,\u8221\'20\'1D a researcher with the PSU, Glacer Ni\u241\'00\'F1o A. Vasquez, said.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CAlthough the growth rates decelerated compared to 2022, we note that travel and tourism as well as some goods-related services such as data services supported this growth,\u8221\'20\'1D Vasquez added.\par \par \uc2 The report also highlights how government \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  is outpacing revenue generation in APEC, with \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  tightening expected in the short term. However, the report underlines the importance of finding the right balance between rebuilding \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  buffers to prepare for future shocks and supporting \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe need a combination of balanced monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies; at the same time, we need to strengthen regional cooperation to resolve the current challenges,\u8221\'20\'1D Kuriyama said.\par \par \uc2 (T.Y012/A/A059/A059) 09-03-2024 20:57:08\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020240309ek39000rt\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Business\par \b \uc2 Indef Predicts Slower  \highlight22\uc2 Economic \highlight\uc2  Growth for Indonesia in 2024\b0\par\par\uc2 461 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 March 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. The Institute for Development of Economics and Finance (Indef) predicts that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2024 will only reach 4.8 percent, falling below the government's target of 5.2 percent.\par \par \uc2 "Considering the global and domestic conditions, it is not pessimistic, but realistic, to forecast \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2024 to be around 4.8 percent," said Indef's Executive Director, Esther Sri Astuti, in Jakarta on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 National \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth has been largely supported by household consumption. Based on data from the Central Statistics Agency (BPS), household consumption contributed significantly to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2023, accounting for 58.83 percent of the \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  components and growing at 4.82 percent.\par \par \uc2 "However, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth components are not limited to household consumption alone, but also include investment, government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , exports, and imports. Yet, household consumption remains dominant," Esther explained.\par \par \uc2 She mentioned that there's a shortage of food supply on the household consumption side in 2024. At the same time, imports have not been fully realized, and rice production has not reached its peak. These factors lead to an increase in demand for food items, especially before the elections. Consequently, prices rise, particularly when supply decreases amid increased demand coupled with seasonal factors such as elections, Ramadan, and Eid.\par \par \uc2 "So, this will erode consumer purchasing power and slow down consumption. Eventually, since 53 percent of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is driven by household consumption, our prediction is an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown," Esther added.\par \par \uc2 Similarly, \uc2 Bank Central Asia\uc2 's Economist Agus Salim Hardjodinoto, predicts that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2024 will reach 5 percent. However, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will still face challenges and opportunities to maintain growth at 5 percent.\par \par \uc2 "We hope that there may be interesting developments amidst the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  that align with the government's target," Agus explained.\par \par \uc2 One of the challenges is to keep the consumption rate at 5 percent. Especially in the first quarter of 2024, there's the election momentum, the distribution of social assistance, food mitigation, and the Ramadan period.\par \par \uc2 "If we can increase it, our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be relatively more solid, and the growth target can be achieved even though other factors may also be affected," Agus concluded.\par \par \uc2 President \uc2 Joko "Jokowi" Widodo\uc2  is targeting \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth to range between 5.3 percent and 5.6 percent in 2025, surpassing the 5.05 percent recorded in 2023 and the 5.2 percent target for this year.\par \par \uc2 In comparison, the \uc2 International Monetary Fund\uc2  (\uc2 IMF\uc2 ) forecasts Indonesia to achieve a growth rate of 5 percent for the current year and the following year. Meanwhile, the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  predicts a decrease in growth for both 2024 and 2025, with the growth rate projected to be 4.9 percent in each of those years.\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020240314ek3e00007\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
