\par\par \b \uc2 Consumers scaled back  \highlight22\uc2 spending \highlight\uc2  in February amid election:  \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 Vincent Fabian Thomas , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 556 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 March 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Consumer confidence declined to 123.1 points in February, down 1.52 points from January, according to \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's (BI) latest monthly report.\par \par \uc2 The figure came in higher, however, than the 122.4 points recorded in February 2023.\par \par \uc2 "The consumer confidence index [IKK] remains above 100, which indicates optimism. This indicates that consumers'confidence in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  remains strong," BI spokesman Erwin Haryono said in a statement on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 The countryheld ageneralelection on Feb. 14. Consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  typically increases in the months leading up to elections in Indonesia as campaign teams fork out on \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  events, but elections also add to \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  course of the country.\par \par \uc2 Consumer confidence dipped across four of five income groups in BI's data, with the deepest month-to-month (mtm) drop seen in those earning between Rp 4.1 million (US$263.22) and Rp 5 million.\par \par \uc2 Respondents to BI's survey expressed less confidence regarding their income and job prospects in February, with the corresponding subindexes dropping by 3.77 percent and 7 percent mtm, respectively. They were also less inclined to purchasedurable goods, which includelong-lasting consumer products like cars andfurniture.\par \par \uc2 However, BI noted that consumers were upbeat about the next six months, with confidence about income and jobs improving by 2.9 percent and 2.46 percent mtm, respectively, but their plans for purchases of durable goods did not reflect the same optimism as the subindex declined further.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's data show that the share of income going to consumption, or the propensity to consume, dropped to 73 percent in February from 74.6 percent in the preceding month.\par \par \uc2 At the same time, the share of income that went to savings increased to 16.7 percent from 16.2 percent, while 10.3 percent went towarddebt payments, up from 9.3 percent in February.\par \par \uc2 The drop in the propensity to consume occurred across all income groups but was particularly pronounced among respondents earning between Rp 1 million and Rp 2 million a month.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, retail sales inched up in February in a seasonal effect following demand induced by the election, Chinese New Year and preparations forRamadan, according to preliminary data released by BI on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's retail sales index was projected to grow by 3.6 percent year-on-year (yoy) to 208.5 points, driven mainly by increased sales in the category of food, beverages and tobacco.\par \par \uc2 Other \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  groups also saw improvement, such as that of information and communication devices as well as that of culture and recreation, both of which had been on a downtrend for months.\par \par \uc2 The projected annual increase in retail sales in February far outpaced the increase of 0.6 percent yoy realized in the same month last year.\par \par \uc2 "On a monthly basis, the growth has improved, even though it remains in the contraction zone," BI's Erwin said in a statement on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 Retail sales are expected to continue increasing over the next three and six months as firms anticipate increased demand from the Lebaran festive period in April and school holidays in July.\par \par \uc2 However, businesses also expect a significant increase in inflation pressure over the next three and six months, driven by the same causes.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240314ek3f0000g\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Business\par \b \uc2 Fitch Ratings\uc2  Affirms Indonesia's 'BBB' Rating with Stable Outlook\b0\par\par\uc2 430 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 March 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. \uc2 Fitch Ratings\uc2  has affirmed Indonesia's credit rating at 'BBB' with a stable outlook. Governor of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2 , \uc2 Perry Warjiyo\uc2 , stated that the rating reflects strong international stakeholders' confidence in macroeconomic stability.\par \par \uc2 "Moreover, it underscores Indonesia's sustained medium-term \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospects following the 2024 elections," Perry said in his statement on Saturday.\par \par \uc2 Perry emphasized that this international trust is supported by \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  credibility and strong \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  synergy between the Government and the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  amidst the lingering high global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Moving forward, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue to monitor global and domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial developments, formulating and implementing necessary measures to ensure the maintenance of macroeconomic and financial stability.\par \par \uc2 "This includes potential adjustments in \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  stances and ongoing reinforcement of synergies with the Government to support the achievement of inclusive and sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 