\par\par \b \uc2 Will a Prabowo presidency spell the end of Indonesian democracy?\b0\par\par\uc2 1,081 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 March 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Satish Mishra,\par \par \uc2 Decentralization has also allowed local politics to flourish and triggered the emergence of a score of such politicians throughout Indonesia, and especially out of Java. Ganjar Pranowo and \uc2 Anies Baswedan\uc2 , two presidential candidates in the 2024 general election, are a case in point. Barring a major external war or a natural catastrophe of unfathomable severity, the possibility of a recentralized military government in Indonesia is almost nonexistent.\par \par \uc2 Second, the level of political and social violence has declined sharply in the democratic era. This was especially true in the first decade following the 1999 elections. The ending of separatist wars in Aceh, the independence of Timor-Leste, the dampening of religious conflicts in Sulawesi and the partition of Papua have all contributed to this impressive result. The greater mobility within the archipelago driven by rapid urbanization and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth have helped to maintain Indonesia's low level of social conflict.\par \par \uc2 Third, there is the impact of Indonesia's urbanization and the rapid rise of its consuming class or middle class. According to \uc2 World Bank\uc2  data, the Indonesian middle class has grown at 12 percent per year since 2002, well above the growth of real GDP. Indonesia's traditional rural \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is being transformed before our eyes into a land of towns and cities.\par \par \uc2 This is transforming both its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social landscape. On the one hand, it is fueling the emergence of an Indonesian-integrated domestic market. Such an integration is triggered by the sustained efforts at physical connectivity through inter-urban airports, highways, bridges and railways. Indonesia's fast-growing middle class is also young and mobile. It has no personal experience of the New Order government or military folklore. It is used to civil society, social media, instant communication and cashless transactions.\par \par \uc2 President-elect Prabowo is surely right when he says that the nature of Indonesian politics has changed beyond recognition. Democracy is here to stay, although much needs to be reformed and rationalized. There are no fiery speeches about the suppression of a given minority, ? la Myanmar or the need to restore national order or freedom of movement as in Hong Kong or to deliver the country from bitter factional strife as in Thailand or indeed the need to keep fiery Mullahs and religious extremism at bay as in Egypt and elsewhere.\par \par \uc2 Prabowo and others are surely right when they see nationalism in Indonesia today not in terms of military takeovers and autocratic rule but in terms of finding ways to accelerate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. It is the time to eradicate the scourge of absolute poverty from its most far-flung village, to promote business start-ups and to provide universal health care and high-quality education.\par \par \uc2 The cuddly grandpa's school meal program for all of Indonesia is just what many international organizations have recommended for decades. Is this such a long way from the idea of universal health care or an increase in education \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 ?\par \par \uc2 It is also true that a precondition for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth as well as democratic consolidation is national security and domestic peace, as the painful experience of numerous countries in Africa and South America caught in prolonged conflict traps continues to illustrate. Indonesia has a vast, open border across its seas and islands. It has potential areas of conflict in its maritime waterways. We live in a dangerous world of big-power rivalries, unchecked international migration and rogue threats to our cybersecurity and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  infrastructure.\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian Military (TNI) has a critical, new, modernized and professional role to play in the country's next development chapter. It needs secure financing and adequate equipment, technical training and experience in the new world of drones and orbiting satellites. It must also be trained in the practice of democratic government and recognize the limits of its authority.\par \par \uc2 Much needs to be done to make this happen. However, not one instance of an attempted coup d'?tat since the elections of 2000 has occurred here, which is evidence of the political choices of former senior officers of the TNI despite serving as very senior ministers. Governments led by retired four-star generals such as Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono have made it into practice and in the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  eye.\par \par \uc2 Times have indeed changed. Indonesia has changed. The world has changed. It is a period of intense international \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  competition driven by technological prowess. In this \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  world, nationalism must also be reoriented from overthrowing an age-old oppressive colonialism toward the rise of a developed, consolidated, democratic Indonesia by the 100th anniversary of its independence.\par \par \uc2 Prabowo's victory also offers an opportunity to change the mindsets and future expectations of even the most fervent reformasi activists, many of whom are in government. The critical realization is that no democracy has been built in a day. We are talking not in terms of decades but in a century or more. The path to a sustained, consolidated democracy is never a straight line, as the lamentations of European democrats continue to illustrate.\par \par \uc2 Indonesian democracy has succeeded in a world of weakening or failing democratic government. Its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is growing fast. The fears of a resurgent and violent Islam have come to nothing. Political violence has declined.\par \par \uc2 Prabowo has transformed himself into a "cuddly grandfather". But there is little reasoned argument to show that this is all a front for a ruthless dictator willing and able to bring back a New Order-style government. Moreover, even if there was such a temptation, the structural changes in Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political system make this almost impossible.\par \par \uc2 What is more, besides the experienced grandfather, the young entrepreneur also stands. Prabowo has committed himself time and time again to following in the footsteps of Indonesia's remarkably popular current President. In the wings also stands Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, another two-term, popular, former president--a democrat and a retired four-star general.\par \par \uc2 Democratic Indonesia did not become a launching-off platform for the TNI then. It is not likely to do so under the new, rebranded cuddly grandpa. Grandpas behave differently to the ambitious young. They are more likely to believe in lasting legacies than endless violence. It is time to keep an open mind. Those who believe in democracy must take the risk of practicing it.\par \par \uc2 _____________________\par \par \uc2 The writer is a former senior associate fellow of the Habibie Centre. The views expressed are personal. This is the second of a two-part article.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240324ek3p0000d\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 The Composition of Prabowo\u8217\'20\'19s Cabinet\b0\par\par\uc2 1,245 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 March 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 IN the past three weeks, President \uc2 Joko Widodo\uc2  has been inviting Defense Minister \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  to join every limited cabinet meeting at the State Palace, Jakarta. Jokowi asked his potential successor to familiarize himself with the performance of state ministries and institutions before officially taking over the government on October 20.\par \par \uc2 Gerindra Party Executive Chairman Sufmi Dasco Ahmad confirmed that Prabowo was asked to \u8216\'20\'18intern\u8217\'20\'19 in limited cabinet meetings. The purpose of which is to delve into the internal dynamics of the cabinet and the coordination pattern of the president\u8217\'20\'19s aides, as well as how to mitigate problems. \u8220\'20\'1CThis is more important than forming a transition team,\u8221\'20\'1D said Dasco when contacted by Tempo on Thursday, March 21.\par \par \uc2 The transition team prepares transition from the old head of government to the new president. In 2014, Jokowi formed a transition team led by \uc2 Rini Soemarno\uc2 , the former Industry Minister. Its members, such as \uc2 Anies Baswedan\uc2  and Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P) Secretary-General Hasto Kristiyanto, drew up a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  roadmap to fulfill Jokowi\u8217\'20\'19s campaign promises.\par \par \uc2 Similar to Dasco, National Mandate Party (PAN) Chairman Zulkifli Hasan said that the transition team is not needed because Prabowo has been involved in the government for almost the last five years. \u8220\'20\'1COnce it is done, continue on, and sprint. There is no need to study for a year, making adjustments, it\u8217\'20\'19s unnecessary,\u8221\'20\'1D said Zulkifli after a fast-breaking event with Prabowo at PAN\u8217\'20\'19s office in South Jakarta, March 21.\par \par \uc2 During the 75-day campaign period, Prabowo labeled himself as the successor to Jokowi\u8217\'20\'19s programs. Partnering with Gibran Rakabuming Raka, Prabowo campaigned in many regions, promoting the tagline \u8220\'20\'1Ccontinuity.\u8221\'20\'1D Prabowo promised to continue the development of the Nusantara Capital City (IKN) and the downstreaming of mining, two policies of the Jokowi administration.\par \par \uc2 President \uc2 Joko Widodo\uc2  (left) talks with Defense Minister \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  (right) after the inauguration of a regional road in the southern part of East Java Province in Madiun, March 8. ANTARA/Siswowidodo\par \par \uc2 On March 18, or two days before the \uc2 General Election Commission (KPU)\uc2  declared Prabowo-Gibran the winner of the presidential election with more than 58 percent of the vote, Prabowo visited the IKN project in East Kalimantan. Prabowo interacted with workers and heard reports about the progress of the project in preparation for Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s independence day celebration there.\par \par \uc2 According to Sufmi Dasco Ahmad, Prabowo, who received the title of honorary general from Jokowi on February 28, will soon form a cabinet. Prabowo will involve coalition parties as well as his main backer, Jokowi. \u8220\'20\'1CFor continuity, it is natural for Pak Prabowo to coordinate with Pak Jokowi about the vision of the future cabinet,\u8221\'20\'1D said the Deputy Speaker of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR).\par \par \uc2 When preparing his cabinet, Prabowo visited numerous figures to gather inputs. One of them is a senior figure from the Golkar Party. A leader of a coalition party said that the senior figure who is also an entrepreneur advised Prabowo to increase the number of ministries from 34 to 40. The aim is to accommodate the large coalition that Prabowo has designed.\par \par \uc2 The same source said that one way to do this is to split the existing ministries. For example, splitting the Environment and Forestry Ministry into two, the Forestry Ministry and Environment Ministry. The two institutions were actually separate during President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono\u8217\'20\'19s governance, but was merged by Jokowi in 2014.\par \par \uc2 Prabowo reportedly will also add the number of deputy ministers to accommodate his supporting parties, especially those that failed to meet the parliamentary threshold. There are three Jokowi-supporting parties that did not make it to the DPR, namely the Indonesian People\u8217\'20\'19s Wave (Gelora) Party, the Crescent Star Party (PBB), and the Indonesian Solidarity Party (PSI).\par \par \uc2 Prabowo also received feedback from the Coordinating Minister for Maritime Affairs and Investment \uc2 Luhut Pandjaitan\uc2  in various occasions. A government official in the Palace circle said that Luhut suggested Prabowo to strengthen financial supervision institutions to thoroughly review the planning of various projects.\par \par \uc2 Coordinating Minister for Maritime Affairs and Investment \uc2 Luhut Binsar Pandjaitan\uc2  (left) talks with Defense Minister \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  during a Plenary Cabinet Meeting at the State Palace, Jakarta, February 26. ANTARA/Sigid Kurniawan\par \par \uc2 Luhut also reminded Prabowo that his administration would be facing global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in its early days. Luhut, who is Prabowo\u8217\'20\'19s former superior at the Special Forces Command, advised Prabowo to scrutinize \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies that burden the state\u8217\'20\'19s finances. For example, the development of the IKN and the free lunch program.\par \par \uc2 In February, the \uc2 World Bank\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s Country Director for Indonesia and Timor-Leste, Satu Kahkonen, warned the government about the free lunch program. There are concerns that the program will add to the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  burden. The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  suggested that the government make careful planning regarding the implementation of the program.\par \par \uc2 To Prabowo, Luhut said that the IKN development and the free lunch program should not be rolled out all at once, but rather gradually. The Prabowo-Gibran administration will also have to make adjustments according to the conditions in each region, such as poverty levels, health indexes, and education.\par \par \uc2 Luhut Pandjaitan\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s spokesperson, Jodi Mahardi, did not respond to phone calls and messages from Tempo until Saturday, March 23. Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2  had proposed a free lunch program using school operational assistance funds. Airlangga held a free lunch simulation in Curug, Tangerang Regency, Banten, on February 29.\par \par \uc2 With various inputs received by Prabowo, there is a possibility that the cabinet\u8217\'20\'19s composition will change. A senior official from Prabowo\u8217\'20\'19s coalition party said that the cabinet would include several retired individuals from outside Gerindra. The party will provide some of its ministerial positions to be occupied by professionals.\par \par \uc2 However, Sufmi Dasco Ahmad claimed that his party has not discussed the details of the cabinet plan, including the names of prospective ministers. \u8220\'20\'1CDiscussions will only take place after Idul Fitri (the end of the fasting month),\u8221\'20\'1D said Dasco on Friday, March 22.\par \par \uc2 With a large coalition, consisting of Gerindra, Golkar, PAN, and possibly PDI-P, National Awakening Party (PKB), and the National Democrat (NasDem) Party, Prabowo seeks to strengthen his supporters in the DPR. Chairman of Projo\u8212\'20\'14the group of volunteers that support Jokowi and Prabowo\u8212\'20\'14Budi Arie Setiadi said that Prabowo wants to maintain political stability.\par \par \uc2 Indications of Prabowo embracing parties outside the coalition became more apparent with his visit to NasDem Chairman Surya Paloh at NasDem Tower, Central Jakarta, Friday, March 22. During the meeting, which was attended by officials from both parties, Surya welcomed Prabowo and shook his hands. \u8220\'20\'1CMy friend, you have become president,\u8221\'20\'1D said Surya.\par \par \uc2 According to Budi Arie, Prabowo will not include all parties in the parliament in his cabinet. \u8220\'20\'1CPrabowo said that there must be those outside the government to maintain democracy,\u8221\'20\'1D said the Communication and Informatics Minister to Tempo.\par \par \uc2 An official from the Prabowo-Gibran National Campaign Team said that the pair would share roles. Prabowo is to lead more macro policies while Gibran focuses on micro, small, and medium businesses as well as the creative \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Gibran did not deny reports about the division of roles. He said that he would also provide input to \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  regarding ministerial candidates. \u8220\'20\'1CThere will be time for that,\u8221\'20\'1D said the Mayor of Solo, Monday, March 18.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/03/24/857368/857368_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/03/24/857369/857369_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/03/24/857370/857370_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020240325ek3p00006\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
