\par\par \uc2 FEATURES\par \b \uc2 INDONESIA'S FINANCIAL SYSTEM STAYS STRONG AMID GLOBAL  \highlight22\uc2 UNCERTAINTIES \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 899 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 March 2024\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - Amid \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  still engulfing the world, the United States" inflation rate declined, albeit still far from the preferred two percent rate, exacerbating doubts and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the reduction in the Fed Funds Rate (FFR).\par \par \uc2 The FFR, or the rate at which depository institutions lend money to one another, that is currently high, in the range of 5.25-5.50 percent, is forecast to last at least until the first half of this year.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, geopolitical tensions arising in various regions around the globe have yet to signal any immediate conclusions.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, China"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth had yet to reach the expected level on account of a property crisis and weakening consumption power. This trend will also contribute to the slowing down of the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and threaten the stability of the global financial system.\par \par \uc2 Amid global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Indonesia"s financial system remains resilient and stable. This financial resilience is reflected in several aspects, including adequate liquidity, decreasing credit risks, potent capital, and a sound level of corporate resilience.\par \par \uc2 In 2023, Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  stood strong despite facing threats posed by global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown and rising global inflationary pressure, as evidenced by the country"s success in achieving an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth rate of 5.05 percent.\par \par \uc2 This feat was a result of the intensification of government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the end of the year as well as the acceleration of the development of several national strategic projects.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, Indonesia"s ratio of non-performing loans was capped at 2.19 percent as of December 2023, a decline of 2.44 percent as compared to the previous year.\par \par \uc2 In the household sector, the credit risk has been maintained at a good level owing to \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentive policies and increased income that led to a stable debt service ratio (DSR), which reflects solid repayment capacity.\par \par \uc2 Despite the favorable trend, banks continued to strengthen risk mitigation by setting impairment loss \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  and capital adequacy ratio at relatively high levels.\par \par \uc2 According to Deputy Governor of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  Juda Agung, the growth of banking credits in Indonesia has continued to show progress.\par \par \uc2 In February 2024, the growth stood at 11.28 percent year-on-year (yoy) owing to positive trends in the availability of banking liquidity and credit demands from business entities as well as a preferred ratio of liquid assets to third-party funds of 27.41 percent.\par \par \uc2 Liquid assets, including state securities and rupiah securities of BI, could serve as resources of liquidity in credit transactions.\par \par \uc2 Amid global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Indonesia"s credit growth this year is projected to lie in the range of 10-12 percent alongside the normalizing growth of third-party funds and adequate banking liquidity.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, the resilience of non-bank financial institutions, such as financing companies, lending financial technology (fintech) companies, pawnshops, and venture capitals is well maintained, as reflected in the good conditions of capital and well-controlled financing risks.\par \par \uc2 In addition, insurance and pension funds have continued to demonstrate positive performance, while the potential of spillover risk from non-bank financial institutions to banks is relatively low.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, corporate resilience has been sustained by well-maintained repayment capacity and debt at risk (DaR) ratio as well as the improving probability of default (PD).\par \par \uc2 Indonesia"s success in keeping its financial system stable is also supported by payment system policies, the deepening of the money market, as well as \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 "s initiative to promote inclusive and green economies through \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  mixes.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been consistently mixing monetary policies and macroprudential policies to maintain stability in tandem with stimulating \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 "s \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  mixes are backed by innovation, synergy, and coordination between the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the government, related authorities, and strategic partners.\par \par \uc2 Hopes for continued growth\par \par \uc2 The prolonged tightening monetary policies of major \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  powers and high inflation rates have become challenges to central banks around the globe.\par \par \uc2 Under these conditions, the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is projected to grow at a modest rate of just three percent this year. Meanwhile, Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to continue to record positive performances, with the growth rate reaching 4.7-5.5 percent.\par \par \uc2 The increasing expectation of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, well-controlled inflation, conducive \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and ongoing development of national strategic projects have given rise to optimism about the continued growth of credits in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 As financial intermediary institutions, banks are expected to remain resilient, supported by low credit risks and strong capital.\par \par \uc2 In terms of demands, corporate financing will continue to rise along with better prospects of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Additionally, resilient household consumption will contribute to an increase in consumer credit demands.\par \par \uc2 Speaking of an inclusive \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , credits involving micro, small, and medium enterprises (MSMEs) will grow alongside the improved performance of such enterprises and the continuation of the People"s Business Credit (KUR) Program in 2024.\par \par \uc2 The projected positive trends, in turn, will stimulate credit growth to reach 10-12 percent this year and 11-13 percent in 2025.\par \par \uc2 Improved performances of financial intermediary institutions will help Indonesia navigate ongoing global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , keeping its financial system stable and resilient.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia"s capability of maintaining its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth will affirm that all policies and instruments devised are instrumental in protecting the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from negative trends at the global level.\par \par \uc2 (T.KR-TEG/B/A075/A075) 28-03-2024 16:38:10\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020240328ek3s000xd\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Rupiah\u8217\'20\'19s Decline: The Fed Is Not the Only Culprit\b0\par\par\uc2 672 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 March 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 RECENTLY, the value of the rupiah has been plummeting quite sharply, nearing Rp15,900 per United States dollar. Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  now appears vulnerable as global financial market roil. This is in contrast to the situation just last year, when Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s financial markets remained relatively resilient amidst various market upheavals.\par \par \uc2 External shocks indeed continue to be the primary driver of the decline of the rupiah. This is mainly attributed to the strengthening of the US dollar, fueled by growing speculation that the \uc2 Federal Reserve\uc2  may postpone interest rate cuts, contrary to the widespread anticipation of financial markets worldwide for months.\par \par \uc2 This shift in \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  direction underscores the nature of market movements. If the Fed\u8217\'20\'19s rates remain high, the US dollar will strengthen, leading to the weakening of currencies around the world. This trend is evident in the Dollar Index, which has risen from 102.36 to 104.357 in the past month. The fluctuations in this index reflect the strength of the US dollar against the six major world currencies.\par \par \uc2 The current strengthening of the US dollar is particularly evident in Asia. For instance, the value of the Malaysian ringgit has fallen to around 4.7 ringgit per US dollar, nearing its lowest point since the 1998 crisis. Similarly, Japan, one of Asia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  giants, is facing significant pressure, with the yen plummeting to its lowest level in 34 years, nearing \u165\'00\'A5152 per US dollar.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, as of Thursday, March 28, the value of the rupiah has already declined by nearly three percent year to date. Without aggressive intervention from \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2 , there is a high possibility that the rupiah\u8217\'20\'19s exchange rate would have exceeded the psychological barrier of Rp16,000 per US dollar.\par \par \uc2 The pressure on the rupiah appears set to persist in the coming weeks. \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  must be prepared to deplete foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  to maintain market stability and support the rupiah. Moreover, BI may need to contemplate raising benchmark \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  if the situation deteriorates further. The escalating pressure on the rupiah stems from various factors beyond the Fed\u8217\'20\'19s rate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  direction.\par \par \uc2 One of these factors is the progressively diminishing trade balance surplus, which could potentially turn into a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This situation poses a risk for Indonesia, as it may lead to a significant reduction in foreign exchange supply. This scenario underscores a fundamental \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  principle: the equilibrium between supply and demand determines prices. If the supply of dollars from export earnings decreases, the price of the dollar, or its exchange rate against the rupiah, will automatically rise.\par \par \uc2 The equilibrium point of onshore dollar liquidity will also shift due to imminent seasonal factors: the repatriation of dividends and the repayment of foreign debts in April-May. The increased demand for dollars to be sent abroad will undoubtedly shift the equilibrium in the market. This tightening of domestic forex liquidity will automatically lead to an increase in the US dollar exchange rate.\par \par \uc2 Another crucial yet difficult-to-quantify factor is the negative sentiment stemming from political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  ahead of the national leadership succession. The Constitutional Court is currently adjudicating disputes over the results of the general elections, contesting \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s victory in the presidential election.\par \par \uc2 Even if the Court eventually rejects these claims, the market still harbors concerns about Prabowo\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  direction if he were to become president, particularly regarding the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Investors remain skeptical that Prabowo will abandon his plans to increase government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to finance various populist programs. This could significantly widen the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  and pose a threat to government finances, presenting significant risks for bondholders.\par \par \uc2 This is also a push factor for foreign investors to sell government bonds in droves. Since the quick count results showed Prabowo as the winner of the presidential election until March 27, foreign investors have net sold government bonds worth Rp32.62 trillion. If this trend continues, the rupiah\u8217\'20\'19s exchange rate could plummet even further.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/03/31/857876/857876_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020240401ek3u0000e\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
