\par\par \b \uc2 The monetary policies needed for a challenging year\b0\par\par\uc2 910 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 April 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Abraham Wahyu Nugroho , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 In the current \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , central banks around the world are pursuing various contemporary and innovative policies. The main goal is to keep the pulse of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  beating steadily amid challenging conditions.\par \par \uc2 Likewise, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  has endeavored to ensure that the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grows sustainably throughout the year, not only in quantity but also in quality.\par \par \uc2 So, what strategies and steps will BI take this year in its monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  so the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues to thrive? This article tries to summarize what policies will be adopted this year and to take a glimpse at \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  progress.\par \par \uc2 In general, the 2024 monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not much different from before, but there are improvements. BI will continue a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  mix in which the monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is directed at \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stabilization (pro-stability) while other policies (macroprudential, payment system, money market deepening and financial inclusion) are directed at spurring growth (pro-growth).\par \par \uc2 Regarding pro-stability, the main problems from last year seem to be continuing today, such as geopolitical fragmentation. This situation will certainly continue to increase global prices for energy and food and disrupt world trade volumes. As a result, the central banks of developed countries must pay a high price to tame inflation, one way of which is to raise the benchmark interest rate. This is no exception in emerging markets, such as Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 During 2023, BI gradually increased its benchmark rate to control the consumer price index (CPI), as inflation remained high. BI increased its rate last October to 6 percent, which has been maintained until March 2024, to offset the pressure of exchange rate volatility on the rupiah due to global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and of course, imported inflation.\par \par \uc2 The government, along with BI, set inflation in line with the specified corridor of 3 percent plus/minus 1 percent in 2023 and 2.5 percent plus/minus 1 percent in 2024 and 2025.\par \par \uc2 Even though Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is improving, the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still filled with \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The motors of advanced economies such as China, England and Japan are slackening.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 United States Federal Reserve\uc2  is expected to decrease its interest rate only in the second half of 2024 due to inflation, which has not yet subsided. As a result, the US dollar has strengthened globally, disrupting foreign capital inflows and further weakening the exchange rates in emerging markets.\par \par \uc2 This situation is certainly on BI's radar as it assesses the developments, prospects and risks of both the global and domestic economies. The formulation of future reference rates of course aims for optimal results by considering the variables of inflation and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, rupiah stabilization and capital flow management.\par \par \uc2 However, what is certain is that throughout this year, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue to calibrate its interest rate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in a measurable (well-calibrated), well-planned and transparent (well-communicated) manner.\par \par \uc2 Complementing the benchmark rate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , BI created a pro-market innovation last year, namely the issuance of securities instruments to support inflation control and exchange rate stability. These instruments include \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Rupiah Securities (SRBI), \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Foreign Currency Securities (SVBI) and \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Foreign Currency Sukuk (SUVBI).\par \par \uc2 Judging from progressive developments, the SRBI, SVBI and SUVBI all appear to be appreciating in the market. As of March 19, 2024, the three instruments had respectively reached Rp 409.38 trillion (US$25.75 billion), $2.31 billion and $387 million.\par \par \uc2 Just as life can sometimes go up, be static, or even go down, the same can happen with the financial and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  cycles.\par \par \uc2 BI projects that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  cycle will boom in the 2025-2026 period, followed by a financial cycle boom in 2026-2027. To prepare for this, the central has taken a loose macroprudential \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  stance (pro-growth) since last year by optimizing bank credit distribution to priority sectors (downstreaming), micro, small and medium enterprises (MSMEs) and sustainable sectors through incentive schemes.\par \par \uc2 Here, the role of central banks everywhere is to create policies that are countercyclical or which balance the financial and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  cycles. When the cycles are in a downturn, macroprudential \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be encouraged. On the other hand, when the cycles are at their peak, such as in 2025, macroprudential \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be tightened.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, this year is the right timing for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  actors, for example the banking industry, to boost credit or financing through existing incentives.\par \par \uc2 These include the Macroprudential Liquidity Incentive \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  (KLM) and a reduction in the Macroprudential Liquidity Buffer (PLM) ratio. This \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  essentially seeks to encourage more optimal credit or financing while maintaining liquidity of the banking sector.\par \par \uc2 Data as of December 2023 showed that KLM realization reached Rp 163 trillion, while PLM has increased liquidity by Rp 81 trillion. It is forecast that macroprudential easing will encourage credit or financing growth of 10-12 percent in 2024 and 11-13 percent in 2025, provided that financial system stability is maintained.\par \par \uc2 In conclusion, future pro-stability policies in the form of accommodative \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , macroprudential easing and a pro-growth payment system are believed to be the driving force for monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Indeed, hard work is needed from all stakeholders for Indonesia to become a high-income country. It will not be absurd, however, if all macroeconomic indicators and achievements are met. The condition is that both the domestic and global economies are also mutually conducive.\par \par \uc2 _____________________\par \par \uc2 Analyst at \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The views expressed are personal.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240331ek410000f\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
