\par\par \uc2 BUSSINESS\par \b \uc2 E ASIA, PACIFIC REGIONS NEED INFRASTRUCTURE, EDUCATION REFORM: WB\b0\par\par\uc2 450 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 April 2024\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Cindy Frishanti Octavia\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - The World Bankadvised developing countries in East Asia and the Pacific regions to reform their infrastructure and education systems to revitalize their \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  amid global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  turmoil.\par \par \uc2 Developing countries in East Asia and the Pacific include Indonesia, Cambodia, China, Laos, Malaysia, Mongolia, Myanmar, Papua New Guinea, the Philippines, Thailand, Timor-Leste, Vietnam, and Pacific Island countries.\par \par \uc2 "Bold policies to unleash competition, improve infrastructure, and reform education can revitalize the region"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," \uc2 World Bank\uc2  chief economist for East Asia and the Pacific, \uc2 Aaditya Mattoo\uc2 , said on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 He made the statement at the launch of the East Asia and Pacific \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Update report, which was followed online from Jakarta.\par \par \uc2 In its report, the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  noted that the per capita income in the East Asia and Pacific region has shown faster growth compared to developing countries in other regions.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in developing countries in East Asia and the Pacific, excluding China, is projected to increase to 4.6 percent this year from 4.4 percent in 2023.\par \par \uc2 However, this outlook is still faced with a number of challenges, such as a larger-than-expected global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown, rising long-term \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in major countries, increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  around the world, and rising geopolitical tensions.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the East Asia and Pacific region is driven more by investment than productivity growth.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  has recommended that countries in the region focus on efforts to encourage increased productivity.\par \par \uc2 Indonesian minister of finance for 2013\u8211\'20\'132014, Chatib Basri, agreed with the recommendation. According to him, one of the challenges to keeping Indonesia"s growth relatively stable at 5 percent is that the level of productivity is still relatively low.\par \par \uc2 He argued that one of the policies that the Indonesian government needs to take to achieve \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 6\u8211\'20\'137 percent is to encourage productivity by increasing human resource (HR) and infrastructure development as well as strengthening good governance.\par \par \uc2 On a separate occasion, Minister of FinanceSri Mulyani Indrawatisaid that the 2024 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  (APBN) is focused on supporting inclusive and sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  transformation toward a developed Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 The strategy includes a commitment to building a foundation for quality human resources, infrastructure, and other reforms.\par \par \uc2 Efforts to improve the quality of human resources are being realized through the allocation of education funds amounting to Rp660.8 trillion (US$41.6 billion) and a health \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp187.5 trillion (US$11.8 billion) in the 2024 APBN. Meanwhile, the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  allocation for infrastructure is Rp422.7 trillion (US$26.6 billion).\par \par \uc2 (T.C009/A/Y012/Y012) 04-04-2024 18:00:25\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020240404ek440012x\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict