\par\par \b \uc2 ADB\uc2  Forecasts 4.9 Percent Growth in Asia-Pacific\b0\par\par\uc2 305 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 April 2024\par \uc2 Tempo.co\par \uc2 TEMPOE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk \par \par \uc2 TEMPO.CO, Jakarta - The \uc2 Asian Development Bank\uc2  (\uc2 ADB\uc2 ) forecasts that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the Asia-Pacific region will reach an average of 4.9 percent in 2024. This growth is supported by strong domestic demand, improved semiconductor exports, and the recovery of the tourism industry.\par \par \uc2 "We believe that growth in the majority of developing economies in Asia will stabilize this year and next," said \uc2 ADB\uc2  Chief Economist Albert Park in the Asian Development Outlook (ADO) April 2024 report released in Jakarta on Thursday, April 11, 2024, as quoted by Antara.\par \par \uc2 ADB\uc2  also predicts that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth next year will be around the same level as this year.\par \par \uc2 Albert stated that stronger growth in South and Southeast Asia is driven by domestic demand and exports. This offsets the slowdown in China due to property market downturns and weak consumption.\par \par \uc2 India is projected to remain a key growth engine in Asia and the Pacific, with growth of 7 percent in 2024 and 7.2 percent in 2025. Meanwhile, China's growth is expected to slow to 4.8 percent this year and 4.5 percent next year, from 5.2 percent last year.\par \par \uc2 "Consumer confidence continues to improve, and overall investment remains strong. External demand also appears to have turned positive, especially in the semiconductor sector," said Albert.\par \par \uc2 However, policymakers should remain cautious as there are still several risks. These risks include supply chain disruptions, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about US monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , extreme weather effects, and the continued weakening of the property market in China.\par \par \uc2 Regarding inflation, \uc2 ADB\uc2  predicts that it will ease in 2024 and 2025, after being boosted by rising food prices in various economies over the past two years.\par \par \uc2 ANTARA\par \par \uc2 Click here to get the latest news updates from Tempo in Google News\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://statik.tempo.co/data/2022/11/30/id_1161567/1161567_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMPOE0020240411ek4b0005m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
