\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Geopolitical strife and commodity volatility: Inflation impact?\b0\par\par\uc2 983 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 April 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Shahifa Assajjadiyyah, Mandiri, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The world has once again witnessed rising geopolitical conflict this year. A clash between Iran and Israel broke out as Iran launched a massive aerial attack on Israel in response to a previous deadly Israeli strike on an Iranian consulate in Syria that killed at least 13 people.\par \par \uc2 As a result, the price of Brent crude oil experienced significant fluctuations, reaching US$89.55 per barrel at the close of trading on Monday.\par \par \uc2 This represents a year-to-date (ytd) increase of 17.2 percent, nearly touching 2022's peak of $92.31 per barrel during the ongoing Russia-Ukraine war.\par \par \uc2 Consequently, this year, global logistics costs are seen to escalate amid higher oil prices and disrupted shipping routes.\par \par \uc2 The price of gold and the United States dollar have also increased as investors flee to safe-haven assets amid increased \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 This will certainly have an impact on the domestic financial market. The rupiah is already under pressure from persistently high US inflation, which has led to widespread expectations that the \uc2 US Federal Reserve\uc2  will not immediately implement a rate cut.\par \par \uc2 Given the latest tensions between Iran and Israel, the rupiah could be lower in value for longer, potentially threatening our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  through higher imported inflation.\par \par \uc2 The rising global oil prices could also directly impact domestic inflation through potentially higher fuel oil (BBM) costs.\par \par \uc2 The global oil price has surpassed the government's assumed price for 2024, which was only $82 per barrel. If the price remains persistently above this assumption, there will be risks of escalated subsidized domestic fuel prices.\par \par \uc2 Based on our calculations, every 1 percent increase in world crude oil prices above the government's assumptions will cause a 0.27 percentage point increase in the price of Pertalite per liter if the government does not roll out any \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  or compensation. Hence, to prevent the rise in subsidized fuel oil prices, \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will play a crucial role.\par \par \uc2 Energy \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  need to be implemented wisely, especially considering that in mid-March, the government had a \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  surplus of 0.10 percent of gross domestic product (GDP), lower than the surplus in the same period last year of 0.59 percent of GDP.\par \par \uc2 On April 1, Statistics Indonesia (BPS) announced that Indonesia's inflation had increased to 3.05 percent year-on-year during March 2024, higher than the previous month's inflation rate of 2.75 percent year-on-year.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, on a monthly basis, the country's inflation was recorded at 0.52 percent month-on-month, which is also significantly higher than the 0.37 percent recorded in February.\par \par \uc2 Several factors contributed to this increase in inflation, one of which was the seasonal factor, where overall prices tended to rise during Ramadan, especially for food commodities such as chicken, beef and other staples like rice.\par \par \uc2 Compared to seasonal patterns in previous years, inflation in March was still relatively moderate. Based on our database, inflation preceding the Idul Fitri celebrations usually ranged from 0.7 percent to 0.9 percent month-on-month from 2010 to 2019.\par \par \uc2 However, the inflation rate in March almost reached the upper inflation limit of 3.5 percent\par \par \uc2 set by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  for this year.\par \par \uc2 The persistent increase in inflation seems to have begun to impact \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  consumption, particularly among the lower-middle class. Our Mandiri \b \highlight22\uc2 Spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  Index indicates that \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  among the lower income group is slowing down faster than among other groups (middle and upper income), possibly due to the relatively high prices of staple foods, including rice.\par \par \uc2 Considering that El Ni?o is expected to subside only in May to July 2024, the government's role once again remains crucial in providing assistance to the lower-middle class in the form of social assistance or food aid.\par \par \uc2 Fortunately, the government has allocated a higher \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for holiday allowances (THR) compared to the previous year, which stimulated \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  consumption during the month of Ramadan.\par \par \uc2 For this year, the government budgeted Rp 38.9 trillion ($2.39 billion) for THR, marking a 13.4 percent increase from the Rp 34.3 trillion allocated in 2023.\par \par \uc2 In accordance with this increase, data from the Mandiri Institute shows that aggregate \b \highlight22\uc2 public spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  patterns during Ramadan this year have increased by 6.5 percent compared to the pre-Ramadan period, surpassing the 5.4 percent increase observed in 2023.\par \par \uc2 However, it is undeniable that the high prices of staple foods still have implications for the lower class.\par \par \uc2 Amid many gloomy outlooks, there are still potential positive catalysts for domestic inflation. The price of rice has shown flattening growth, supported by the fulfillment of rice supplies through imports and improving domestic production amid the easing of El Ni?o.\par \par \uc2 The Meteorology, Climatology and Geophysics Agency (BMKG) predicts that El Ni?o will become neutral from May to July 2024. Looking ahead, the government needs to ensure that inflation is maintained within BI's target range to preserve people's purchasing power.\par \par \uc2 To achieve this, the government plans to implement various measures, including the realization of rice import quotas, stabilization of food supply and prices (SPHP) and the provision of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  and fertilizer discounts to maintain food availability.\par \par \uc2 Rice imports in 2024 may reach 4.1 million tonnes to ensure stock availability, with SPHP rice distribution capped at a maximum of 200,000 tonnes per month until March 2024.\par \par \uc2 Additionally, fertilizer \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  totaling Rp 14 trillion will be allocated for a total of 9.55 million tonnes of fertilizer in 2024, along with preparations to provide a 40 percent discount for non-subsidized fertilizer\par \par \uc2 Overall, we expect Indonesia's inflation to reach around 3.2 percent year-on-year by the end of 2024 with some upward bias, compared to the 2.61 percent year-on-year realization in 2023.\par \par \uc2 ___________________\par \par \uc2 Economist at \uc2 Bank Mandiri\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240416ek4h0000e\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
