\par\par \b \uc2 New leader, same old Singapore\b0\par\par\uc2 655 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 April 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post,\par \par \uc2 When he officially takes the helm of Singapore on May 15, Lawrence Wong will owe a debt to his predecessor \uc2 Lee Hsien Loong\uc2 , the outgoing prime minister, and the country's two previous leaders, who have all played a part in transforming Singapore into one of the world's most advanced nations.\par \par \uc2 About five months later, president-elect \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  will likely join Wong as a new leader of an ASEAN member state when he takes over from President \uc2 Joko "Jokowi" Widodo\uc2 . Along with other regional leaders, Wong and Prabowo will navigate ASEAN through regional and global turmoil.\par \par \uc2 Lee announced his resignation on Monday afternoon. The 72-year-old prime minister has held the post for 20 years, since 2004, after serving as deputy prime minister under Singapore's second prime minister, Goh Chok Tong, for 14 years. Lee is the eldest son of Singapore's first prime minister and founding father \uc2 Lee Kuan Yew\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 General Elections Commission (KPU)\uc2  declared Prabowo, 72, and his running mate Gibran Rakabuming Raka the winners of the Feb. 14 presidential election, but their rivals are now challenging the outcome at the Constitutional Court. The final and binding decision will be issued on Monday.\par \par \uc2 Despite their big age gap, Prabowo and Wong have already built a good personal relationship. In June of last year, Wong met with Prabowo, as well as other presidential aspirants \uc2 Anies Baswedan\uc2  and Ganjar Pranowo, during a visit to Jakarta.\par \par \uc2 During his campaign, Prabowo expressed an intention to play a more global role while sticking with ASEAN as his foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  base.\par \par \uc2 At the bilateral level, both Indonesia and Singapore have maintained good neighborhood relations. As both Wong and Prabowo have committed themselves to continuing the policies of their predecessors, there will be no meaningful hurdles in the future relationship between the two neighbors. As ASEAN leaders, the two are also expected to work closely with other regional leaders in addressing the global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  and tensions affecting the regional grouping.\par \par \uc2 ASEAN, like other regions, is feeling the pinch of global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and military turbulence, including soaring oil and commodities prices resulting from the wars in the Middle East and Ukraine.\par \par \uc2 The escalating tension between China and the United States, along with its allies in the Indo-Pacific, notably on the South China Sea and the Taiwan Strait, has also put ASEAN in a challenging position. China is the most important trading and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  partner for all members of ASEAN, while the US is needed to counterbalance China's domination.\par \par \uc2 China claims nearly the entire South China Sea, putting it in territorial disputes with ASEAN members Vietnam, Malaysia, Brunei and the Philippines. Under President \uc2 Ferdinand Marcos Jr\uc2 , the Philippines has decided to move closer to the US as China is becoming more assertive in its claim over the resource-rich South China Sea.\par \par \uc2 While the Singapore-Indonesia relationship will remain largely the same after the change of guard, hopes are high that Wong will help make a difference in the way ASEAN tackles both internal challenges and external threats.\par \par \uc2 One pending issue facing ASEAN is the Myanmar crisis. ASEAN has gradually isolated the Myanmar military junta by preventing it from representing the country at official ASEAN gatherings in response to its refusal to comply with the bloc's Five-Point Consensus, a road map to bring democracy back to the country.\par \par \uc2 Armed conflict between pro-democracy groups and the military junta shows no sign of ending, at the expense of the people of Myanmar. The country looks likely to remain a headache for the region in the future.\par \par \uc2 At 51, Wong is expected to have a more persuasive approach than other ASEAN leaders, most of whom are older than him, and to be more willing to explore mutually beneficial relationships with the neighbors.\par \par \uc2 Amid the current and future challenges, ASEAN will be looking forward to Wong's contribution.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240417ek4i00007\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
