\par\par \b \uc2 Fed, geopolitics may push rupiah to historic low\b0\par\par\uc2 Deni Ghifari, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 528 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 April 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The rupiah has been on a downward slope in the past week amid \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about United States monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and geopolitical conflicts. Analysts do not rule out a historic low for Indonesia's currency.\par \par \uc2 Financial market analyst Ariston Tjendra says there was"a possibility" of the rupiah touching or breaching the historic low of Rp 16,950 to the US dollar, given "how close it is now" to that level.\par \par \uc2 The national currency stooped to that exchange value back in 1998, when the archipelago experienced a monetary crisis that left an imprint on the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 In this century, the rupiah came closest to the 1998 nadir in March 2020, when the pandemic shook the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and pushed the currency down to Rp 16,640 per dollar.\par \par \uc2 Not far from that level, the rupiah touched a multiyear low of Rp 16,340 against the greenback on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 The depreciation was fueled by two big global events, namely the \uc2 US Federal Reserve\uc2  signaling it wouldkeep its key \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  higher for longer and geopolitical tension exacerbated most recently by attacks between Iran and Israel, Ariston told The Jakarta Post on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 Hawkish Fed\par \par \uc2 After assessing recent macroeconomic data on inflation, job growth and retail \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , all of which veeredfrom expectations, the Fed has signaled that its restrictive monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  needs to be maintained longer.\par \par \uc2 "Given the strength of the labor market and progress on inflation so far, it is appropriate to allow restrictive \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  further time to work and let the data and the evolving outlook guide us," Fed Chairman \uc2 Jerome Powell\uc2  said in Washington, DC, on Tuesday. Market actors had been expecting a Fed rate cut in June, but the Fed's hawkish signals have pushed that back to September, at the earliest.\par \par \uc2 David Sumual, chief economist at Indonesian lender BCA, told the Post on Wednesday that "it is even possible to be pushed back to next year".\par \par \uc2 Dashed hoped for sooner cuts prompted investors to hold onto or buy more dollar assets, pushing up the dollar index that measures the greenback versus six other currencies.\par \par \uc2 The greenback's appreciation also reflected in its value vis-?-vis Indonesia's currency.\par \par \uc2 Coordinating \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister \uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2  pointed out in a press conference on Tuesday that the rupiah was holding up better than the currencies of Malaysia and China but worse than those of South Korea and Thailand, adding: "We are strongly affected, but a lot of other countries are more strongly affected."\par \par \uc2 BCA's David said the rupiah had been "overvalued" in the year's first months, given that it had only weakened slightly, while some currencies had dropped 10 percent against the dollar.\par \par \uc2 Its most recent drop, however, meant the rupiah's valuation was now more reflective of its true value, David opined.\par \par \uc2 On Wednesday evening, the rupiah was down around 5.65 percent against the dollar year-to-date (ytd), while the dollar index had strengthened 4.84 percent ytd.\par \par \uc2 Concurring with Ariston, David said an "overshoot" of the rupiah down to a new low was plausible.\par \par \uc2 Continued on page 11\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240417ek4i0000