\par\par \b \uc2 BRI records Rp 15.98 trillion in profit, focuses more on domestic challenges through empowering SMEs\b0\par\par\uc2 613 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 April 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post,\par \par \uc2 Amid dynamic global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and geopolitical challenges, \uc2 PT Bank Rakyat Indonesia\uc2  (Persero) (BRI) has achieved positive profit growth, with consolidated profits reaching Rp 15.98 trillion as of the end of the first quarter of this year. This was revealed by BRI president director Sunarso during a financial performance press conference for the first quarter in Jakarta on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 Sunarso said the company would continue to monitor global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  developments while simultaneously focusing more on domestic challenges.\par \par \uc2 "Currently, the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation is highly \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the \uc2 Federal Reserve\uc2  is expected to maintain its benchmark \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  at a high level for a longer period to curb inflation in the United States. On the other hand, escalating geopolitical tensions in the Middle East have led investors to shift their assets to safe havens, thus putting pressure on the exchange rate of the rupiah against the dollar and the [\uc2 Indonesia Stock Exchange\uc2  (IDX) Composite]," explained Sunarso.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, Sunarso remained optimistic about BRI's future performance and said the bank would concentrate more on domestic challenges.\par \par \uc2 "The company sees the current national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions as resilient to global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability, and BRI is committed to supporting government programs that promote domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth," added Sunarso.\par \par \uc2 One of BRI's commitments to supporting national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is by continuing to promote job creation, especially in the SME segment through quality credit disbursements.\par \par \uc2 As of the end of March of this year, BRI successfully disbursed credit totaling Rp 1,308.65 trillion, representing a double-digit growth of 10.89 percent year on year (yoy). Of these credit disbursements, 83.25 percent or Rp 1,089.41 trillion was allocated to the SME segment. This double-digit credit growth has led to an increase in the company's assets, with BRI's assets reaching Rp 1,989.07 trillion, growing 9.11 percent yoy.\par \par \uc2 "BRI believes that the continuous empowerment of the SME segment contributes to national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  resilience, considering that SMEs account for approximately 97 percent of job creation in Indonesia and contribute around 61 percent to the GDP," explained Sunarso.\par \par \uc2 All of BRI's loan segments recorded positive growth. The micro segment grew by 10.51 percent yoy to Rp 622.61 trillion, the consumer segment grew by 11.62 percent yoy to Rp 193.96 trillion, the small and medium segment grew by 8.06 percent yoy to Rp 272.85 trillion and the corporate segment grew by 15.10 percent year on year to Rp 219.24 trillion.\par \par \uc2 Despite achieving double-digit credit growth, BRI has managed to maintain the quality of its credit disbursements. By the end of the first quarter of 2024, BRI's non-performing loan (NPL) ratio was controlled at around 3.11 percent, with an improved loan at risk (LAR) ratio, decreasing from 16.39 percent at the end of the first quarter of 2023 to 12.70 percent at the end of the first quarter of 2024.\par \par \uc2 "As the bank with the largest portfolio in the SME segment, the 3 percent NPL ratio is evidence that BRI has effectively managed its credit quality through prudent risk management principles," Sunarso added.\par \par \uc2 In terms of liabilities, the company managed to gather third-party funds (DPK) of Rp 1,416.21 trillion, growing 12.80 percent yoy as of the end of March. Low-cost funds (Current Account Savings Account [CASA]) still dominate the savings portfolio with 7.80 percent yoy growth. This CASA growth is attributed to BRI's aspiration to transform liabilities by strengthening funding bases focusing on sta\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240425ek4q00005\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
