\par\par \b \uc2 A reckoning on Indonesia's foreign  \highlight22\uc2 policy \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 1,234 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 April 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Teuku Faizasyah , Oslo\par \par \uc2 Traveling by car from Oslo to Bergen one morning last weekend, I was surprised to experience several changes in the weather in a single day. It was as if the Oslo spring was bidding me farewell as birds sang and the heat of the sun reminded me of summer, in contrast with the snow-capped mountains in view, reminding me of winter days past, and as we finally approached Bergen, autumn-like rain welcomed us.\par \par \uc2 Recalling Vivaldi's best-known work The Four Seasons, I could not help but think of the Indonesian proverb "sedia payung sebelum hujan" (ready an umbrella before rain), which advises preparing ahead in anticipation of future \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 In the global arena lately, we continue juggling amid many \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , from boiling tensions in the Middle East to power games between major powers, and to the prospects of a slowdown in the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Six months before a new government is established under president-elect \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2 , a process of reckoning is already underway on, I assume, the possible impact of global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Perhaps these efforts involve those tasked with overseeing the transition between the current and next government.\par \par \uc2 Speaking on the correlation between international and domestic issues, referred to as "intermestic" by former foreign minister Hassan Wirajuda, I recall Dino Patti Djalal's opinion piece published on April 17 in The Jakarta Post. In it, he outlines four major agendas or rather, what I would call four major \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  challenges, awaiting president-elect Prabowo.\par \par \uc2 The three agendas Dino highlighted besides foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , namely legal and judicial reform, democracy and the climate, are very much intertwined with Indonesia's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  interests.\par \par \uc2 Suffice it to say, success in tackling the challenges associated with each of these will help Indonesia meet its foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  objectives, particularly regarding \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  diplomacy.\par \par \uc2 Laser-like focus on legal and judicial reform, coupled with a strong determination to eradicate corruption and red tape, will make Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  climate gain more traction among foreign investors.\par \par \uc2 In the meantime, it is important to highlight that the country's diplomats overseas are receiving many queries from their counterparts concerning Indonesia's outlook post-President \uc2 Joko "Jokowi" Widodo\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 These questions range from the most likely political makeup of the next cabinet, prospects for political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability, and whether there will be any shift or changes in Indonesia's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  focus.\par \par \uc2 It is a given that foreign diplomats and \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  analysts based in Jakarta are also conducting similar data gathering to build informed knowledge on the likelihood of the government-in-waiting.\par \par \uc2 In the interests of sharing information and sustaining international confidence in Indonesia, particularly in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sphere, the Indonesian Embassy in Oslo, in collaboration with the \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  representative in London, is holding on May 24 a business forum themed "Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Outlook Post-National Elections 2024".\par \par \uc2 Gaining and sustaining trust and confidence serve as the backbone of Indonesia's diplomacy. Needless to say, the international system will not function well in the absence of\par \par \uc2 trust and confidence, and disorder and chaos would loom large instead, especially nowadays, when we are living in a more fragmented world.\par \par \uc2 Over time, Indonesia has been regarded as a trusted partner by many friendly countries. This was evident when Indonesia received the highest number of votes during the election of \uc2 Human Rights Council\uc2  members in 2023: Indonesia gained 186 "yes" votes from a total of 192 countries.\par \par \uc2 This is in line with the appreciation received from countries friendly to Indonesia as we continue to give our support to various international organizations. So in the case of Indonesia, our words and actions are in sync.\par \par \uc2 In the realm of diplomacy, trust serves as a good currency in generating support for many diplomatic initiatives.\par \par \uc2 Over the past nine years, some of Indonesia's geo-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  as well as geo-strategic initiatives include the Pacific Elevation and Indonesia-Pacific Forum for Development, the Indonesia-Latin America and the Caribbean Business Forum (INA-LAC) and the ASEAN Outlook on the Indo-Pacific (AOIP).\par \par \uc2 The basic premise of those strategic initiatives is to nurture better understanding and trust among nations, as well as to develop concrete cooperation across geographical divides in areas of mutual interest, particularly in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector.\par \par \uc2 These initiatives could serve as a building block for other types of cooperation, including culture and sports, to flourish, thereby bringing people closer.\par \par \uc2 From the geostrategic perspective, the nature of Indonesia's initiatives is a win-win approach that is far removed from a self-centered view to gaining supremacy.\par \par \uc2 On the AOIP, Dino is correct in suggesting that the COVID-19 pandemic is partly responsible for the delay in progress.\par \par \uc2 Yet, I am confident that this delay has not made the initiative obsolete. However, the AOIP must also find its place among other versions of the Indo-Pacific outlook floated by countries within and beyond the region.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, let us not forget that by way of initiating the AOIP, Indonesia intrigued other countries, big and small, to think through their perceptions of the Indo-Pacific for the present and beyond.\par \par \uc2 In a nutshell, from observing the traits of Indonesian diplomacy, especially over the past nine years, I can cautiously say that in the realm of foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2 and diplomacy, the world needs more of Indonesia for at least three reasons.\par \par \uc2 First, as a prominent player in the Global South, Indonesia does not shy away from championing a just cause, such as on the issue of decolonizing Palestine.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia has not been swayed by conditionality for joining the \uc2 Organisation for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Co-operation and Development\uc2  (\uc2 OECD\uc2 ) by opening diplomatic relations with Israel at the expense of a prior resolution to the Palestine cause.\par \par \uc2 Thus, Indonesia is not in the business of transactional diplomacy.\par \par \uc2 Second, Indonesia is a middle power country that has played a leadership role when chairing multilateral forums.\par \par \uc2 When chairing the \uc2 Group of 20\uc2  in 2022 for instance, Indonesia was not dissuaded by major powers attempting to stir and align the G20 agenda with their parochial interests.\par \par \uc2 This is among the reasons the \uc2 Lowy Institute\uc2  categorized Indonesia in 2023 as a middle power showing strong growth in its diplomatic influence.\par \par \uc2 Third, it is a country that is actively promoting solidarity among nations to tackle global issues of common concern, such as poverty and global health.\par \par \uc2 This signature brand of Indonesia led to the appointment of Foreign Minister Retno LP Marsudi as cochair of the COVAX AMC Engagement Group in 2021.\par \par \uc2 The group's responsibility was to decide on the distribution of COVID-19 vaccines among developing countries.\par \par \uc2 As a final note, it would be unfortunate if Indonesia's tangible works in the diplomatic sphere under President Jokowi and the stewardship of foreign minister Retno were underappreciated.\par \par \uc2 As diplomacy operates in a continuum, borrowing the phrase "change and continuity" coined by former foreign minister Marty Natalegawa, it would be fitting for the government-in-waiting to consider continuing all these good works and apply change when necessary.\par \par \uc2 Thus, a measured approach is always best despite global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and we should be careful of being tempted into proposing prescriptive formulas to the next government on what to do in foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and diplomacy. Now, let's replay Vivaldi's masterpiece, The Four Seasons.\par \par \uc2 _____________________\par \par \uc2 Indonesian Ambassador to Norway and Iceland. The views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240426ek4r0000i\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Import Restrictions and Trade Surplus\b0\par\par\uc2 1,159 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 April 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 IRAN\u8217\'20\'19s attack on Israel on April 13, prompted the State-Owned Enterprises Ministry to take special action. According to Frans Marganda Tambunan, Chief Executive Officer (CEO) of \uc2 Rajawali Nusantara Indonesia\uc2  or ID Food, the Ministry ordered a number of state-owned enterprises with high import rates to prepare stress tests or simulation reports to assess their resilience in facing three conditions.\par \par \uc2 Frans explained that companies like ID Food were asked to make simulations to anticipate fluctuations in the rupiah exchange rate, supply issues, price hikes, and logistical disruptions. The order, said Frans, would be discussed at a meeting this week. \u8220\'20\'1CWe were expected to prepare optimistic, moderate, and pessimistic strategies,\u8221\'20\'1D he told Tempo on April 25.\par \par \uc2 The same thing is done by \uc2 Pupuk Kaltim\uc2 , a subsidiary of \uc2 Pupuk Indonesia\uc2 , which is the largest urea fertilizer producer in Indonesia. According to Anggono Wijaya, Vice President of Corporate Communication of \uc2 Pupuk Kaltim\uc2 , the company has learned from the experience of the Russia-Ukraine war that broke out in 2022. At the time, \uc2 Pupuk Kaltim\uc2  faced difficulties in obtaining raw materials. \u8220\'20\'1CThe early days of the Russia-Ukraine conflict led to an increase in raw material prices due to \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in logistics routes and costs,\u8221\'20\'1D he said on April 26.\par \par \uc2 In anticipation of recent conditions, \uc2 Pupuk Kaltim\uc2 , Anggono continued, has increased its stock of raw materials and expanded the countries from which it imports fertilizer raw materials. \u8220\'20\'1CWe are also collaborating with \uc2 Pupuk Indonesia\uc2  to conduct joint tenders to secure the best raw material prices,\u8221\'20\'1D he added.\par \par \uc2 A worker inspects car tires production at a factory in Cikarang, Bekasi, West Java. TEMPO Doc./Seto Wardhana\par \par \uc2 According to Nailul Huda, an economist from the Center of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Law Studies, conflicts in the Middle East affect the fertilizer industry, which relies on imported raw materials. During the Russia-Ukraine war, he explained, prices of nitrogen-containing fertilizers soared due to the significant increase in the price of natural gas, its raw material. The recent Iran-Israel conflict, according to Huda, could lead to similar conditions.\par \par \uc2 Not only the rise in oil and gas prices, but another challenge faced by industry players is the weakening of the rupiah exchange rate. Industry players using imported raw materials will face increased production costs. For example, the tire manufacturing industry faces increased costs due to the continuous rise in the prices of imported raw materials. Azis Pane, Chairman of the Indonesian Tire Entrepreneurs Association, cited examples such as the skyrocketing costs of importing cup lump or latex coagulum and formic acid. \u8220\'20\'1CAbout 72 percent of tire raw materials are still imported,\u8221\'20\'1D he said on April 26.\par \par \uc2 The difficulty in importing raw materials has occurred since the implementation of the National Commodity Balance System, or Sinas NK, established by Presidential \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 32/2022. According to Azis, the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  stipulates that export and import permits must be based on commodity balances. The government then prepared an integrated digital system for issuing export and import permits through Sinas NK. However, Azis added, Sinas NK often encounters problems and hampers the import of raw materials. Additionally, imported raw materials are limited, not aligning with the needs of the industry.\par \par \uc2 The issuance of Trade Minister \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 36/2023, amended to Trade Minister \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 3/2024 on import provisions, has caused an outcry among textile and footwear industry players. Several raw materials that were previously freely imported now face prohibitions and/or restrictions (lartas) through the mechanism of import approvals, surveyor reports, and technical approvals. \u8220\'20\'1CImported raw materials for fabrics and footwear plastics are now subject to lartas," said Firman Bakrie, Executive Director of the Indonesian Footwear Association, on March 19.\par \par \uc2 It is not just the footwear industry, electronic producers also face similar challenges. After the issuance of import restrictions, the Industry Ministry issued Industry Minister \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 6/2024 on the procedure for issuing technical considerations for the import of electronic products. Initially, this \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  aimed to support the development of the domestic electronics industry. However, entrepreneurs have complained about the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  because it restricts the import of some products and components that cannot yet be produced in Indonesia. Additionally, the trade balance for electronic products remained in \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  until last year.\par \par \uc2 Economist Josua Pardede said that the scarcity of raw materials hampers the production process and decreases manufacturing industry performance. \u8220\'20\'1CWe believe import restrictions have impacted the availability of industrial raw materials, especially those that cannot yet be produced domestically,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. However, Josua considers the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  as providing room for the development of industries substituting imported materials while also protecting domestic industries that have long been pressed due to dumping practices.\par \par \uc2 Data from the Central Statistics Agency (BPS) indicates a decrease in the import figures for several types of raw materials in March. For example, imports of machinery and equipment or products under \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  code HS 84 decreased by 13.9 percent annually. Similarly, imports of vehicles and vehicle components or products under \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  code HS 87 decreased by 41.14 percent annually. However, Josua described the decline in imports as caused by a combination of several factors, not just the import \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \u8220\'20\'1COther factors were the decreasing industrial activity during Ramadan (Islamic fasting month), exchange rate changes, and the wait-and-see attitude of entrepreneurs amid turbulent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Last week, the BPS announced that Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s trade balance for March experienced a surplus of US$4.47 billion. The surplus value increased by 22.8 percent compared to the previous month\u8217\'20\'19s data. Compared to March 2023 data, the surplus value surged by 58.3 percent. The surplus occurred alongside a decrease in import figures, reaching 2.6 percent monthly and 12.76 percent annually. According to the BPS, the value of imports in March reached US$17.96 billion.\par \par \uc2 According to acting Chief of BPS, Amalia Adininggar Widyasanti, the cumulative trade surplus is shrinking amid global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown. Amid the tensions in the Middle East, she revealed that Indonesia experienced a trade \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  with that region. Throughout last year, the value of trade in goods between Indonesia and Middle Eastern countries reached US$19.20 billion. Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s exports to this region were US$9.06 billion, while imports were US$10.31 billion. \u8220\'20\'1CThe trade balance \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  reached US$1.07 billion,\u8221\'20\'1D she said.\par \par \uc2 The decline in import value indeed contributes to the creation of a trade surplus. However, for entrepreneurs, decreases due to regulations such as the implementation of import restrictions are not entirely beneficial. Chairman of the Korea Chamber of Commerce and Industry in Indonesia, Lee Kang-hyun, stated that only a few companies received import approvals. This situation, he said, is not only a problem for Korean companies but also affects all businesses in Indonesia. \u8220\'20\'1CWhen import permit applications are delayed, financial losses and supply chain issues are inevitable.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/04/29/859930/859930_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/04/29/859931/859931_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/04/29/859913/859913_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020240429ek4s0000d\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Interest Rate Hike Falls Short, Market Awaits Prabowo\u8217\'20\'19s Direction\b0\par\par\uc2 647 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 April 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 BANK Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) has been compelled to take a decisive step in combating the depreciation of the rupiah by raising \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Last week, BI\u8217\'20\'19s reference rate, the BI Rate, was elevated from 6 percent to 6.25 percent. This move is expected to inevitably dampen \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Such is the cost of stabilizing the rupiah.\par \par \uc2 The market, however, did not respond enthusiastically. A day before the rate hike, the exchange rate did slightly improve, touching Rp16,150 per United States dollar in the spot market. However, the rupiah reverted back to around Rp16,200 per US dollar on the following day. It seems this is the new equilibrium point for the rupiah after the BI Rate hike.\par \par \uc2 From the perspective of the authorities, this new equilibrium is still far from the ideal level. For example, the government set the benchmark for the rupiah exchange rate at Rp15,000 per US dollar in this year\u8217\'20\'19s state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . If the rupiah does not move back closer to that benchmark and the actual exchange rate differs significantly from this target, the government could face serious problems.\par \par \uc2 An immediate adverse effect could be the worsening of the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  credibility. Indonesia is dangerously riding the wave, as credible \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  management is a key anchor for investor confidence in Indonesia. This is one of the most important considerations for foreign investors before bringing their investment funds into Indonesia, especially into government bond instruments.\par \par \uc2 There are two important indicators that can reflect investor\u8217\'20\'19s confidence in Indonesia: the position of foreign funds invested in government bonds and the movement of government bonds yield. Unfortunately, both indicators have been deteriorating recently.\par \par \uc2 Gradually, foreign funds continue to trickle out of government bonds. Foreign investors have been in a net sell position for quite some time. They reallocate funds to safer havens. As of April 24, the total outflow of foreign funds from these instruments has reached Rp49 trillion. Investor confidence in Indonesia has been in retreat as the Federal Reserve \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  show no signs of imminent decrease.\par \par \uc2 The increase in yields on Indonesian government bonds also confirms this lack of confidence. For example, the yield on 10-year Indonesian government bonds, an important market benchmark, has risen rapidly. From around 6.65 percent in early April, it had reached 7.19 percent by last Thursday, April 24. The rise in yield reflects an increasing investment risk in Indonesia. As the risk increases, investors demand higher returns.\par \par \uc2 Unfortunately, the BI Rate hike seems powerless to improve market confidence. Something tells us that merely a rate hike is not sufficient. At least one question still hangs in the balance. The financial markets are not convinced that the Indonesian government will not pursue aggressive \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies leading to a ballooning \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . There is no strong political commitment yet to prevent a surge in government debt during this difficult period.\par \par \uc2 It is not from \uc2 Joko Widodo\uc2 , who is nearing the end of his term, that the market awaits an answer, but rather from \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2 . As the president-elect set to take office in October, Prabowo could restore investor confidence in the financial markets if he promptly clarifies how Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be directed during his tenure.\par \par \uc2 Without a clear indication from the incoming president, the market will continue to speculate about the increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Meanwhile, turmoil in the global markets continues to add negative pressure on the rupiah exchange rate. As usual, risk-taking investors will capitalize on this volatile atmosphere for speculation.\par \par \uc2 The interplay of these various factors will undoubtedly continue to buffet the rupiah. Currency stability is increasingly distant from reality. The rupiah remains in distress. Meanwhile, the risk of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown due to the BI Rate hike remains a burden we must bear.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/04/28/859884/859884_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020240429ek4s0000i\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Retno Marsudi\uc2 : There\u8217\'20\'19s no intention of establishing diplomatic relations with Israel\b0\par\par\uc2 2,297 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 April 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 THE conflicts in the Middle East are intensifying. Amid the ongoing Gaza war that shows no sign of letting up, a new conflict has broken out. On April 14, Iran launched 300 drones and missiles toward Israel in retaliation against Israel\u8217\'20\'19s airstrike on the Iranian consulate in Damascus, Syria, which killed two Iranian Revolutionary Guard generals.\par \par \uc2 Many countries, including Indonesia, are concerned about the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  repercussions from this latest conflict. Crude oil prices are predicted to soar if there is turmoil in the Strait of Hormuz, which is the world\u8217\'20\'19s most important oil shipping route. \u8220\'20\'1COil price surges will have a huge impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ,\u8221\'20\'1D said Foreign Affairs Minister \uc2 Retno Lestari Priansari Marsudi\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 To help prevent the conflict from escalating, Retno reached out to Iranian Foreign Minister \uc2 Hossein Amir-Abdollahian\uc2 , as well as the foreign ministers of Israel\u8217\'20\'19s allied countries. She urged all parties to exercise restraint and reminded them not to overlook the fate of Palestinians caught in the \uc2 Hamas\uc2 -Israel war.\par \par \uc2 Retno Marsudi\uc2  met with Tempo journalists, Raymundus Rikang and Yosea Arga Pramudita, for an interview at her office at the Foreign Affairs Ministry in Central Jakarta on Thursday, April 18. She explained the plan to establish diplomatic relations with Israel. \u8220\'20\'1CThe news was deliberately circulated by certain parties because Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s position is highly strategic,\u8221\'20\'1D said the diplomat that hails from Semarang, Central Java.\par \par \uc2 How is the latest condition in the Middle East following the recent Iran-Israel conflict?\par \par \uc2 The situation is very fluid. We have to look back at the series of events since April 1, when Israel attacked the Iranian consulate in Damascus, Syria. A diplomatic facility is a territory that every nation must respect. The tension between the two countries has been going on for a long time, but this is the first time they have had direct contact. Previously, they engaged in a proxy war.\par \par \uc2 Do you think the conflict will escalate?\par \par \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s possible. It is the point where we all need to work quickly to de-escalate the situation. Ideally, the intensity of the conflict should decrease, but it requires hard work and commitment from all parties.\par \par \uc2 What diplomacy did you adopt to resolve it?\par \par \uc2 I contacted Iranian Foreign Minister \uc2 Hossein Amir-Abdollahian\uc2  and the foreign ministers from several Middle East countries. I also got in touch with Hungarian and United States foreign ministers because they are close allies of Israel. We spoke with Israel\u8217\'20\'19s allies to persuade Israel to exercise restraint.\par \par \uc2 From your communication with Hossein, what was the reason for their attack?\par \par \uc2 After Israel\u8217\'20\'19s strike on their consulate in Damascus, Iran wrote to the United Nations Security Council (UNSC). However, there was no response. He explained that the attacks were deliberately carried out in a limited fashion, avoiding civil facilities, as they did not want casualties. That\u8217\'20\'19s why they targeted military facilities. The Iranian Foreign Minister said they had no intention of continuing the attack.\par \par \uc2 Why didn\u8217\'20\'19t the \uc2 UN Security Council\uc2  respond?\par \par \uc2 I also questioned why the \uc2 UNSC\uc2  did not discuss Iran\u8217\'20\'19s letter about the Damascus attack. But when Iran attacked Israel, the latter asked the \uc2 UNSC\uc2  to discuss the issue, and it obliged. The \uc2 UNSC\uc2 , which is tasked with maintaining peace, should carry out its duties fairly. There\u8217\'20\'19s the need for justice, as they have extraordinary responsibilities.\par \par \uc2 Isn\u8217\'20\'19t the impartiality of the \uc2 UNSC\uc2  long been doubted? One of the reasons is the presence of superpowers as permanent members.\par \par \uc2 These superpowers will continue to have their roles. If they want to be consistent, they should not apply double standards. They talk about human rights, but how about the fate of Palestine? They must have the same respect for humanity in Palestine. Why do they remain calm and relaxed when tens of thousands of Palestinians are being killed? That\u8217\'20\'19s not right.\par \par \uc2 You also communicated with the US, Israel\u8217\'20\'19s close ally. What did you discuss?\par \par \uc2 They said they would not support Israel if Israel would launch a retaliatory attack.\par \par \uc2 Will they maintain their commitment?\par \par \uc2 The US is committed not to support it, but will Israel listen even if the US refuses to help them? ? It also depends on Iran and its proxies. That\u8217\'20\'19s why there are a lot of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the situation in the Middle East.\par \par \uc2 Israel still responded by attacking Iran\u8217\'20\'19s defense facilities. What is your response?\par \par \uc2 I spoke with a number of foreign ministers after the incident, and none of them wanted to see escalations. There hasn\u8217\'20\'19t been any major escalation yet, but we have to be vigilant. On the other hand, the US has actually increased military aid to Israel. This doesn\u8217\'20\'19t foster peace and stability in the region.\par \par \uc2 Is the US not serious about preventing increased tensions in the Middle East?\par \par \uc2 We know they are trying hard, but will the Netanyahu government listen to them? America has tried to talk to Israel several times regarding the situation in Gaza, but we haven\u8217\'20\'19t seen any results. We also saw a shift in the US\u8217\'20\'19s stance in the latest \uc2 UNSC\uc2  resolution on Palestine. They abstained from Security Council Resolution No. 2728 on a ceasefire. This move made Israel unhappy.\par \par \uc2 Is the change in the US\u8217\'20\'19s stance related to their domestic political situation: \uc2 Joe Biden\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s bid for the second term and the American \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s divided attitudes toward Palestine?\par \par \uc2 That\u8217\'20\'19s their domestic affairs. I don\u8217\'20\'19t want to comment further on that.\par \par \uc2 Indonesian Foreign Affairs Minister Reno Marsudi delivers Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s statement at the \uc2 UN Security Council\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s in New York, January 23. ANTARA/Yashinta Difa\par \par \uc2 Is there a possibility that Iran\u8217\'20\'19s allies, like China, may also aggravate the situation?\par \par \uc2 I met with the Chinese Foreign Minister, Wang Yi, in Jakarta. We are confident that the People\u8217\'20\'19s Republic of China will use its influence to prevent escalation in the Middle East. Iran and China have rather close \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ties, and this aspect will be affected should a war break out. Indonesia and China are also on the same page regarding the Palestine issue, which is supporting a ceasefire and (Palestine\u8217\'20\'19s) full membership in the \uc2 UN\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Does Israel\u8217\'20\'19s retaliatory attack on Iran signify that diplomacy is not effective in preventing the conflict?\par \par \uc2 We do not see Israel\u8217\'20\'19s intention to respect international law from the beginning. Israel always emphasizes their security rights. The consistency of Israel\u8217\'20\'19s violations of international law reflects their lack of commitment to creating peace in the region.\par \par \uc2 What are the worst impacts of the Iran-Israel conflict that you anticipate?\par \par \uc2 There will definitely be casualties if an open war happens. There are no happy war stories. History teaches us that on the first day a war begins, we can never tell when it will end. Look at Gaza and Ukraine. We are also concerned about the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  impacts.\par \par \uc2 How serious is the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  impact of the Middle East conflict on Indonesia?\par \par \uc2 The Strait of Hormuz, which is in Iranian territory, is a vital trade route, especially for oil and gas. If the oil trade is disrupted, we must immediately look at the balance sheet. The assumption of oil price in the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is around US$80 per barrel. If the price of oil goes up to US$100 per barrel, the impact on our finances will be significant.\par \par \uc2 How is the government mitigating that risk?\par \par \uc2 The President has held a meeting with ministers in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  affairs and the Governor of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 . They had presented all the indicators and figures. The President advised that we must always be vigilant and continue to calculate (the situation). One of the favorable factors is that our macroeconomic foundation is still quite strong.\par \par \uc2 Has the government calculated the most profound impact on our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ?\par \par \uc2 The Finance Ministry already has a calculation if the oil price breaks US$120 per barrel. We see the most obvious impact is on global oil prices. Indonesia is doing what other countries are doing, where the head of government sits down with ministers to calculate. The global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation fluctuates. There was the Covid-19 pandemic, followed by the war in Ukraine. The Ukraine conflict is not finished yet, there is Gaza, then Iran-Israel. It\u8217\'20\'19s one after another.\par \par \uc2 What about the rescue efforts of Indonesian citizens in the Iran-Israel conflict areas?\par \par \uc2 Our standard operating procedure is in place. The Indonesian Embassy in Jordan monitors our citizens who are in Israel, and the status is on alert I. Meanwhile, the Embassy in Iran is on alert level II. The Director of Indonesian Citizen Protection has coordinated with our representatives in Egypt, Lebanon and Iraq. We have also issued a travel advisory and informed what to do in a critical situation.\par \par \uc2 Retno Lestari Priansari Marsudi\par \par \uc2 Place and Date of Birth:\par \par \uc2 Semarang, Central Java, November 27, 1962\par \par \uc2 Education:\par \par \uc2 * Bachelor of International Relations, Gadjah Mada University, Yogyakarta\par \par \uc2 * Master of European Union Law, De Haagse Hogeschool, Netherlands\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Offices:\par \par \uc2 * Minister of Foreign Affairs (2014-2024)\par \par \uc2 * Ambassador to the Kingdom of Netherlands (2012-2014)\par \par \uc2 * Director-General for America and Europe, Foreign Affairs Ministry (2008-2012)\par \par \uc2 * Ambassador to the Kingdom of Norway and Iceland (2005-2008)\par \par \uc2 Reported Wealth:\par \par \uc2 Rp32 billion (2022)\par \par \uc2 Are they already in the safe zones?\par \par \uc2 There are 376 Indonesians in Iran, mostly students. While in Israel, there are about 130 Indonesians who are on pilgrimage. Therefore, we issued a travel advisory with the hope that, if there are no urgent matters, please postpone the trip. The government cannot prohibit its citizens from traveling, but we are obliged to advise them.\par \par \uc2 To what extent the Iran-Israel conflict affects the situation in Gaza?\par \par \uc2 I told my colleagues, the foreign ministers, that we must not let the Iran and Israel issue distract us from the Palestinian cause and the situation in Gaza. The situation in Gaza has been going on for six months and has not been resolved. Casualties continue to fall. The delivery of humanitarian aid to Gaza is also hampered. We must keep our attention on Gaza.\par \par \uc2 Is it true that Israel\u8217\'20\'19s attacks on Iran are an attempt to divert the world\u8217\'20\'19s attention from the situation in Gaza?\par \par \uc2 I dare not answer hypothetically. But the emergence of a new problem should not ignore the root of the problem. If we want to see a stable Middle East, resolving the Palestinian issue must be done fairly. Regional security is collective security\u8212\'20\'14a condition that must be enjoyed by nations (in the region), including Palestine. Israel\u8217\'20\'19s security will not be guaranteed if the Palestinian issue is not resolved fairly.\par \par \uc2 How is the progress of Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s support for Palestinian independence?\par \par \uc2 Palestine\u8217\'20\'19s full membership in the \uc2 UN\uc2  is currently being discussed. Indonesia is at the forefront of supporting this effort. This membership issue is crucial. When Palestine officially becomes a full member of the \uc2 UN\uc2 , its position will be equal. So, if there is a negotiation forum, Palestine will be on the same level.\par \par \uc2 There is a rumor about the effort to establish Jakarta\u8217\'20\'19s relations with Tel Aviv in return for support for Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s membership in the \uc2 Organization for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation and Development\uc2  (\uc2 OECD\uc2 )?\par \par \uc2 The news was deliberately spread by certain parties. Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s position is very clear, there is no intention of establishing diplomatic relations with Israel. Moreover, the situation in Gaza is not conducive yet. Does it make sense that, in the midst of the current conditions in the Gaza Strip, we open relations with Israel? What will be the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s reaction?\par \par \uc2 But we have trade relations with Israel, even though we don\u8217\'20\'19t have diplomatic channels.\par \par \uc2 The amount is not significant. No one forbids \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations. Indonesia also does not have diplomatic relations with Taiwan, but we have trade relations.\par \par \uc2 What is President \uc2 Joko Widodo\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s stance on normalizing Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s relations with Israel?\par \par \uc2 President Jokowi still firmly supports Palestine. We get respect from the international community due to our principles in implementing foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . We are not easily pressured. Imagine if our foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was merely transactional, we would not be respected.\par \par \uc2 Is it possible that diplomatic relations will be established in the next government. Israeli media reported that \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  had communicated with Israeli officials.\par \par \uc2 I don't have the right to speak about the next government. But I believe and hope that the basic principles of our foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be continued.\par \par \uc2 (The Defense Minister\u8217\'20\'19s spokesperson, Dahnil Anzar Simanjuntak, said that information about contact between Prabowo and Israeli parties is foreign propaganda. According to Dahnil, Prabowo has no intention of normalizing Jakarta\u8217\'20\'19s relations with Tel Aviv. \u8220\'20\'1CIndonesia\u8217\'20\'19s stance supports Palestinian independence,\u8221\'20\'1D he said via a WhatsApp message on Wednesday, April 24.)\par \par \uc2 Jokowi\u8217\'20\'19s administration will end in October. What are your plans?\par \par \uc2 Retired. I have been serving the government for 10 years. I have served in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs since 1985, which means almost 40 years. There is a time to start and a time to stop.\par \par \uc2 There is criticism of Jokowi\u8217\'20\'19s diplomatic style, which seems ceremonial but lacks impact. One example is the visit to Ukraine amid the war. What is your response?\par \par \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s not like that. I emphasized that it\u8217\'20\'19s not a mere ceremonial activity. It may seem so on television. In the G20 meeting in Bali, for example, the President chaired meetings, led discussions, and adopted declarations. That\u8217\'20\'19s what appeared in \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But behind these, there were emergency meetings, negotiations, and lobbying. It\u8217\'20\'19s impossible to show the kitchen sink to the media. What the President has done is not just ceremonial activities.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/04/29/859946/859946_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/04/29/859947/859947_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020240429ek4s0000e\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
