\par\par \b \uc2 Inflation eases but rate cut deemed unlikely for now\b0\par\par\uc2 Deni Ghifari, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 464 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 May 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's consumer price index (CPI) growth has been steadily within acceptable boundaries for almost a year, yet \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  hiked its key interest rate twice during that time, and analysts believe the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  will remain cautious despite safe inflation readings.\par \par \uc2 Interim Statistics Indonesia (BPS) head Amalia Adininggar Widyasanti announced at a press briefing on Thursday that headline inflation, which measures the year-on-year (yoy) increase in consumer prices, declined marginally to 3 percent in April from 3.05 percent in the preceding month.\par \par \uc2 In monthly terms, however, CPI growth eased significantly, as consumer prices in April were only 0.25 percent higher than in March, marking a slowdown from a month-to-month (mtm) increase of 0.52 logged in March.\par \par \uc2 Amalia attributed that slowdown to reduced price pressure in staple food products like "red chili, rice and eggs".\par \par \uc2 Inflation has been well maintained within BI's target range for almost a year now, but the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  nonetheless decided to increase its benchmark interest rate twice in that period, most recently with a 25-basis-point (bps) increase on April 24, lifting the BI Rate to 6.25 percent.\par \par \uc2 BI's inflation target range for 2023 was 2 to 4 percent, which was ultimately attained at the year's close with 2.61 percent. The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  then set a more ambitious target of 2.5 plus/minus 1 percent for this year, and so far, CPI growth has stayed well clear of the upper limit.\par \par \uc2 After a prolonged period of high inflation in Indonesia and much of the world, domestic inflation finally came back down to BI's target range in May 2023 as CPI growth touched 4 percent yoy.\par \par \uc2 It has remained within the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's target range ever since, hence BI's two most recent interest rate hikes were interpreted as preemptive moves aimed at anticipating any risks from external \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , such as conflict in the Middle East.\par \par \uc2 While the first surprise hike took place in October 2023 amid mutual attacks between Israel and \uc2 Hamas\uc2 , the one last month came against the backdrop of escalating tension between Iran and Israel.\par \par \uc2 In addition to geopolitical risks, BI's April hike also came after United States macroeconomic data had prompted the USFederal Reserve to signal to financial markets that it would keep its key \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  "higher for longer".\par \par \uc2 The Fed kept the federal funds rate unchanged on Wednesday, and Fed chairman \uc2 Jerome Powell\uc2  said in Washington, DC, that inflation was too high and progress in bringing it down was \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but he did not entertain growing speculation that the Fed might need to hike the rate.\par \par \uc2 Continued on page 11\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240502ek530000a\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 OJK\u8217\'20\'19s Stricter Rules to Prevent Banks from Collapsing\b0\par\par\uc2 2,152 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 May 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 LIKE a marathon, \uc2 Bank Oke Indonesia\uc2  (OK! Bank) has been focusing on strengthening its capital for the past two years. In 2022, the bank, which falls under the capital category of KBMI I (bank classification based on core capital), had just managed to raise its core equity from Rp1 trillion to Rp3 trillion (around US$63.5 million to US$190.7 million), as required by the \uc2 Financial Services Authority (OJK)\uc2 . Last year, OK! Bank and 65 other KBMI I class banks were obliged to have core equity of Rp6 trillion (US$389.2 million).\par \par \uc2 Now, OK! Bank and other banks must prepare additional capital after the OJK issued \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 5/2024 on the Determination of Supervision Status and Handling of General Banking Issues on March 25. In this \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the OJK instructed banks to prepare capital surcharges to anticipate losses amid unfavorable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions.\par \par \uc2 According to Efdinal Alamsyah, Director of Compliance at OK! Bank, this obligation begins with the requirement to submit a recovery plan to anticipate the risk of worsening \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions that could lead to bank failures. \u8220\'20\'1CThe OJK wants to anticipate so that there are no bank closures like during the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crises in previous years,\u8221\'20\'1D he told Tempo on April 30.\par \par \uc2 Not only medium to large-sized banks, or banks with the systemic category, are required by the OJK to fulfill this obligation, but small banks and banks with branches located overseas (KCBLN) are also required to submit a recovery plan. The term systemic bank refers to a bank that can cause the failure of part or all of the financial services sector because the company has significant assets and networks that affect the financial system.\par \par \uc2 The recovery plan must also contain options to address capital problems. These options include increasing the bank\u8217\'20\'19s capital, which becomes the obligation of the shareholders, or converting certain liabilities into capital. According to the OJK \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , banks other than KCBLN that have been operating before December 31, 2023, are required to fulfill the obligation of owning deposits and other instruments with capital characteristics.\par \par \uc2 This obligation applies gradually. For KBMI I banks, this requirement must be met no later than December 31, 2027. If they fail to do so, they will be subject to administrative sanctions. According to Efdinal, meeting these requirements is not easy. \u8220\'20\'1CIf shareholders cannot meet these requirements, the bank must find other investors, which is certainly not an easy task,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. Therefore, Efdinal asked the OJK to consider providing incentives or other compensation for banks that meet these requirements. \u8220\'20\'1CFor example, \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives, \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  recognition, or regulatory relief.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Piter Abdullah Redjalam, Executive Director of the Segara Research Institute, said the latest OJK \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is a consequence that the banking industry must face. \u8220\'20\'1CWhen conditions are vulnerable, all banks can instantly become systemic,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. For small banks that do not have abundant liquidity, the situation will become more difficult because they have to compete for funds, including through interest rate wars. \u8220\'20\'1CBanks with fewer customers have to survive, so they end up offering high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 ,\u8221\'20\'1D said Piter.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 THE OJK \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 5/2024 was issued as the banking industry is facing challenging conditions. Turmoil in the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially after tensions escalated in the Middle East, pushed up inflation figures, prompting central banks worldwide to adjust their benchmark \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Additionally, the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  on interest rate hikes by the \uc2 United States Federal Reserve\uc2  caused capital outflows from emerging economies like Indonesia. This has caused the exchange rate to plummet, forcing the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to intervene. Last week, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  raised its benchmark 7-Day Reverse Repo Rate (7DRRR) by 25 basis points to 6.25 percent.\par \par \uc2 For players in the banking industry, this is an alarm signaling a dire situation. Before conditions worsen further, they must prepare anticipatory measures. Dian Ediana Rae, Executive Head of Banking Supervision at the OJK, said that \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 5/2024 was issued to strengthen supervision of the banking industry and enhance coordination among agencies. \u8220\'20\'1CThis \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  was drafted taking into account the current situation,\u8221\'20\'1D he told Tempo on May 1.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Governor \uc2 Perry Warjiyo\uc2  and his deputies present the results of the Board of Governors Meeting at the \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Building, Jakarta, February 21. TEMPO/Tony Hartawan\par \par \uc2 According to Dian, this \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is a continuation of Law No. 4/2023 on the Development and Strengthening of the Financial Sector. However, he denied that the obligation to formulate recovery plans and additional capital was designed to increase the burden on banks, especially small banks with limited capabilities. \u8220\'20\'1CIn principle, this scheme will make banks more prepared to face problems,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. The capital requirements are adjusted to the characteristics of each bank.\par \par \uc2 Dian said that by having recovery plans, banks are expected to be able to anticipate various situations, including global geopolitical conditions that could disrupt the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \u8220\'20\'1CAs well as their own business activities,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. The action plan consists of recovery options that the bank will take in response to financial pressures and to maintain business continuity.\par \par \uc2 In addition to the recovery plan, the OJK \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  also governs the coordination of systemic bank designation and capital surcharge. Banks that are designated as systemic banks based on OJK\u8217\'20\'19s assessment are required to establish a capital surcharge in anticipation of operational failure and losses. In determining a systemic bank, Dian said the OJK uses a number of indicators, such as the bank\u8217\'20\'19s size, the complexity of its business activities, and its connections with the financial system. \u8220\'20\'1CThe OJK then calculates the bank\u8217\'20\'19s systemic score and sets the threshold.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Upon closer examination, this \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  also includes the term \u8220\'20\'1Cfollow-up supervision\u8221\'20\'1D for banks under normal supervision but facing difficulties that jeopardize their business continuity. This status is given to banks showing deteriorating business conditions but not yet meeting the criteria for problematic banks. It serves as an indicator of declining capital, asset quality, liquidity, and profitability, or unsound banking practices. This clause allows the OJK to intervene in banks with these criteria at an early stage.\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, the OJK is preparing a rule for the establishment of an intermediary bank. OJK \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 5/2024 defines an intermediary bank as a commercial bank that can only be established and owned by the Deposit Insurance Corporation (LPS) as a tool of resolution by accepting the transfer of some or all assets of troubled banks. Intermediary banks can only be established under certain conditions, including when there is a threat of crisis or disturbance to the financial system.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, this \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is undeniably a consequence of the current conditions experienced by the banking sector as the manager of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  funds. The Chief Executive Officer (CEO) of \uc2 Bank of India Indonesia\uc2 , RM \uc2 Raharjo Satrio Unggul\uc2 , said the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  have led to tighter liquidity. \u8220\'20\'1COf course, KBMI I and II banks are affected. We are experiencing the same thing, although liquidity ratios still show that conditions are safe,\u8221\'20\'1D he said on May 2.\par \par \uc2 CEO of \uc2 Bank of India Indonesia\uc2  (BOII), RM \uc2 Raharjo Satrio Unggul\uc2 . boiindonesia.co.id\par \par \uc2 According to the February 2024 edition of the Indonesian Banking Statistics, the loan-to-deposit ratio (LDR) of commercial bank deposits stood at 84.05 percent, a 79.80 percent year-on-year increase from the same period last year. The higher the LDR, the more illiquid the bank. In other words, the bank may have difficulties in paying its short-term commitments. Conversely, the lower the LDR, the more liquid the bank.\par \par \uc2 Raharjo stated that there are various short-term and medium-term efforts to shift customer funds to other banks offering higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This must be done by banks in the low capital class. \u8220\'20\'1CIn the medium term, we are trying to develop services and products similar to those offered by KBMI III and IV banks to increase customer loyalty,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Banking observer and payment system practitioner Arianto Muditomo said that in an era of high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , banks need to be creative in sourcing low-cost funds through trading transaction features and retail payment transactions, and to offer investment products that can generate fee-based income. However, such efforts are difficult for small banks with limited capital. In the midst of difficult conditions, Arianto said, banks need to be wise in collecting high-cost funds.\par \par \uc2 Under such conditions, banks with small equities are forced to implement efficiency measures. However, these measures will not be sufficient if these banks are required to increase their capital. Another path that KBMI I and II banks can take is consolidation through a merger or acquisition scheme.\par \par \uc2 David Sumual, Chief Economist at \uc2 Bank Central Asia\uc2 , said mergers and acquisitions of banks with minimal capital are also driven by the increasingly stringent regulations imposed by the OJK. \u8220\'20\'1CNatural selection will eventually take place. The need for mergers and acquisitions will come from the banks themselves. Those that are weak will not survive,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Two national banking entities currently exploring a merger are \uc2 Bank MNC Internasional\uc2  (MNC Bank) and \uc2 Bank Nationalnobu\uc2  (Nobu Bank). The consolidation of financial entities belonging to the MNC Group and the \uc2 Lippo Group\uc2 , respectively, is taking place because both have failed to meet the core equity capital requirements set by the OJK. The OJK is targeting the two banks to merge in June next year.\par \par \uc2 Josua Pardede, Chief Economist of \uc2 Bank Permata\uc2 , stated that banks have three options to meet capital requirements. These include shareholders injecting fresh funds, merging with other banks, or being acquired by another bank or financial institution. \u8220\'20\'1CMergers tend to be more complex because usually, the shareholders of the two companies have different views and business models,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 According to Josua, acquisition is a more feasible option as small banks can improve their performance to attract the interest of new investors. \u8220\'20\'1CThe process is faster. They just have to wait for the right price.\u8221\'20\'1D Meanwhile, the option of raising capital is rarely chosen because of the limited capacity of shareholders, especially amid grim \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions.\par \par \uc2 There is hardly any way for small banks to survive without increasing capital other than through consolidation. In addition, the potential for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  shocks is becoming more real, and competition between banks is more intense. Josua predicts that the era of high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue for quite some time, at least until the middle of next year. \u8220\'20\'1CThe chances for \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  to cut \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are getting slimmer given the Fed\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and efforts to maintain rupiah stability.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of high-\b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  inevitably continues amidst the strength of the United States \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , coupled with the US inflation rate still being far from the 2 percent target. This is reinforced by the Fed\u8217\'20\'19s statement that they will not rush to lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  while observing the development of future \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  data. Meanwhile, the escalating geopolitical tensions in the Middle East following the conflict between Iran and Israel raise concerns that the war will escalate and burden the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , particularly in terms of the rise in prices of key energy and mineral commodities, as well as the increase in logistic costs due to disruptions in major trade routes resulting from the conflict.\par \par \uc2 Rising geopolitical tensions and global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  have significantly bolstered the US dollar\u8217\'20\'19s status as a safe-haven asset sought by many market players. The domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , on the other hand, is also affected by the external situation. One of the indicators is the inflation data, which stood at 3 percent year-on-year as of April, higher than the January position of 2.57 percent.\par \par \uc2 Dian Ediana Rae ensured that the national banking sector is resilient enough to absorb both global and domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  risks, especially the trend of rising \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the greenback\u8217\'20\'19s appreciation. According to the OJK\u8217\'20\'19s stress test results, the current conditions have not had a significant impact on banks' capital. The reason, Dian said, is that the net foreign exchange position of banks in Indonesia is still far below the threshold. Additionally, the foreign exchange assets of banks are greater than the foreign exchange liabilities they are required to pay.\par \par \uc2 OJK\u8217\'20\'19s Executive Head of Banking Supervision, Dian Ediana Rae, in Jakarta, September 2020. TEMPO/Tony Hartawan\par \par \uc2 Dian went on to say that banks\u8217\'20\'19 capital cushion is quite strong as evidenced by the high capital adequacy ratio. He believes this can withstand turmoil due to fluctuations in the rupiah exchange rate or high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \u8220\'20\'1CHowever, we urge banks to always monitor the impact of global and domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  turmoils.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par {\field{\*\fld