\par\par \b \uc2 Insight: Indonesia, the Global South, and the need for  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  development\b0\par\par\uc2 1,225 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 May 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Philips Vermonte,\par \par \uc2 The term "Global South" is difficult to define, as it encompasses a diverse range of countries, each with its own unique foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  objectives as well as domestic and external challenges.\par \par \uc2 One common feature across Global South nations is, however, the presence of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  disparities and underdevelopment, which have had a profound influence on such states' foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  decision-making processes. Therefore, I would argue, that "development" has been, and must be understood as, the main foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  objective across the Global South.\par \par \uc2 One persistent objective in the foreign policies of the Global South is that these nations seek to secure their rights for development. This is evidenced by the increasing emphasis on South-South cooperation and the formation of regional blocs and organizations aimed at promoting collective development interests and amplifying the voices of the Global South in global decision-making processes that particularly relate to development issues.\par \par \uc2 The foreign relations and domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development of the Global South are often affected by its regional environment. Many nations in the Global South have historically formed regional organizations to address common challenges and advance mutual interests.\par \par \uc2 ASEAN is a prime example. Born out of regional conflicts, ASEAN has thus far been able to create a region that is politically stable, maintains relative strategic autonomy from external powers and has allowed member states to grow economically. The Southeast Asian region has been an example of a region with consistent robust \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth over the past three decades or so.\par \par \uc2 In navigating the new world order, the Global South naturally brings a unique perspective that prioritizes inclusive development, shared prosperity and multilateral cooperation (Jordaan, 2001). Through their leadership roles and active participation in international forums, countries like Indonesia, Brazil, South Africa and Turkey have consistently pushed for inclusive development and shared prosperity.\par \par \uc2 The Global South's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth has created new opportunities for cooperation and development. The \uc2 International Monetary Fund\uc2  says that from 1999 to 2019, the Global South's GDP grew by about 4.8 percent a year. This is faster than in many developed countries. This growth has been driven by trade, investments in infrastructure and technology.\par \par \uc2 Demographic trends in the Global South have also been transformative, with a growing population and a growing middle class. According to the \uc2 Brookings Institution\uc2  (Kharas, 2010), by 2030, more than 80 percent of the world's middle class will live in Asia and Africa. This will change how the world consumes and influences the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 As \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, demographic trends and an expanding middle class continue to shape the Global South, its influence in international affairs may also be strengthened, to pave the way for a more diversified, inclusive and dynamic multipolar world order with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development at the center of the collective interest. As the Global South's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues to expand, its partnerships with emerging powers (mostly of the Global South as well) have become increasingly crucial.\par \par \uc2 One of the key examples of the partnership is so-called South-South cooperation and development assistance. Countries in the Global South have increasingly engaged in collaborative efforts with emerging powers within their own region, such as China, India, Brazil, Indonesia and South Africa.\par \par \uc2 Lastly, it has to be noted that countries in the Global South have shown resilience in times of crisis, indicating the increasing strength and capacity of their institutions. According to the \uc2 IMF\uc2 's forecast, as the world gradually emerges from the disruptions caused by the pandemic, several regions within the Global South, particularly the Middle East and Central Asia, sub-Saharan Africa and Latin America, are about to experience robust \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth between 2023 and 2028. Southeast Asia has also experienced consistently robust \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth even during the years of the pandemic.\par \par \uc2 But big problems remain. The Global South must deal with the effects of the pandemic, such as supply chain disruptions, new pandemics, climate change and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and strategic \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  due to geopolitical and geo-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  tension.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia and some emerging powers in the Global South are in a very unique position to navigate such strategic \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . They, first and foremost, should provide a narrative that emphasizes the importance of maintaining strategic autonomy against major powers, either from the North or South. Such a narrative needs to consistently highlight that the main strategic interest of the Global South, i.e. \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development and the right to development, should not be defined by great power politics, including the rivalry between the United States and China.\par \par \uc2 The great powers should treat the Global South nations according to their own (\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) rights, not because of the former's need to balance, or exclude, their strategic opponents. For Indonesia, there is a practical platform that can be used.\par \par \uc2 The year 2025 marks the 70th anniversary of the Asia-Africa Conference. The commemoration next year, rather than just a ceremonial extravaganza with the usual spectacular show for the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , can be transformed into a strategic meeting of leaders of Asian and African countries to discuss in particular their \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development and cooperation. The sense of solidarity and the fact that the Global South has one shared goal for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prosperity shall be recalled.\par \par \uc2 It may sound a bit clich?, but such solidarity was actually on display during the pandemic, when many countries in the Global South worked hard to ensure that their populations had access to vaccines.\par \par \uc2 Second, the Global South certainly cannot escape from the US-China geopolitical and geo-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  rivalries. One way to navigate the rivalry is by strengthening the regional organizations. ASEAN has been showing a remarkable ability, with Indonesia being the largest nation in it, in fending off the consequences of great power competition, in which the competitors often tried to use the region as their proxy theater.\par \par \uc2 That was the success story of ASEAN from the 1970s to 1990s, during the US-Soviet Union Cold War. What is needed by ASEAN to maintain the region's strategic autonomy is once again leadership with a clear longer-term \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and development vision for the region. The experience of ASEAN in creatively engaging the major powers from outside the region might be shared with other regional organizations in the Global South.\par \par \uc2 We are living in an era with great strategic \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The US remains a dominant power militarily and is still the superpower, but it seems to have forgotten how to act like one, given its domestic political problems. China is poised to be the next superpower. However, a superpower is measured by its ability to provide solutions to international crises, and we have yet to see how China could provide one in the many crises facing the world today.\par \par \uc2 Both the US and China at times become part of international problems rather than solutions, as in the cases of Ukraine, Gaza and the South China Sea. So, it is fair to say that we in the Global South are on our own.\par \par \uc2 The narrative for the Global South's shared vision for our own \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  needs and strong regional organizations in the Global South must be consistently advocated.\par \par \uc2 ______________________\par \par \uc2 A senior fellow at the Jakarta-based Centre for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) and the dean of the School of Social Sciences at Indonesia International Islamic University (UIII) in Depok, West Java\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240505ek5600009\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
